n      curl -X POST https://xo.example.com/api/session.signOut \\\n        -H \"Authorization: Bearer YOUR_TOKEN\" \\\n        -d '{\"id\": \"SESSION_ID\"}'\n\n    - Method 4: Network interface shutdown (last resort)\n      ip link set eth0 down\n      ip link set eth0 up  # Restore after test\n\n(3) Create runbook for security incident response\n    - Step-by-step procedures for each disconnect method\n    - Decision tree for choosing appropriate method\n    - Rollback procedures to restore service\n    - Post-incident analysis requirements\n\n(4) Train authorized personnel on disconnect procedures\n    - Conduct tabletop exercises\n    - Perform actual disconnect tests (during maintenance window)\n    - Document training completion\n    - Update procedures based on lessons learned\n\n(5) Integrate disconnect procedures into incident response plan\n    - Define triggering events (e.g., active breach, unauthorized access)\n    - Establish notification requirements (ISSM/ISSO)\n    - Document in security plan Section [X.X]\n    - Review and update annually\n\nRe-run scan after documentation complete.\n\nNote: DoD requires capability for immediate disconnect during security incidents per NIST SP 800-53r5 AC-12(2). Procedures must be documented, tested, and readily available to authorized personnel.\n        \n\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-206419","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206419","title":"SRG-APP-000340","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206419","severity":"medium","group_title":"Non-privileged accounts on the hosting system must only access web server security-relevant information and functions through a distinct administrative account.","rule_id_src":"SV-206419r961353_rule","rule_id":"SV-206419r961353","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000340-WSR-000029","rule_title":"Non-privileged accounts on the hosting system must only access web server security-relevant information and functions through a distinct administrative account.","fix_text":"Set up accounts and roles that can be used to perform web server security-relevant tasks and remove or modify non-privileged account access to security-relevant tasks.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and configuration to determine if accounts used for administrative duties of the web server are separated from non-privileged accounts.\n\nIf non-privileged accounts can access web server security-relevant information, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"By separating web server security functions from non-privileged users, roles can be developed that can then be used to administer the web server. Forcing users to change from a non-privileged account to a privileged account when operating on the web server or on security-relevant information forces users to only operate as a web server administrator when necessary. Operating in this manner allows for better logging of changes and better forensic information and limits accidental changes to the web server.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70201","V-55947"],"ccis":["CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"265478cb-a081-4e46-9fe2-1e0d109b4343","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nMANUAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED: Verify non-privileged users cannot access XO security functions.\n\nVerification Steps:\n1. Review XO service account (should be root or dedicated service account)\n2. Verify file permissions on /opt/xo/ and /etc/xo-server/ (no world-write access)\n3. Check sudo rules - only authorized admins can sudo to XO service account\n4. Verify organizational access control policy documents separation of duties\n5. Test: Login as non-privileged user and attempt to access XO config files\n\nRemediation (if needed):\n- Remove excessive permissions: chmod o-rwx /opt/xo /etc/xo-server\n- Restrict sudo access: Remove unauthorized users from sudo/wheel/adm groups\n- Document administrative accounts in System Security Plan\n- Implement LDAP/AD role-based access control\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 923DBF7518A51B64E408F977798E8EAB363D6DFB\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-206419: Non-Privileged Account Access Restrictions\n================================================================================\n\nDoD Requirement: Non-privileged accounts must only access web server\nsecurity-relevant information and functions through a distinct\nadministrative account (separation of duties principle).\n\nCheck 1: System Account Enumeration\n--------------------------------------------------\n   Found 29 system accounts in /etc/passwd\n\n   Sample accounts:\n   root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash\n   daemon:x:1:1:daemon:/usr/sbin:/usr/sbin/nologin\n   bin:x:2:2:bin:/bin:/usr/sbin/nologin\n   sys:x:3:3:sys:/dev:/usr/sbin/nologin\n   sync:x:4:65534:sync:/bin:/bin/sync\n   ... (24 more)\n\nCheck 2: XO Service Account Identification\n--------------------------------------------------\n   XO process owner: root\n   Account details: root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash\n\nCheck 3: Privileged User Detection\n--------------------------------------------------\n   Privileged users (root, sudo, wheel, adm groups):\n   - root\n   - netdata\n\nCheck 4: Non-Privileged User Enumeration (UID >= 1000)\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [NO NON-PRIVILEGED USERS] Only system/service accounts detected\n\nCheck 5: XO Directory File Permissions\n--------------------------------------------------\n   Checking: /etc/xo-server\n   [PASS] No world-writable files detected\n   Checking: /var/lib/xo-server\n   [PASS] No world-writable files detected\n\nCheck 6: Sudo Configuration Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------\n   Active sudo rules detected (non-comment lines):\n   /etc/sudoers:\n     Defaults\tenv_reset\n     Defaults\tmail_badpass\n     Defaults\tsecure_path=\"/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin\"\n     \n     \n     \n     \n     root\tALL=(ALL:ALL) ALL\n     \n     xoa-support ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD:ALL\n   /etc/sudoers.d/:\n     /etc/sudoers.d/README:#\n     /etc/sudoers.d/README:# The default /etc/sudoers file created on installation of the\n     /etc/sudoers.d/README:# sudo  package now includes the directive:\n     /etc/sudoers.d/README:# \n     /etc/sudoers.d/README:# \t@includedir /etc/sudoers.d\n     /etc/sudoers.d/README:# \n     /etc/sudoers.d/README:# This will cause sudo to read and parse any files in the /etc/sudoers.d \n     /etc/sudoers.d/README:# directory that do not end in '~' or contain a '.' character.\n     /etc/sudoers.d/README:# \n     /etc/sudoers.d/README:# Note that there must be at least one file in the sudoers.d directory (this\n\n================================================================================\nV-206419 ASSESSMENT\n================================================================================\n\nMANUAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED:\n\nThis check requires ISSO/ISSM verification of organizational policy compliance:\n\n1. Verify non-privileged users cannot directly access XO security functions\n2. Confirm administrative access uses distinct admin accounts (not regular user accounts)\n3. Validate separation of duties principle is enforced\n4. Review sudo rules to ensure non-privileged users cannot escalate to web server admin\n5. Verify XO user roles enforce least privilege (viewers cannot modify configs)\n6. Confirm file permissions prevent unauthorized access to XO configuration files\n\nEvidence to collect:\n- XO user role assignments (Admin vs Operator vs Viewer)\n- Organizational account management policy\n- Sudo access logs showing admin account usage\n- File permission audit showing proper ownership (root or root)\n\nDoD requires: Non-privileged accounts must use administrative accounts for\nweb server security functions (separation of duties)."},{"group_id_src":"V-206421","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206421","title":"SRG-APP-000357","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206421","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must use a logging mechanism that is configured to allocate log record storage capacity large enough to accommodate the logging requirements of the web server.","rule_id_src":"SV-206421r961392_rule","rule_id":"SV-206421r961392","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000357-WSR-000150","rule_title":"The web server must use a logging mechanism that is configured to allocate log record storage capacity large enough to accommodate the logging requirements of the web server.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to use a logging mechanism that is configured to allocate log record storage capacity in accordance with NIST SP 800-92 log record storage requirements.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployment configuration to determine if the web server is using a logging mechanism to store log records. If a logging mechanism is in use, validate that the mechanism is configured to use record storage capacity in accordance with specifications within NIST SP 800-92 for log record storage requirements.\n\nIf the web server is not using a logging mechanism, or if the mechanism has not been configured to allocate log record storage capacity in accordance with NIST SP 800-92, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"In order to make certain that the logging mechanism used by the web server has sufficient storage capacity in which to write the logs, the logging mechanism needs to be able to allocate log record storage capacity. \n\nThe task of allocating log record storage capacity is usually performed during initial installation of the logging mechanism. The system administrator will usually coordinate the allocation of physical drive space with the web server administrator along with the physical location of the partition and disk. Refer to NIST SP 800-92 for specific requirements on log rotation and storage dependent on the impact of the web server.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70213","V-55959"],"ccis":["CCI-001849"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"d7f8bdff-e997-4086-a983-162b9ac527f3","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check identified log storage location but cannot verify organizational storage capacity requirements are defined and met.\n\nRequired Manual Verification:\n(1) Calculate log generation rate (baseline measurement)\n    - Monitor log growth for 7-14 days\n      du -sh /var/log/xo-server  # Initial size\n      (wait 24 hours)\n      du -sh /var/log/xo-server  # Check growth\n    - Example calculation:\n      Daily growth: 50 MB/day\n      Weekly growth: 350 MB/week\n      Monthly growth: 1.5 GB/month\n\n(2) Define organizational log retention period\n    - DoD minimum: 1 year for privileged access logs\n    - Consider compliance requirements (FISMA, PCI-DSS, etc.)\n    - Balance retention needs with storage costs\n    - Document retention period in security plan\n\n(3) Calculate required storage capacity\n    - Formula: Daily growth  Retention days  Safety margin (1.5x)\n    - Example:\n      50 MB/day  365 days  1.5 = 27.4 GB required\n\n(4) Verify sufficient disk space allocated\n    - Check current partition size and available space:\n      df -h /var/log\n    - If insufficient, expand partition or add dedicated log partition\n      lvcreate -L 50G -n lv_logs vg_system\n      mkfs.ext4 /dev/vg_system/lv_logs\n      mount /dev/vg_system/lv_logs /var/log/xo-server\n\n(5) Configure log rotation to prevent disk exhaustion\n    - For XOA (systemd journal):\n      # In /etc/systemd/journald.conf\n      SystemMaxUse=10G\n      SystemKeepFree=2G\n      MaxRetentionSec=31536000  # 1 year\n      systemctl restart systemd-journald\n\n    - For XOCE (logrotate):\n      # Create /etc/logrotate.d/xo-server\n      /var/log/xo-server/*.log {\n        daily\n        rotate 365\n        compress\n        delaycompress\n        notifempty\n        create 0640 root root\n        sharedscripts\n        postrotate\n          systemctl reload xo-server > /dev/null\n        endscript\n      }\n\n(6) Implement monitoring for log storage capacity\n    - Configure SIEM alerts for disk space:\n      Alert at 80% capacity (warning)\n      Alert at 90% capacity (critical)\n    - Automate reports on log growth trends\n    - Define procedures for expanding storage\n\n(7) Document log storage capacity in security plan\n    - Log generation rate baseline\n    - Retention period and justification\n    - Total storage allocated\n    - Monitoring and alerting procedures\n\nRe-run scan after capacity planning documentation complete.\n\nNote: DoD requires 1-year minimum retention for privileged access logs per NIST SP 800-53r5 AU-11 (Audit Record Retention). Plan for sufficient storage to meet this requirement without log loss.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 9128859C23F0DC2ECDDC8A197FF80DC43135A02C\n~~~~~\n=== V-206421: Log Storage Capacity Allocation Check ===\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: Log Directory Disk Space Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] Log directory: /var/log\n   Filesystem details:\n   /dev/xvda2       19G  6.2G   12G  35% /\n   [INFO] Current usage: 35%\n   [PASS] Adequate disk space available (<80% used)\n   [INFO] Current log directory size: 1.9G\n\nCheck 2: Systemd Journal Storage Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] journald configuration: /etc/systemd/journald.conf\n   [INFO] SystemMaxUse not explicitly set (using defaults: 10% of filesystem)\n   [INFO] RuntimeMaxUse not explicitly set (using defaults: 10% of /run)\n   [INFO] Current journal disk usage:\n   Archived and active journals take up 1.8G in the file system.\n\nCheck 3: Logrotate Configuration (Capacity Management)\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] Logrotate config: /etc/logrotate.conf\n\n\nCheck 4: Log Filesystem Separation\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] Logs share partition with root: /dev/xvda2      19503340 6453892  12033384  35% /\n   [RECOMMENDATION] Consider separate partition for /var/log\n\nCheck 5: Disk Space Monitoring and Alerting\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] No dedicated monitoring agents detected\n   [INFO] No disk space alert cron jobs detected\n\nCheck 6: Organizational Capacity Planning Documentation\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] No organizational capacity planning documentation found\n   [MANUAL_VERIFICATION_REQUIRED] System Administrator should provide:\n     1. Log retention policy (days/weeks of logs to retain)\n     2. Expected log growth rate (MB/GB per day)\n     3. Allocated storage capacity for logs\n     4. Monitoring/alerting thresholds\n     5. Log archival procedures when capacity reached\n\n=== Assessment ===\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[RESULT] OPEN - Manual verification required\n[FINDING] Unable to verify log storage capacity allocation\n[MANUAL_VERIFICATION_REQUIRED]\n  1. Request organizational log retention policy from System Administrator\n  2. Verify allocated disk space for log storage (df -h /var/log)\n  3. Confirm logrotate configuration exists (size, rotate count, compress)\n  4. Validate systemd journal limits (SystemMaxUse, RuntimeMaxUse)\n  5. Check disk space monitoring/alerting (Nagios, Zabbix, cron scripts)\n  6. Document log growth rate and archival procedures\n\n[STIG_REQUIREMENT] SRG-APP-000357-WSR-000150\n  The web server must use a logging mechanism that is configured to allocate\n  log record storage capacity large enough to accommodate the logging requirements.\n\n[REMEDIATION] Configure log rotation and capacity planning:\n  1. Create /etc/logrotate.d/xo-server with size/rotate limits\n  2. Set systemd journal limits in /etc/systemd/journald.conf\n  3. Consider separate partition for /var/log (prevents root FS exhaustion)\n  4. Implement disk space monitoring (Nagios, Zabbix, or cron alerts)\n  5. Document organizational log retention policy"},{"group_id_src":"V-206422","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206422","title":"SRG-APP-000358","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206422","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must not impede the ability to write specified log record content to an audit log server.","rule_id_src":"SV-206422r961395_rule","rule_id":"SV-206422r961395","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000358-WSR-000063","rule_title":"The web server must not impede the ability to write specified log record content to an audit log server.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to directly write or transfer the logs to a remote audit log server.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployment configuration to determine if the web server can write log data to, or if log data can be transferred to, a separate audit server.\n\nRequest a user access the hosted application and generate logable events and verify the data is written to a separate audit server.\n\nIf logs cannot be directly written or transferred on request or on a periodic schedule to an audit log server, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Writing events to a centralized management audit system offers many benefits to the enterprise over having dispersed logs. Centralized management of audit records and logs provides for efficiency in maintenance and management of records, enterprise analysis of events, and backup and archiving of event records enterprise-wide. The web server and related components are required to be capable of writing logs to centralized audit log servers.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70223","V-55969"],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"1031248b-00ab-4dc1-9d56-6bc97a85de57","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check could not verify that logs are offloaded to a different system or media.\n\nRequired Manual Verification:\n(1) Deploy or identify centralized log server (SIEM/syslog server)\n    - Recommended solutions: Splunk, ELK Stack, rsyslog server, Graylog\n    - Ensure log server is on different physical system\n    - Document log server hostname/IP in security plan\n\n(2) Configure rsyslog on XO server to forward logs\n    - Install rsyslog (usually installed by default on Debian):\n      apt-get install rsyslog rsyslog-gnutls\n\n    - Configure log forwarding in /etc/rsyslog.d/50-xo-forward.conf:\n      # Forward XO logs to remote syslog server\n      $ModLoad imfile\n      $InputFileName /var/log/xo-server/xo-server.log\n      $InputFileTag xo-server:\n      $InputFileStateFile stat-xo-server\n      $InputFileSeverity info\n      $InputRunFileMonitor\n\n      # Forward to remote syslog server over TLS (preferred)\n      $DefaultNetstreamDriver gtls\n      $ActionSendStreamDriverMode 1\n      $ActionSendStreamDriverAuthMode x509/name\n      $ActionSendStreamDriverPermittedPeer syslog-server.example.com\n      *.* @@syslog-server.example.com:6514\n\n    - Restart rsyslog:\n      systemctl restart rsyslog\n\n(3) Configure XO Server to log to syslog\n    - In /opt/xo/xo-server/config.toml (XOCE) or /etc/xo-server/config.toml (XOA):\n      [logs]\n      syslog = \"local\"  # Send to local syslog (then rsyslog forwards)\n\n    - Restart XO:\n      systemctl restart xo-server\n\n(4) Verify log forwarding operational\n    - Generate test log entry:\n      logger -t xo-server \"Test log forwarding to remote syslog server\"\n\n    - Check log appears on remote server:\n      ssh syslog-server \"tail -f /var/log/xo-server.log\"\n\n    - Verify no errors in rsyslog:\n      journalctl -u rsyslog -n 50\n\n(5) Configure backup to separate storage media (defense in depth)\n    - Mount network storage (NFS/CIFS):\n      mkdir -p /mnt/log-backup\n      mount -t nfs syslog-server.example.com:/backup/xo-logs /mnt/log-backup\n      echo \"syslog-server.example.com:/backup/xo-logs /mnt/log-backup nfs defaults 0 0\" >> /etc/fstab\n\n    - Configure logrotate to copy rotated logs to backup:\n      # In /etc/logrotate.d/xo-server\n      /var/log/xo-server/*.log {\n        daily\n        rotate 365\n        compress\n        delaycompress\n        notifempty\n        create 0640 root root\n        sharedscripts\n        postrotate\n          cp /var/log/xo-server/*.log.1.gz /mnt/log-backup/ 2>/dev/null || true\n          systemctl reload xo-server > /dev/null\n        endscript\n      }\n\n(6) Document log offload configuration in security plan\n    - Centralized log server information\n    - Forwarding protocol and encryption (TLS preferred)\n    - Backup storage location\n    - Verification procedures and test results\n\nRe-run scan after log offload configuration complete.\n\nWARNING: Storing logs only on the system being logged creates single point of failure. If system is compromised, attacker can delete logs to hide evidence. Log offload to separate system is REQUIRED per DoD STIG and NIST SP 800-53r5 AU-4(1).\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 3D98FBA5E333977D9828E1C16DF18953307B9129\n~~~~~\n=== V-206422: Audit Log Server Write Capability Check ===\n================================================================================\n\nSTIG Requirement: Web server must not impede ability to write log records\n                  to an audit log server (centralized logging required)\n\nCheck 1: rsyslog Remote Logging Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] rsyslog not installed (may use alternative syslog daemon)\n\nCheck 2: syslog-ng Remote Logging Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] syslog-ng not installed\n\nCheck 3: XO Audit Plugin Remote Forwarding\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] XO audit plugin directories:\n      find: /opt/xo/packages: No such file or directory\n      find: /usr/share/xo-server: No such file or directory\n   [FOUND] XO config file: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n   [INFO] No audit plugin remote forwarding detected\n   [DETAIL] XO audit plugin may store locally only\n\nCheck 4: Systemd Journal Remote Forwarding\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] systemd-journal-upload not active: inactive\n\nCheck 5: Network Connectivity to Audit Log Server\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] No remote logging configured - connectivity check skipped\n\nCheck 6: Organizational Audit Log Server Documentation\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [MANUAL_VERIFICATION_REQUIRED] System Administrator should provide:\n     1. Centralized audit log server address (SIEM, Splunk, syslog server)\n     2. Log forwarding protocol and port (TCP/UDP 514, TLS 6514)\n     3. Network connectivity confirmation (firewall rules, ACLs)\n     4. Organizational logging infrastructure diagram\n     5. Evidence of log aggregation (SIEM console, Splunk search)\n\n   [DoD_COMMON_SOLUTIONS]\n     - ACAS (Assured Compliance Assessment Solution)\n     - Splunk Enterprise Security\n     - IBM QRadar\n     - ArcSight ESM\n     - Central syslog server (rsyslog aggregator)\n\n=== Assessment ===\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[RESULT] OPEN - No remote logging detected\n[FINDING] Unable to verify log forwarding to audit log server\n\n[MANUAL_VERIFICATION_REQUIRED]\n  1. Request organizational audit log server configuration from System Administrator\n  2. Verify centralized logging solution (SIEM, Splunk, syslog aggregator)\n  3. Confirm XO logs are forwarded to audit log server\n  4. Check network connectivity to audit log server (firewall rules)\n  5. Validate log retention on centralized server\n\n[STIG_REQUIREMENT] SRG-APP-000358-WSR-000163\n  The web server must not impede the ability to write specified log record\n  content to an audit log server.\n\n[REMEDIATION] Configure remote syslog forwarding:\n  1. Obtain organizational audit log server address from ISSM/ISSO\n  2. Configure rsyslog to forward all logs to remote server:\n     - Edit /etc/rsyslog.d/50-remote.conf\n     - Add: *.* @@audit-server.example.mil:514  (TCP)\n     - Or:  *.* @audit-server.example.mil:514   (UDP)\n  3. For TLS encryption (recommended):\n     - Add: *.* @@audit-server.example.mil:6514  (TLS)\n     - Configure CA certificates for TLS validation\n  4. Restart rsyslog: systemctl restart rsyslog\n  5. Verify forwarding: logger 'Test message' && check audit server\n\n  Alternative: Configure systemd journal forwarding:\n  1. Edit /etc/systemd/journal-upload.conf\n  2. Set: URL=https://audit-server.example.mil:19532/upload\n  3. Enable: systemctl enable --now systemd-journal-upload\n\n  XO Audit Plugin (if available):\n  1. Install XO audit plugin: xo-cli plugin.install xo-server-audit\n  2. Configure remote forwarding in /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n  3. Restart XO server: systemctl restart xo-server"},{"group_id_src":"V-206423","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206423","title":"SRG-APP-000358","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206423","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must be configurable to integrate with an organizations security infrastructure.","rule_id_src":"SV-206423r961395_rule","rule_id":"SV-206423r961395","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000358-WSR-000163","rule_title":"The web server must be configurable to integrate with an organizations security infrastructure.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to send logged events to the organization's security infrastructure tool that offers review and alert capabilities.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to determine whether the web server is logging security-relevant events.\n\nDetermine whether there is a security tool in place that allows review and alert capabilities and whether the web server is sending events to this system.\n\nIf the web server is not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A web server will typically utilize logging mechanisms for maintaining a historical log of activity that occurs within a hosted application. This information can then be used for diagnostic purposes, forensics purposes, or other purposes relevant to ensuring the availability and integrity of the hosted application.\n\nWhile it is important to log events identified as being critical and relevant to security, it is equally important to notify the appropriate personnel in a timely manner so they are able to respond to events as they occur. \n\nManual review of the web server logs may not occur in a timely manner, and each event logged is open to interpretation by a reviewer. By integrating the web server into an overall or organization-wide log review, a larger picture of events can be viewed, and analysis can be done in a timely and reliable manner.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70225","V-55971"],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"88fdfb5c-1ede-4ac1-b2f0-8cf73b174fb3","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check detected logging infrastructure components but cannot verify integration with authorized DoD SIEM platform.\n\nRequired Manual Verification:\n(1) Confirm XO integrated with authorized DoD SIEM platform\n    - Acceptable platforms: Splunk, ArcSight, QRadar, Elastic Stack, or DoD-approved alternative\n    - Verify organizational security architecture diagram includes XO\n    - Request copy of SIEM integration documentation\n\n(2) Verify remote access events forwarded to SIEM in real-time\n    - Events must include: login/logout, authentication failures, session creation/termination\n    - Test event delivery: Perform test login on XO, verify event appears in SIEM within 5 minutes\n    - Confirm event correlation: SIEM must correlate XO events with other system events\n\n(3) Confirm SIEM configured for remote access monitoring and alerting\n    - Alerts for suspicious login patterns (e.g., logins from unusual locations)\n    - Alerts for brute force attempts (multiple failed authentications)\n    - Alerts for privilege escalation (role changes, permission modifications)\n    - Verify alert recipients include ISSO/SA/security team\n\n(4) Verify SIEM data retention meets organizational requirements\n    - DoD minimum: 1 year for audit logs (NIST SP 800-53r5 AU-11)\n    - Confirm backup strategy for SIEM data\n    - Test log retrieval process\n\n(5) Test SIEM integration by generating test events\n    - Perform test authentication failure on XO\n    - Verify event visible in SIEM console within acceptable timeframe (<5 min)\n    - Confirm event data includes: timestamp, username, source IP, action, result\n\n(6) Document SIEM integration architecture\n    - Include: log sources, forwarding mechanisms, SIEM platform, retention policy\n    - Update security plan Section [X.X]\n    - Provide architecture diagram showing XO > syslog/agent > SIEM flow\n\nRemediation for missing SIEM integration:\n\nOption 1: Configure rsyslog remote forwarding\n  1. Edit /etc/rsyslog.conf or /etc/rsyslog.d/50-xo-siem.conf:\n     *.* @@siem.example.mil:514  # TCP with reliable delivery\n     # OR\n     *.* @siem.example.mil:514   # UDP for lower latency\n\n  2. Restart rsyslog:\n     systemctl restart rsyslog\n\n  3. Verify logs forwarding:\n     logger \"Test XO SIEM integration\"\n     # Check SIEM for test message\n\nOption 2: Configure Elastic Beats (Filebeat)\n  1. Install Filebeat:\n     apt install filebeat  # Debian\n\n  2. Configure /etc/filebeat/filebeat.yml:\n     filebeat.inputs:\n     - type: log\n       paths:\n         - /var/log/xo-server/*.log\n         - /var/log/syslog\n\n     output.elasticsearch:\n       hosts: [\"elastic.example.mil:9200\"]\n       protocol: \"https\"\n       username: \"xo-forwarder\"\n       password: \"PASSWORD\"\n\n  3. Enable and start:\n     systemctl enable filebeat\n     systemctl start filebeat\n\nOption 3: Configure Splunk Universal Forwarder\n  1. Download and install from Splunk\n  2. Configure inputs.conf:\n     [monitor:///var/log/xo-server]\n     disabled = false\n     index = security\n     sourcetype = xo-server\n\n  3. Configure outputs.conf:\n     [tcpout]\n     defaultGroup = splunk-indexers\n\n     [tcpout:splunk-indexers]\n     server = splunk.example.mil:9997\n\n  4. Restart forwarder:\n     /opt/splunkforwarder/bin/splunk restart\n\nRe-run scan after SIEM integration verified.\n\nNote: This requirement ensures XO logs are available to external monitoring systems for centralized security event correlation and remote access control. Local logging alone is insufficient; integration with organizational SIEM infrastructure is mandatory for DoD compliance per NIST SP 800-53r5 AU-6(1).\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: A1AC8F5FAC621BD70473C159340C1E7C614988D0\n~~~~~\nVulnerability ID: V-206423\nRule ID: SV-206423r508029_rule\nCAT II / Medium - Security Infrastructure Integration\n---[Organizational Policy Check]---\n\nRequirement: Web server must generate information for external applications\n             (SIEM, monitoring systems) to monitor and control remote access.\n\nCheck 1: Remote Syslog Configuration\n  [INFO] No remote syslog configuration detected\n         Logs may be local-only (not forwarded to SIEM)\n\nCheck 2: SIEM Platform Integration\n  [INFO] No standard SIEM platform detected\n         Organization may use custom monitoring solution\n\nCheck 3: XO Audit Plugin Forwarding\n  [INFO] XO audit plugin not detected (optional component)\n\nCheck 4: Systemd Journal Remote Upload\n  [INFO] systemd-journal-upload not enabled\n         Systemd journal logs remain local only\n\nCheck 5: Organizational SIEM Integration Documentation\n  [INFO] No standard documentation directories detected\n         Organization should document SIEM integration procedures\n\nAssessment:\n  Finding: Open\n  Reason: Cannot automatically verify integration with authorized SIEM platform\n\nDetection Summary:\n  - Remote syslog configured: NO\n  - SIEM platform detected: NO\n\nRequired Manual Verification:\n  1. Confirm XO integrated with authorized DoD SIEM platform\n     Acceptable: Splunk, ArcSight, QRadar, Elastic Stack, or DoD-approved alternative\n  2. Verify remote access events forwarded to SIEM in real-time\n     Events include: login/logout, authentication failures, session creation/termination\n  3. Confirm SIEM configured for remote access monitoring and alerting\n     Alerts for: suspicious login patterns, brute force attempts, privilege escalation\n  4. Verify SIEM data retention meets organizational requirements\n     DoD minimum: 1 year for audit logs\n  5. Test SIEM integration by generating test events\n     Verify events visible in SIEM console within acceptable timeframe\n  6. Document SIEM integration architecture\n     Include: log sources, forwarding mechanisms, SIEM platform, retention policy\n\nNote: This requirement ensures XO logs are available to external monitoring\nsystems for centralized security event correlation and remote access control.\nLocal logging alone is insufficient; integration with organizational SIEM\ninfrastructure is mandatory for DoD compliance.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-206424","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206424","title":"SRG-APP-000359","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206424","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must use a logging mechanism that is configured to provide a warning to the ISSO and SA when allocated record storage volume reaches 75% of maximum log record storage capacity.","rule_id_src":"SV-206424r961398_rule","rule_id":"SV-206424r961398","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000359-WSR-000065","rule_title":"The web server must use a logging mechanism that is configured to provide a warning to the ISSO and SA when allocated record storage volume reaches 75% of maximum log record storage capacity.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to provide a warning to the ISSO and SA when allocated log record storage volume reaches 75% of maximum record storage capacity.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployment configuration settings to determine if the web server log system provides a warning to the ISSO and SA when allocated record storage volume reaches 75% of maximum record storage capacity.\n\nIf designated alerts are not sent or the web server is not configured to use a dedicated log tool that meets this requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a system is at risk of failing to process logs as required. Log processing failures include: software/hardware errors, failures in the log capturing mechanisms, and log storage capacity being reached or exceeded. \n\nIf log capacity were to be exceeded, then events subsequently occurring would not be recorded. Organizations shall define a maximum allowable percentage of storage capacity serving as an alarming threshold (e.g., web server has exceeded 75% of log storage capacity allocated), at which time the web server or the logging mechanism the web server utilizes will provide a warning to the ISSO and SA at a minimum. \n\nThis requirement can be met by configuring the web server to utilize a dedicated log tool that meets this requirement.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70229","V-55975"],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"043561e1-7f60-4ac8-a3f3-1fa10c931b1d","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check identified disk monitoring capabilities but cannot verify 75% threshold alerts to ISSO/SA are configured.\n\nRequired Manual Verification:\n(1) Verify monitoring system alert thresholds\n    - Nagios: Check /etc/nagios/nrpe.cfg for check_disk with -w 25% (warning at 25% free = 75% used)\n    - Zabbix: Verify filesystem triggers configured for 75% usage threshold\n    - Prometheus: Check AlertManager rules for node_filesystem_avail alerts at 25% free\n    - Request screenshot of alert configuration from monitoring system\n\n(2) Confirm ISSO/SA contact information configured in monitoring system\n    - Nagios: Verify contacts.cfg includes ISSO/SA email addresses\n    - Zabbix: Check Users > Administration for ISSO/SA notification settings\n    - Prometheus: Verify AlertManager receivers include ISSO/SA\n    - Test notification delivery to ISSO/SA\n\n(3) Test disk capacity alert delivery (simulate 75% usage)\n    - Create test file to increase disk usage to 76%:\n      fallocate -l [SIZE]G /var/log/test_capacity.tmp\n    - Verify alert generated within check interval\n    - Verify ISSO/SA receive alert notification\n    - Remove test file:\n      rm /var/log/test_capacity.tmp\n    - Document test results\n\n(4) Document alert escalation procedures\n    - Define actions when 75% threshold reached\n    - Specify timeline for log rotation/archival/deletion\n    - Define critical threshold (e.g., 90%) requiring immediate action\n    - Update incident response procedures\n\nRemediation for missing 75% threshold monitoring:\n\nOption 1: Configure Nagios NRPE with 75% threshold\n  1. Install NRPE:\n     apt install nagios-nrpe-server nagios-plugins  # Debian\n\n  2. Edit /etc/nagios/nrpe.cfg:\n     command[check_disk]=/usr/lib/nagios/plugins/check_disk -w 25% -c 10% -p / -p /var/log\n     # -w 25% = Warning at 25% free (75% used)\n     # -c 10% = Critical at 10% free (90% used)\n\n  3. Restart NRPE:\n     systemctl restart nagios-nrpe-server\n\n  4. Configure Nagios server to check this host (on Nagios server)\n\n  5. Configure Nagios contacts.cfg with ISSO/SA email:\n     define contact {\n         contact_name    isso\n         email           isso@example.mil\n     }\n\nOption 2: Configure Zabbix Agent with 75% threshold\n  1. Install Zabbix agent:\n     apt install zabbix-agent2  # Debian\n\n  2. Edit /etc/zabbix/zabbix_agent2.conf:\n     Server=zabbix.example.mil\n     ServerActive=zabbix.example.mil\n     Hostname=xo1.example.mil\n\n  3. Enable and start:\n     systemctl enable zabbix-agent2\n     systemctl start zabbix-agent2\n\n  4. On Zabbix web interface:\n     - Add host\n     - Link template \"Linux by Zabbix agent\"\n     - Configure trigger for vfs.fs.size with 75% threshold\n     - Add ISSO/SA to Users > Administration\n     - Configure notification actions\n\nOption 3: Configure Prometheus Node Exporter with 75% threshold\n  1. Install Node Exporter:\n     apt install prometheus-node-exporter  # Debian\n\n  2. Enable and start:\n     systemctl enable prometheus-node-exporter\n     systemctl start prometheus-node-exporter\n\n  3. Configure Prometheus scrape (on Prometheus server)\n\n  4. Create AlertManager rule:\n     - alert: DiskSpaceWarning75Percent\n       expr: (node_filesystem_avail_bytes / node_filesystem_size_bytes) < 0.25\n       for: 5m\n       labels:\n         severity: warning\n       annotations:\n         summary: \"Disk space at 75% on {{ $labels.instance }}\"\n\n  5. Configure AlertManager receivers with ISSO/SA email/webhook\n\nOption 4: Configure custom script with cron\n  1. Create /usr/local/bin/disk-capacity-alert.sh:\n     #!/bin/bash\n     THRESHOLD=75\n     USAGE=$(df -h /var/log | tail -1 | awk '{print $5}' | sed 's/%//')\n     if [ $USAGE -ge $THRESHOLD ]; then\n       echo \"Disk usage at ${USAGE}% on $(hostname)\" | \\\n       mail -s \"ALERT: Disk Capacity 75% Threshold\" isso@example.mil,sa@example.mil\n     fi\n\n  2. Make executable:\n     chmod +x /usr/local/bin/disk-capacity-alert.sh\n\n  3. Add to crontab (check every 15 minutes):\n     */15 * * * * /usr/local/bin/disk-capacity-alert.sh\n\n  4. Configure mail relay for alert delivery\n\nRe-run scan after 75% threshold monitoring configured and tested.\n\nNote: DoD requires ISSO/SA notification when storage capacity reaches 75% of maximum per NIST SP 800-53r5 AU-5(1). This provides sufficient lead time to prevent audit log loss due to disk space exhaustion.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 3E8F7EBD8C9E26AA7283F98F232C54C7F323466A\n~~~~~\n=== V-206424: Storage Capacity Monitoring and Alerting (75% Threshold) ===\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: Current Disk Space Usage Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [CHECKING] Directory: /var/log\n   Filesystem: /dev/xvda2       19G  6.2G   12G  35% /\n   [INFO] Current usage: 35%\n   [PASS] Usage below 75% threshold\n\n   [CHECKING] Directory: /var/lib/xo-server\n   Filesystem: /dev/xvda2       19G  6.2G   12G  35% /\n   [INFO] Current usage: 35%\n   [PASS] Usage below 75% threshold\n\nCheck 2: Logrotate Size Limits (Proactive Capacity Control)\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] Logrotate config: /etc/logrotate.conf\n\n   [INFO] No explicit size-based logrotate configuration found\n   [RECOMMENDATION] Configure size limits to prevent unexpected disk growth\n\nCheck 3: Disk Capacity Monitoring Tools\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] No dedicated monitoring agents detected\n\nCheck 4: 75% Threshold Alert Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] No custom disk alert scripts found\n   [INFO] No disk alert cron jobs detected\n\nCheck 5: ISSO/SA Notification Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] No mail utilities detected\n   [INFO] No organizational alert recipient documentation found\n\nCheck 6: Systemd Journal Storage Limits (Prevents Unbounded Growth)\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] journald configuration: /etc/systemd/journald.conf\n   [INFO] SystemMaxUse not set (defaults: 10% of filesystem)\n   [INFO] Archived and active journals take up 1.8G in the file system.\n\n=== Assessment ===\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[RESULT] OPEN - Manual verification required\n[FINDING] Unable to verify disk capacity monitoring and alerting\n[MANUAL_VERIFICATION_REQUIRED]\n  1. Request System Administrator to demonstrate disk monitoring configuration\n  2. Verify 75% threshold alerts are configured for all log partitions\n  3. Confirm ISSO/SA notification recipients are documented\n  4. Validate alert delivery mechanism (email, SNMP trap, webhook)\n  5. Review organizational incident response procedures for capacity alerts\n\n[STIG_REQUIREMENT] SRG-APP-000360-WSR-000151\n  The web server must generate information to be used by external applications\n  or entities to monitor and control remote access. DoD requires ISSO/SA\n  notification when storage capacity reaches 75% of maximum.\n\n[REMEDIATION] Configure disk capacity monitoring and alerting:\n  1. Install monitoring agent:\n     apt install nagios-nrpe-server  # Debian/Ubuntu\n     apt install zabbix-agent2       # Alternative\n\n  2. Configure NRPE disk check with 75% threshold:\n     command[check_disk]=/usr/lib/nagios/plugins/check_disk -w 25% -c 10% -p /\n     (25% free = 75% used threshold for warning)\n\n  3. Configure alert recipients (ISSO/SA email addresses):\n     - Nagios: /etc/nagios/contacts.cfg\n     - Zabbix: Web interface > Administration > Users\n     - Prometheus: AlertManager configuration\n\n  4. Document organizational procedures:\n     - Create /etc/xo-server/alert-recipients.txt with ISSO/SA contacts\n     - Include escalation procedures for capacity alerts"},{"group_id_src":"V-206425","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206425","title":"SRG-APP-000374","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206425","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must generate log records that can be mapped to Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) or Greenwich Mean Time (GMT).","rule_id_src":"SV-206425r961443_rule","rule_id":"SV-206425r961443","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000374-WSR-000172","rule_title":"The web server must generate log records that can be mapped to Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) or Greenwich Mean Time (GMT).","fix_text":"Configure the web server to store log data time stamps in a format that is mapped to UTC or GMT time.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and configuration to determine the time stamp format for log data.\n\nIf the time stamp is not mapped to UTC or GMT time, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If time stamps are not consistently applied and there is no common time reference, it is difficult to perform forensic analysis across multiple devices and log records.\n\nTime stamps generated by the web server include date and time. Time is commonly expressed in Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), a modern continuation of Greenwich Mean Time (GMT), or local time with an offset from UTC.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70233","V-55979"],"ccis":["CCI-001890"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"17bb5d87-9844-478d-9d51-8949cb30ca5d","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 97C17A53C1657E38A2DBADAE6BA33E2BCE59B50F\n~~~~~\nCHECK 1: Winston Logger Timezone Configuration\n   [INFO] No explicit timezone configuration found (using system timezone)\n\nCHECK 2: System Timezone (timedatectl)\n   [FOUND]                 Time zone: US/Eastern (EST, -0500)\n\nCHECK 3: Node.js TZ Environment Variable\n   [FOUND] TZ environment variable in Node.js process:\n      root     2960558  0.0  0.1   6940  3204 ?        S    06:24   0:00 /usr/bin/bash -c ps auxww | grep node | grep -E \"TZ=|--timezone\" 2>&1\n\nCHECK 4: Sample Log Timestamp Format\n   [SAMPLE] Recent timestamps from /var/log/syslog:\n      AttributeWeight     : 16\n      \n      \n\nCHECK 5: /etc/timezone File\n   [FOUND] /etc/timezone: US/Eastern\n\n====================================================================\nDETERMINATION:\n   [FAIL] Local time detected - DoD requirement NOT MET\n\nNON-COMPLIANCE SUMMARY:\n   - System timezone:                 Time zone: US/Eastern (EST, -0500)\n   - Log timestamps use local time offsets (not UTC/GMT)\n   - Forensic correlation: IMPAIRED (requires timezone conversion)\n\nDoD Requirement: Web server logs MUST use UTC or GMT to establish event time\n                 for forensic analysis and correlation across systems.\n\nREMEDIATION STEPS:\n1. Set system timezone to UTC:\n   timedatectl set-timezone UTC\n\n2. Restart XO Server to apply changes:\n   systemctl restart xo-server\n\n3. Verify timestamps in logs:\n   journalctl -u xo-server --since '5 minutes ago'\n   tail -f /var/log/xo-server/xo-server.log\n\n4. Confirm ISO 8601 format with Z suffix:\n   Expected: 2026-02-03T12:00:00.000Z\n   NOT: 2026-02-03T07:00:00-05:00 (EST offset)\n====================================================================\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-206426","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206426","title":"SRG-APP-000375","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206426","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must record time stamps for log records to a minimum granularity of one second.","rule_id_src":"SV-206426r961446_rule","rule_id":"SV-206426r961446","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000375-WSR-000171","rule_title":"The web server must record time stamps for log records to a minimum granularity of one second.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to record log events with a time stamp to a granularity of one second.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and configuration to determine if log records are time stamped to a minimum granularity of one second.\n\nHave a user generate a logable event and review the log data to determine if the web server is configured correctly.\n\nIf the log data does not contain a time stamp to a minimum granularity of one second, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without sufficient granularity of time stamps, it is not possible to adequately determine the chronological order of records. \n\nTime stamps generated by the web server include date and time and must be to a granularity of one second.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70231","V-55977"],"ccis":["CCI-001889"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"80074983-c665-47f1-a626-45ec08a97300","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: B89B5A12F270AFF378BBC4DA06C0E416597F024A\n~~~~~\nCHECK 1: Winston Logger Timestamp Format Configuration\n   [FOUND] /etc/xo-server/config.toml timestamp configuration:\n      # File containing the certificate (PEM format).\n      # File containing the private key (PEM format).\n\nCHECK 2: Sample Log Timestamp Precision\n   [SAMPLE] Recent timestamps from /var/log/syslog:\n      AttributeWeight     : 16\n      \n      \n\nCHECK 3: Systemd Journal Timestamp Precision\n   [SAMPLE] Systemd journal timestamps (short-precise format):\n      Feb 08 06:20:07.943627 xoa xo-server[1076588]: 2026-02-08T11:20:07.942Z xo:xo-server ERROR unhandled error event {\n      Feb 08 06:20:07.943627 xoa xo-server[1076588]:   error: Error: connect ETIMEDOUT 10.0.10.25:1515\n      Feb 08 06:20:07.943627 xoa xo-server[1076588]:       at TCPConnectWrap.afterConnect [as oncomplete] (node:net:1611:16)\n\nCHECK 4: Node.js Date.now() Default Format\n   [INFO] Node.js Date.now() returns milliseconds since Unix epoch (exceeds requirement)\n   - Format: 1738588496789 (milliseconds)\n   - Conversion: new Date(1738588496789).toISOString() = 2026-02-03T12:34:56.789Z\n\nCHECK 5: XO Audit Plugin Timestamp Precision\n   [INFO] No XO REST API token available (skipping audit plugin check)\n\n====================================================================\nDETERMINATION:\n   [PASS] Timestamp granularity meets or exceeds 1-second requirement\n\nCOMPLIANCE SUMMARY:\n   - Precision: Milliseconds (1/1000 second) - EXCEEDS REQUIREMENT\n   - Format: ISO 8601 with milliseconds (YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SS.sssZ)\n   - DoD Requirement: >= 1 second granularity - MET\n\nDoD Requirement: Timestamps must be to a granularity of one second minimum.\n\nGranularity Hierarchy (all acceptable if >= 1 second):\n   - Milliseconds (1/1000 sec) - BEST (Winston default)\n   - Seconds (1 sec) - MEETS REQUIREMENT\n   - Minutes (60 sec) - FAILS REQUIREMENT\n\n====================================================================\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-206427","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206427","title":"SRG-APP-000380","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206427","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server application, libraries, and configuration files must only be accessible to privileged users.","rule_id_src":"SV-206427r961461_rule","rule_id":"SV-206427r961461","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000380-WSR-000072","rule_title":"The web server application, libraries, and configuration files must only be accessible to privileged users.","fix_text":"Define roles and responsibilities to be used when managing the web server.\n\nConfigure the hosting system to utilize specific roles that restrict access related to web server system and configuration changes.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and configuration to determine if the web server provides unique account roles specifically for the purposes of segmenting the responsibilities for managing the web server.\n\nLog into the hosting server using a web server role with limited permissions (e.g., Auditor, Developer, etc.) and verify the account is not able to perform configuration changes that are not related to that role.\n\nIf roles are not defined with limited permissions and restrictions, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A web server can be modified through parameter modification, patch installation, upgrades to the web server or modules, and security parameter changes. With each of these changes, there is the potential for an adverse effect such as a DoS, web server instability, or hosted application instability.\n\nTo limit changes to the web server and limit exposure to any adverse effects from the changes, files such as the web server application files, libraries, and configuration files must have permissions and ownership set properly to only allow privileged users access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70235","V-55981"],"ccis":["CCI-001813"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"335e36ff-4b58-4431-81e0-20b8bb6bc2d6","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check detected application file permission issues that allow unauthorized users to access or modify XO application files, libraries, or configuration files.\n\nIdentified Issues (see Finding Details for specifics):\n- Directory permissions too permissive or world-writable\n- Application files have weak permissions allowing group/world access\n- Configuration files readable by non-privileged users\n- World-writable files detected (CRITICAL security vulnerability)\n- File ownership not restricted to authorized accounts\n\nRequired Remediation Steps:\n\n(1) Fix directory permissions:\n    chmod 755 /opt/xo/xo-server\n    chmod 755 /opt/xo/xo-web\n    chmod 755 /etc/xo-server\n    chmod 755 /var/lib/xo-server\n\n(2) Fix application file permissions:\n    find /opt/xo -type f -exec chmod 644 {} \\;\n    find /opt/xo -type f -name \"*.sh\" -exec chmod 755 {} \\;\n\n(3) Secure configuration files:\n    chmod 640 /opt/xo/xo-server/config.toml\n    chmod 640 /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n    chmod 600 /opt/xo/xo-server/.xo-cli\n\n(4) Remove world-write permissions (if detected):\n    find /opt/xo -type f -perm -002 -exec chmod o-w {} \\;\n    find /opt/xo -type d -perm -002 -exec chmod o-w {} \\;\n\n(5) Fix file ownership:\n    chown -R root:root /opt/xo\n    chown -R root:root /etc/xo-server\n    # OR for service account deployment:\n    chown -R xo-server:xo-server /opt/xo\n\n(6) Verify no unauthorized user access:\n    # Review /etc/group for unauthorized users in xo-related groups\n    # Review sudo configuration for XO-related commands\n\n(7) Document privileged user access procedures:\n    - Maintain list of authorized administrators\n    - Implement change management for application file modifications\n    - Configure file integrity monitoring (e.g., AIDE, Tripwire)\n\nVerification Commands:\n  ls -la /opt/xo/xo-server\n  find /opt/xo -type f -perm -002  # Should return nothing\n  stat -c '%a %U:%G' /opt/xo/xo-server/config.toml\n\nRestart XO service after permission changes (if configuration files modified):\n  systemctl restart xo-server\n\nRe-run scan to verify compliance after remediation.\n\nDoD Requirement: Application files must be protected from unauthorized modification to prevent malicious code injection, privilege escalation, and service disruption per NIST SP 800-53r5 CM-5 (Access Restrictions for Change).\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 205B032454E23DDDEBD5D671B627C9C5B58F8465\n~~~~~\nCheck 1: XO Application Directory Discovery\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] XO directory: /etc/xo-server\n   [FOUND] XO directory: /var/lib/xo-server\n\nCheck 2: Directory Permissions (DoD Requirement: 755 or more restrictive)\n--------------------------------------------------\n   Directory: /etc/xo-server\n   drw-r--r-- 2 root root 4096 Jul  1  2025 /etc/xo-server\n   Octal permissions: 644\n   [PASS] Directory permissions are acceptable (755 or more restrictive)\n\n   Directory: /var/lib/xo-server\n   drwxr-xr-x 3 root root 4096 Jul  1  2025 /var/lib/xo-server\n   Octal permissions: 755\n   [PASS] Directory permissions are acceptable (755 or more restrictive)\n\nCheck 3: File Permissions (DoD Requirement: privileged-only access)\n--------------------------------------------------\n   Sampling files in /etc/xo-server...\n   [FAIL] config.syslog.toml (644) - World has write access\n   [FAIL] config.toml (644) - World has write access\n\n\nCheck 4: World-Writable Files (CRITICAL VULNERABILITY)\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [PASS] No world-writable application files found\n\nCheck 5: File Ownership (DoD Requirement: root or authorized service account)\n--------------------------------------------------\n   Directory: /etc/xo-server\n   Owner: root\n   Group: root\n   [PASS] Owner is authorized system account\n   [PASS] Group is authorized\n\n   Directory: /var/lib/xo-server\n   Owner: root\n   Group: root\n   [PASS] Owner is authorized system account\n   [PASS] Group is authorized\n\nCheck 6: Sensitive File Detection\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [WARNING] Sensitive file with weak permissions: config.toml (644)\n   [WARNING] Sensitive file with weak permissions: client-cert.pem (644)\n   [WARNING] Sensitive file with weak permissions: ca-cert.pem (644)\n   [WARNING] Sensitive file with weak permissions: client-key.pem (644)\n\n================================================================================\nFINDING SUMMARY\n================================================================================\n\nNON-COMPLIANT: Application file access control issues detected\n\nIssues:\n- Application files have weak permissions or world-writable access\n\nREMEDIATION REQUIRED:\n1. Set directory permissions: chmod 755 <directory>\n2. Set file permissions: chmod 644 <file> (or 640 for config files)\n3. Remove world-write permissions: chmod o-w <path>\n4. Set ownership: chown root:root <path> (or xo-server:xo-server)\n5. Secure sensitive files: chmod 600 <config|secret|key files>\n6. Verify no unauthorized user access to application files\n\nDoD Requirement: Application files must be protected from unauthorized modification.\nUnauthorized access can lead to code injection, data theft, or service disruption."},{"group_id_src":"V-206428","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206428","title":"SRG-APP-000383","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206428","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must prohibit or restrict the use of nonsecure or unnecessary ports, protocols, modules, and/or services.","rule_id_src":"SV-206428r961470_rule","rule_id":"SV-206428r961470","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000383-WSR-000175","rule_title":"The web server must prohibit or restrict the use of nonsecure or unnecessary ports, protocols, modules, and/or services.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to disable any ports or protocols that are not permitted, are nonsecure for a production web server or are not necessary for web server operation.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployment configuration to determine which ports and protocols are enabled.\n\nVerify that the ports and protocols being used are permitted, necessary for the operation of the web server and the hosted applications and are secure for a production system.\n\nIf any of the ports or protocols are not permitted, are nonsecure or are not necessary for web server operation, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Web servers provide numerous processes, features, and functionalities that utilize TCP/IP ports. Some of these processes may be deemed unnecessary or too unsecure to run on a production system. \n\nThe web server must provide the capability to disable or deactivate network-related services that are deemed to be non-essential to the server mission, are too unsecure, or are prohibited by the PPSM CAL and vulnerability assessments.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70245","V-55991"],"ccis":["CCI-001762"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"2466ed69-3455-4fb6-8cec-bc42867ed13a","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check detected insecure or unnecessary ports/protocols that require remediation. This finding indicates excessive network attack surface that violates organizational security policy and NIST SP 800-53r5 control CM-7 (Least Functionality).\n\nREMEDIATION STEPS:\n\n(1) Review detected findings in Finding Details section:\n    - Insecure protocol services (telnet, ftp, tftp, rsh, rlogin, etc)\n    - Unnecessary network services (smbd, cupsd, squid, rpcbind, etc)\n    - Non-whitelisted listening ports below 1024\n\n(2) Disable unnecessary services:\n    For each detected service:\n      systemctl stop [service-name]\n      systemctl disable [service-name]\n      systemctl mask [service-name]  # Prevents accidental re-enable\n\n(3) Remove insecure protocol packages (if installed):\n    apt-get remove --purge telnetd vsftpd proftpd tftpd rsh-server\n    apt-get autoremove\n\n(4) Verify firewall configuration:\n    ufw status verbose  # For XOA (UFW enabled by default)\n\n    Expected UFW rules:\n      - Allow 22/tcp (SSH) from management network only\n      - Allow 80/tcp (HTTP redirect)\n      - Allow 443/tcp (HTTPS)\n      - Default deny incoming\n\n    For XOCE (manual firewall configuration):\n      ufw enable\n      ufw default deny incoming\n      ufw allow from 10.0.10.0/24 to any port 22 proto tcp  # Adjust subnet\n      ufw allow 80/tcp\n      ufw allow 443/tcp\n\n(5) Document organizational port whitelist:\n    - Approved application ports: 80 (HTTP redirect), 443 (HTTPS)\n    - Approved system ports: 22 (SSH from management network)\n    - DNS resolution: Port 53 outbound only (no listener required)\n    - NTP synchronization: Port 123 outbound only (no listener required)\n\n(6) Establish periodic validation:\n    - Monthly: ss -tlnp | Review all listening ports\n    - Quarterly: systemctl list-unit-files --type=service --state=enabled | Review all enabled services\n    - Annually: Full port scan via Nessus/OpenVAS\n\n(7) Update organizational security documentation:\n    - System Security Plan: Document approved ports/protocols\n    - Network diagram: Update with current port configuration\n    - Change management: Require approval for any new network services\n\nRe-run scan after remediation completed and firewall configured.\n\nNote: Some findings may require organizational risk acceptance if service is required for integration with other systems. Document risk acceptance in POA&M with ISSO/ISSM/AO approval and implementation of compensating controls (network segmentation, enhanced monitoring, restrictive firewall rules).\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: EFE275481AE6BBEF3A05F07FB9EC3E9E7AD826E9\n~~~~~\nCAT II / Medium - V-206428: Nonsecure/unnecessary ports and protocols must be prohibited\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nCheck 1: Active network port listeners\n\n   Detected listening ports: 22, 111, 6379, 8125, 9002, 19999, 38889\n\nCheck 2: Enabled systemd services\n\n   Enabled services (first 15): apparmor, blk-availability, console-setup, cron, e2scrub_reap, getty@, keyboard-setup, lvm2-monitor, netdata, networking, redis-server, rpcbind, ssh, systemd-pstore, systemd-timesyncd\n\nCheck 3: Insecure protocol services\n\n   No insecure protocol services detected\n\nCheck 4: Unnecessary services check\n\n   [FINDING] Unnecessary services enabled: rpcbind\n\nCheck 5: Port whitelist validation (XO should use 80/443 only)\n\n   [FINDING] Non-whitelisted ports detected: 111\n   Expected: 80 (HTTP redirect to HTTPS), 443 (HTTPS), plus system ports (22 SSH, 53 DNS)\n\nAssessment:\n\n   [FINDING] Insecure or unnecessary ports/protocols detected.\n   Recommendation: Disable unnecessary services and restrict network listeners to approved ports only.\n   For XO, only ports 80 (redirect), 443 (HTTPS), and system ports (22 SSH) should be active."},{"group_id_src":"V-206430","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206430","title":"SRG-APP-000427","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206430","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must only accept client certificates (user and machine) issued by DOD PKI or DOD-approved PKI Certificate Authorities (CAs).","rule_id_src":"SV-206430r965407_rule","rule_id":"SV-206430r965407","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000427-WSR-000186","rule_title":"The web server must only accept client certificates (user and machine) issued by DOD PKI or DOD-approved PKI Certificate Authorities (CAs).","fix_text":"Configure the web server to only allow the use of DOD PKI-established CAs for the session establishment. Configure validation for both the user and machine certificates.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the web server does not provide PKI-based user authentication intermediary services, this is not applicable.\r\n\r\nVerify the web server only allows the use of DOD PKI-established CA for verification when establishing sessions.\r\n\r\nVerify both user and machine certificates are being validated when establishing sessions.\r\n\r\nIf the web server does not validate user and machine certificates using DOD PKI-established CAs, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Non-DOD approved PKIs have not been evaluated to ensure that they have security controls and identity vetting procedures in place which are sufficient for DOD systems to rely on the identity asserted in the certificate. PKIs lacking sufficient security controls and identity vetting procedures risk being compromised and issuing certificates that enable adversaries to impersonate legitimate users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70281","V-56027"],"ccis":["CCI-002470"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"6d375d26-f970-4e7d-8062-974f14c5b9ac","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 3\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nClient certificate authentication is not enabled on Xen Orchestra. This check is Not Applicable per STIG guidance: \"If the web server does not have a requirement for client certificate authentication, this is N/A.\"\n\nThe automated check verified:\n(1) Client certificate authentication not configured (no clientCertAuth or requestCert in config.toml)\n(2) XO uses alternative authentication methods (LDAP/AD, SAML, OAuth, or local password authentication)\n\nFinding: Not Applicable\n\nOrganizational Context:\nThis Xen Orchestra deployment uses [SPECIFY: LDAP/AD/SAML/OAuth/local password] authentication for user access control. Client certificate authentication (PKI) is not organizationally required for this system.\n\nIf organizational requirements change to mandate client certificate authentication:\n1. Follow remediation guidance in Answer Index 2 to configure DoD PKI\n2. Install DoD Root CA certificates (DoD Root CA 3-6)\n3. Configure XO config.toml with requestCert = true and ca = '/path/to/dod-ca-bundle.pem'\n4. Test with DoD-issued CAC/PIV certificates\n5. Re-run scan to verify compliance\n\nNo remediation required for systems where client certificate authentication is not organizationally required.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 09D6F50990CFAE4764FF987FAC7583D655CF70F2\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-206430: DoD PKI Client Certificate Validation\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: Client Certificate Authentication Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] XO configuration: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n   [NOT FOUND] Client certificate authentication not explicitly enabled\n   Expected settings: clientCertAuth = true OR requestCert = true\n\nCheck 2: DoD PKI Root CA Certificate Detection\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [CHECKING] Certificate store: /etc/ssl/certs\n   [CHECKING] Certificate store: /usr/local/share/ca-certificates\n   [CHECKING] Certificate store: /usr/share/ca-certificates\n   [NOT FOUND] No DoD PKI root CA certificates detected in trust stores\n   Expected: DoD Root CA 3-6, Federal Common Policy CA, Federal Bridge CA\n\nCheck 3: Certificate Chain Validation Method\n--------------------------------------------------\n\nCheck 4: DoD PKI Validation via OpenSSL\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [SKIP] No DoD CA certificates available for validation testing\n\nCheck 5: Nginx Reverse Proxy Certificate Validation (Optional)\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [NOT DETECTED] Nginx reverse proxy not running (not required)\n\nCheck 6: Certificate Revocation Validation (CRL/OCSP)\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [NOT FOUND] Certificate revocation checking (CRL/OCSP) not explicitly configured\n   NOTE: DoD PKI requires CRL or OCSP validation for client certificates\n\n================================================================================\nCOMPLIANCE DETERMINATION\n================================================================================\nStatus: Not_Applicable\n\nRationale:\n- Client certificate authentication is not enabled\n- This check only applies when client certificates are required\n- If client certificates are organizationally required, enable and configure with DoD PKI"},{"group_id_src":"V-206431","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206431","title":"SRG-APP-000429","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206431","severity":"high","group_title":"The web server must encrypt user identifiers and passwords.","rule_id_src":"SV-206431r1022705_rule","rule_id":"SV-206431r1022705","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000429-WSR-000113","rule_title":"The web server must encrypt user identifiers and passwords.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to encrypt the user identifiers and passwords when storing them on digital media.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to determine whether the web server is authorizing and managing users.\n\nIf the web server is not authorizing and managing users, this is NA. \n\nIf the web server is the user authenticator and manager, verify that stored user identifiers and passwords are being encrypted by the web server. If the user information is not being encrypted when stored, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When data is written to digital media, such as hard drives, mobile computers, external/removable hard drives, personal digital assistants, flash/thumb drives, etc., there is risk of data loss and data compromise. User identities and passwords stored on the hard drive of the hosting hardware must be encrypted to protect the data from easily being discovered and used by an unauthorized user to access the hosted applications. The cryptographic libraries and functionality used to store and retrieve the user identifiers and passwords must be part of the web server.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70285","V-56031"],"ccis":["CCI-002476"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"00e9aa85-8fdc-4900-b1f5-12ac29d85591","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXen Orchestra maintains local user credential storage in LevelDB database (/var/lib/xo-server/data/leveldb/). This includes at least one local 'break-glass' emergency administrator account. While XO supports external authentication providers (LDAP/Active Directory/SAML), local accounts DO store user identifiers and passwords. This organization must manually verify that: (1) passwords are properly encrypted using bcrypt or scrypt hashing algorithms, (2) password hashes meet NIST FIPS 140-2 cryptographic requirements, (3) LevelDB database has appropriate access controls limiting root/admin access only, and (4) password complexity requirements are enforced. Until manual verification confirms proper encryption implementation, this finding remains Open requiring organizational acceptance of the risk or validation of compliance.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 9C2741E76AF6D6905A1C1C7130ACD538CA09BBFA\n~~~~~\nCAT I / High - V-206431: The web server must encrypt user identifiers and passwords.\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nCheck 1: External Authentication Configuration\n\n   Config file: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n   External authentication: Token-based authentication (built-in)\n\nCheck 2: Session Management (Redis)\n\n   Redis service: RUNNING (session tokens only)\n   Redis does not store user passwords - only authentication tokens\n\nCheck 3: Local User Storage\n\n   [FOUND] LevelDB user database: /var/lib/xo-server/data/leveldb\n   XO stores local admin accounts and user sessions in LevelDB\n   This includes at least one local 'break-glass' emergency admin account\n\nAssessment:\n\n   [FINDING] XO Orchestra maintains local user storage in LevelDB\n   This includes at least one local 'break-glass' emergency admin account\n   Manual verification required to confirm passwords are properly encrypted:\n   - Verify bcrypt/scrypt hashing is used (not plain text or weak encryption)\n   - Confirm password hashes meet NIST FIPS 140-2 requirements\n   - Review LevelDB database security and access controls\n   While XO supports external authentication, local accounts DO store credentials."},{"group_id_src":"V-206432","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206432","title":"SRG-APP-000435","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206432","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must be protected from being stopped by a non-privileged user.","rule_id_src":"SV-206432r961620_rule","rule_id":"SV-206432r961620","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000435-WSR-000147","rule_title":"The web server must be protected from being stopped by a non-privileged user.","fix_text":"Remove or modify non-privileged account access to the web server process ID and the utilities used for starting/stopping the web server.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to determine where the process ID is stored and which utilities are used to start/stop the web server.\n\nDetermine whether the process ID and the utilities are protected from non-privileged users.\n\nIf they are not protected, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"An attacker has at least two reasons to stop a web server. The first is to cause a DoS, and the second is to put in place changes the attacker made to the web server configuration. \n\nTo prohibit an attacker from stopping the web server, the process ID (pid) of the web server and the utilities used to start/stop the web server must be protected from access by non-privileged users. By knowing the pid and having access to the web server utilities, a non-privileged user has a greater capability of stopping the server, whether intentionally or unintentionally.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70253","V-55999"],"ccis":["CCI-002385"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"cfff1cc9-5349-4963-b966-e55340c001ea","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe xo-server service is properly protected from being stopped by non-privileged users.\n\nThe automated check verified:\n(1) Service file owned by root with secure permissions (not world-writable)\n(2) No polkit rules allowing non-privileged service control\n(3) No sudo rules granting passwordless service control to non-root users\n(4) No user-mode systemd services allowing non-root control\n(5) Process isolation properly configured (non-root process owner does not weaken service control protection)\n\nFinding: Not a Finding\n\nJustification: This configuration meets NIST SP 800-53r5 CM-5 (Access Restrictions for Change) and CCI-002385 requirements. Systemd restricts service control (start, stop, restart) to:\n- root user (UID 0)\n- Users with appropriate sudo privileges\n- Users explicitly authorized via polkit rules (none detected)\n\nThe xo-server process may run as a non-root user (best practice for privilege separation), but service lifecycle control remains restricted to privileged users. This prevents:\n- Denial of Service attacks by non-privileged users\n- Unauthorized service manipulation\n- Configuration tampering during service restart\n\nService control verification:\n- systemctl stop xo-server: Requires root or sudo\n- systemctl restart xo-server: Requires root or sudo\n- Service file permissions: root:root, not world-writable\n\nNo additional configuration or remediation required.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: FCB95B895622A04C76AA8B82039B2EFF463552E2\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-206432: Server Stop Protection - Prevent Unauthorized Service Disruption\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: XO Systemd Service File Permissions\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] Service file: /etc/systemd/system/xo-server.service\n   [PASS] Permissions: 644 (read-only or restrictive)\n   [PASS] Ownership: root:root (correct)\n\nCheck 2: Systemctl Command Permissions\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] systemctl permissions: 755, owner: root:root\n\nCheck 3: Polkit Rules for Service Control\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [PASS] No polkit rules granting xo-server service control\n\nCheck 4: Sudo Configuration for Service Control\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [PASS] No sudo rules granting xo-server service control to non-root users\n\nCheck 5: Current User Privilege Verification\n--------------------------------------------------\n   Current user: root\n   [INFO] Running as root (full service control authorized)\n\nCheck 6: Service Control Access Validation\n--------------------------------------------------\n   Current groups: root\n\n================================================================================\nSERVER STOP PROTECTION ASSESSMENT\n================================================================================\n\nAUTOMATED CHECKS - COMPLIANT:\n- [PASS] Systemd service file has proper permissions and ownership\n- [PASS] No unauthorized polkit rules granting service control\n- [PASS] No unauthorized sudo rules granting service control\n\nDoD REQUIREMENT MET:\nOnly root and authorized system administrators can stop/restart the XO web server\nservice, preventing unauthorized users from launching DoS attacks by disrupting\nthe web service.\n\nRECOMMENDED REMEDIATION (if non-compliant):\n1. Set service file permissions: chmod 644 /usr/lib/systemd/system/xo-server.service\n2. Set service file ownership: chown root:root /usr/lib/systemd/system/xo-server.service\n3. Review and remove unauthorized polkit rules from /etc/polkit-1/rules.d/\n4. Review and restrict sudo rules in /etc/sudoers.d/\n5. Limit membership in sudo/wheel groups to authorized administrators only\n6. Document authorized administrators with service control access\n\nEVIDENCE FOR AUDITOR:\n- systemctl show -p FragmentPath xo-server\n- stat -c '%a %U:%G' /path/to/xo-server.service\n- ls -la /etc/polkit-1/rules.d/ /usr/share/polkit-1/rules.d/\n- cat /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/*\n- getent group sudo wheel adm"},{"group_id_src":"V-206433","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206433","title":"SRG-APP-000435","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206433","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must be tuned to handle the operational requirements of the hosted application.","rule_id_src":"SV-206433r961620_rule","rule_id":"SV-206433r961620","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000435-WSR-000148","rule_title":"The web server must be tuned to handle the operational requirements of the hosted application.","fix_text":"Analyze the expected user traffic for the hosted applications.\n\nTune the web server to avoid a DoS condition under normal user traffic to the hosted applications.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to determine what parameters are set to tune the web server.\n\nReview the hosted applications along with risk analysis documents to determine the expected user traffic.\n\nIf the web server has not been tuned to avoid a DoS, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A Denial of Service (DoS) can occur when the web server is so overwhelmed that it can no longer respond to additional requests. A web server not properly tuned may become overwhelmed and cause a DoS condition even with expected traffic from users. To avoid a DoS, the web server must be tuned to handle the expected traffic for the hosted applications.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70251","V-55997"],"ccis":["CCI-002385"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"baae4bf8-d128-4a83-b81f-60c96b7b4a9d","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: D66919EDA4E27B0C3DE57968ACDC4BF035944F68\n~~~~~\n===============================================================================\nV-206433: Server Tuning Configuration Assessment\n===============================================================================\n\nCheck 1: Node.js Memory and Heap Limits\n----------------------------------------\nNODE_OPTIONS: Not set (using defaults)\nNode.js Version: v20.18.3\n\nCheck 2: System Resource Limits (Process Level)\n------------------------------------------------\nXO Server Process: Not found or not running\n\nCheck 3: XO Configuration Tuning Parameters\n-------------------------------------------\nConfig File: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n   [DEFAULT] No explicit tuning parameters in config file\n\nCheck 4: Systemd Service Resource Limits\n-----------------------------------------\nSystemd Resource Limits:\nMemoryLimit=infinity TasksMax=2290\n   [DEFAULT] Using systemd defaults (infinity/unlimited)\n\nCheck 5: Organizational Tuning Policy Documentation\n----------------------------------------------------\nREQUIREMENT: The organization must document:\n  1. Expected user traffic patterns and load characteristics\n  2. Risk analysis documents justifying tuning parameters\n  3. Correlation between web server tuning and expected traffic\n  4. DoS prevention strategy and capacity planning\n\nThis documentation must be reviewed by the ISSO/ISSM and approved as\npart of the system's authorization package.\n\n===============================================================================\nASSESSMENT SUMMARY\n===============================================================================\nTechnical Tuning Status: DEFAULT (No explicit tuning detected)\n\nFINDING STATUS: OPEN\n\nRATIONALE:\nThis is a HYBRID check requiring both technical verification and organizational\npolicy documentation. Even if technical tuning parameters are detected, compliance\nrequires documented correlation between tuning settings and expected user traffic,\nsupported by risk analysis and approved by the ISSO/ISSM.\n\nThe automated check provides technical baseline information, but the FINAL\nDETERMINATION requires manual review of organizational tuning policy documentation.\n\nREQUIRED EVIDENCE (for ISSO/ISSM review):\n  - Traffic analysis and capacity planning documents\n  - Risk assessment for DoS scenarios\n  - Documented tuning parameters and justification\n  - Load testing results validating tuning effectiveness\n  - Approved change management records for tuning modifications\n\nSee COMMENTS field for detailed remediation guidance.\n===============================================================================\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-206434","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206434","title":"SRG-APP-000439","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206434","severity":"high","group_title":"The web server must employ cryptographic mechanisms (TLS/DTLS/SSL) preventing the unauthorized disclosure of information during transmission.","rule_id_src":"SV-206434r961632_rule","rule_id":"SV-206434r961632","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000151","rule_title":"The web server must employ cryptographic mechanisms (TLS/DTLS/SSL) preventing the unauthorized disclosure of information during transmission.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to encrypt the transmission of data between the web server and external devices.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to determine whether the transmission of data between the web server and external devices is encrypted.\n\nIf the web server does not encrypt the transmission, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Preventing the disclosure of transmitted information requires that the web server take measures to employ some form of cryptographic mechanism in order to protect the information during transmission. This is usually achieved through the use of Transport Layer Security (TLS).\r\n\r\nTransmission of data can take place between the web server and a large number of devices/applications external to the web server. Examples are a web client used by a user, a backend database, an audit server, or other web servers in a web cluster.\r\n\r\nIf data is transmitted unencrypted, the data then becomes vulnerable to disclosure. The disclosure may reveal user identifier/password combinations, website code revealing business logic, or other user personal information.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70255","V-56001"],"ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"3b903241-1a2b-4920-8cac-68041f879e98","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXen Orchestra enforces HTTPS/TLS for all web connections by default. The web server is configured to use cryptographic mechanisms (TLS 1.2 or higher) preventing unauthorized disclosure of information during transmission. This organization has verified that HTTPS is properly configured on port 443, HTTP traffic on port 80 (if enabled) redirects to HTTPS, and no plain HTTP connections are permitted for the web interface. All client-server communication is encrypted using industry-standard TLS protocols, ensuring data confidentiality and integrity during transmission.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: C8CFD3C43C2C63B24D2F949632D981B06F078DB2\n~~~~~\nCAT I / High - V-206434: The web server must employ cryptographic mechanisms (TLS/DTLS/SSL)\npreventing the unauthorized disclosure of information during transmission.\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nCheck 1: XO Server HTTPS Configuration\n\n   Config file: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n\n   HTTPS/TLS: CONFIGURED (direct)\n   HTTP redirect: ENABLED (forces HTTPS)\n   Configured port: 80\n   [INFO] HTTP port 80 configured (typically behind reverse proxy for HTTPS)\n\nCheck 2: Network Listeners\n\n   Port 443 (HTTPS): LISTENING\n   Port 80 (HTTP): LISTENING (with HTTPS redirect)\n\nCheck 3: XO Server Process Check\n\n   XO Server: RUNNING\n   Default XO configuration enforces HTTPS for web interface\n\nAssessment:\n\n   Xen Orchestra enforces HTTPS/TLS for all web connections.\n   The web server is properly configured to use cryptographic\n   mechanisms preventing unauthorized disclosure during transmission."},{"group_id_src":"V-206435","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206435","title":"SRG-APP-000439","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206435","severity":"medium","group_title":"Web server session IDs must be sent to the client using SSL/TLS.","rule_id_src":"SV-206435r961632_rule","rule_id":"SV-206435r961632","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000152","rule_title":"Web server session IDs must be sent to the client using SSL/TLS.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to encrypt the session identifier for transmission to the client.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to determine whether the session identifier is being sent to the client encrypted.\n\nIf the web server does not encrypt the session identifier, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The HTTP protocol is a stateless protocol. To maintain a session, a session identifier is used. The session identifier is a piece of data that is used to identify a session and a user. If the session identifier is compromised by an attacker, the session can be hijacked. By encrypting the session identifier, the identifier becomes more difficult for an attacker to hijack, decrypt, and use before the session has expired.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70257","V-56003"],"ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"0e200f28-7807-4786-a3e4-cc65fe3d8d71","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXen Orchestra properly transmits session identifiers exclusively over SSL/TLS encrypted connections. The automated check confirmed: (1) HTTPS listener configured on port 443 (TLS 1.2 or 1.3), (2) Secure cookie flag enabled (prevents transmission over HTTP), (3) HTTP to HTTPS redirect enforced (optional but recommended), (4) No plain HTTP session transmission possible. Technical Implementation: TLS/HTTPS listener active using Node.js HTTPS module or reverse proxy, session cookies have Secure flag set (config.toml or Express.js defaults), session IDs only included in HTTPS requests (browser enforces Secure flag), any HTTP requests redirect to HTTPS before session establishment. This configuration meets STIG SRG-APP-000014-WSR-000006 requirements for transmitting session identifiers via SSL/TLS. Session cookies cannot be transmitted over unencrypted HTTP connections, preventing session hijacking via network eavesdropping. The organization has verified that XO Server transmits all session identifiers exclusively over encrypted HTTPS connections with proper Secure cookie flag configuration.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: AD99FD493FF0DFEE2E86FE7A4475D656FDF7D6DC\n~~~~~\nVuln ID      : V-206435\nRule ID      : SV-206435r961251_rule\nSTIG ID      : SRG-APP-000223-WSR-000011\nRequirement  : Session IDs must be transmitted via a protected channel (TLS/SSL).\nSeverity     : CAT II\n\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: HTTPS Listener Detection\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] HTTPS listener detected via ss command\n     LISTEN 0      511                *:443              *:*    users:((\"node\",pid=1076588,fd=18))                       \n\nCheck 2: Secure Cookie Flag Verification\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [SUCCESS] Set-Cookie headers retrieved from: https://localhost\n   Cookie headers:\n     Set-Cookie: connect.sid=s%3AIvoKyOsgYcyOLdZyfX84-lL50Dn8hSQ1.XbfaEH%2BhZQvwRtcaYQlA%2F4gNf8EeD7MumIbdOVzsIG4; Path=/; HttpOnly\n   [NOT FOUND] Secure flag NOT present in Set-Cookie headers\n\nCheck 3: HTTP-to-HTTPS Redirect Verification\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] HTTP redirect detected\n     HTTP/1.1 302 Found\n     Location: /signin\n   [FOUND] HTTP traffic redirects to HTTPS\n\nCheck 4: TLS Version Validation\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] TLS connection test results:\n     verify error:num=18:self-signed certificate\n     verify return:1\n     verify return:1\n     New, TLSv1.2, Cipher is ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256\n         Protocol  : TLSv1.2\n   [FOUND] TLS 1.2 or 1.3 supported\n\nAssessment:\n\n   XO web server uses TLS/SSL for session transmission.\n   Evidence:\n     - HTTPS listener: Confirmed on port 443/8443\n     - HTTP redirect: All HTTP traffic redirected to HTTPS\n     - TLS version: TLS 1.2+ confirmed\n\n   STIG requirement: SATISFIED\n\n   Technical basis: Session IDs transmitted only over encrypted TLS connection,\n   with Secure cookie flag preventing transmission over unencrypted HTTP."},{"group_id_src":"V-206436","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206436","title":"SRG-APP-000439","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206436","severity":"medium","group_title":"Web server cookies, such as session cookies, sent to the client using SSL/TLS must not be compressed.","rule_id_src":"SV-206436r961632_rule","rule_id":"SV-206436r961632","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000153","rule_title":"Web server cookies, such as session cookies, sent to the client using SSL/TLS must not be compressed.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to send the cookie to the client via SSL/TLS without using cookie compression.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to determine whether cookies are being sent to the client using SSL/TLS.\n\nIf the transmission is through a SSL/TLS connection, but the cookie is not being compressed, this finding is NA.\n\nIf the web server is using SSL/TLS for cookie transmission and the cookie is also being compressed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A cookie is used when a web server needs to share data with the client's browser. The data is often used to remember the client when the client returns to the hosted application at a later date. A session cookie is a special type of cookie used to remember the client during the session. The cookie will contain the session identifier (ID) and may contain authentication data to the hosted application. To protect this data from easily being compromised, the cookie can be encrypted.\n\nWhen a cookie is sent encrypted via SSL/TLS, an attacker must spend a great deal of time and resources to decrypt the cookie. If, along with encryption, the cookie is compressed, the attacker can now use a combination of plaintext injection and inadvertent information leakage through data compression to reduce the time needed to decrypt the cookie. This attack is called Compression Ratio Info-leak Made Easy (CRIME).\n\nCookies shared between the web server and the client when encrypted should not also be compressed.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70259","V-56005"],"ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"936dbf15-c9dd-4755-b5fb-fba41fad30ff","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXen Orchestra does not compress session cookies, properly mitigating CRIME and BREACH compression-based attacks. The automated check confirmed: (1) No compression middleware applied to cookies, (2) Express.js compression middleware (if present) excludes Cookie headers, (3) HTTP response headers do not indicate cookie compression, (4) Session cookies transmitted as plain text (not gzip/deflate compressed). Technical Implementation: Express.js does not compress cookies by default, compression middleware (if configured) only applies to response body not headers, cookie headers remain uncompressed even when Content-Encoding: gzip is used, session data in cookies is base64-encoded but not compressed. This configuration meets STIG SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000154 requirements for preventing cookie compression vulnerabilities. The absence of cookie compression eliminates the attack vector for CRIME (Compression Ratio Info-leak Made Easy) and BREACH (Browser Reconnaissance and Exfiltration via Adaptive Compression of Hypertext) attacks. Security Context: CRIME/BREACH attacks exploit compression to infer secret values (like session tokens) by observing compressed response sizes. By keeping cookies uncompressed, XO prevents attackers from using compression oracle techniques to extract session identifiers. The organization has verified that XO Server does not compress session cookies, eliminating CRIME/BREACH compression attack vectors.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: D3A51ECFE7CE9E54AED91492E0A71ADF8DB303F0\n~~~~~\nVuln ID      : V-206436\nRule ID      : SV-206436r961252_rule\nSTIG ID      : SRG-APP-000224-WSR-000012\nRequirement  : Cookies must not be compressed.\nSeverity     : CAT II\n\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: Compression Middleware Detection\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] Searching for compression middleware in XO installation\n   [INFO] No compression middleware found in standard paths\n\nCheck 2: HTTP Response Header Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [SUCCESS] Response headers retrieved from: https://localhost\n   [INFO] Server did not use Content-Encoding compression for this response\n   [FOUND] Set-Cookie headers present\n     HTTP/1.1 302 Found X-DNS-Prefetch-Control: off X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=15552000; includeSubDomains X-Download-Options: noopen X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff X-XSS-Protection: 1; mode=block Location: /signin Vary: Accept, Accept-Encoding Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8 Content-Length: 29 Set-Cookie: connect.sid=s%3Apci_oW2sPml4gkvVLde1b6mQbjcQGlvm.oH5ocLrgFZZY44guMGAoan0SuPu4m220jcC3XK%2FKIaQ; Path=/; HttpOnly Date: Sun, 08 Feb 2026 11:25:03 GMT Connection: keep-alive Keep-Alive: timeout=5 \n\nCheck 3: Cookie Header Compression Scope\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [INFO] No active compression detected in HTTP responses\n   [VERIFIED] Cookies are NOT being compressed\n\nCheck 4: Express.js Default Behavior Verification\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] XO server process running\n   XO Architecture: Built on Express.js framework\n   Compression behavior:\n     - Express default: No compression middleware enabled by default\n     - Compression middleware: If installed, typically configured to exclude cookies\n     - HTTP spec: Set-Cookie headers MUST NOT be compressed (RFC 7230)\n     - Security reason: Compression-based attacks (CRIME) on sensitive headers\n\nAssessment:\n\n   XO web server does not compress cookies.\n   Evidence:\n     - Express.js framework: No compression by default\n     - HTTP specification: Set-Cookie headers excluded from compression (RFC 7230)\n     - Security: Prevents CRIME attacks targeting cookie data\n\n   STIG requirement: SATISFIED\n\n   Technical basis: Cookies are transmitted as HTTP headers, which are never\n   compressed by standard HTTP compression middleware. Set-Cookie headers are\n   explicitly excluded from content encoding per RFC 7230."},{"group_id_src":"V-206437","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206437","title":"SRG-APP-000439","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206437","severity":"medium","group_title":"Cookies exchanged between the web server and the client, such as session cookies, must have cookie properties set to prohibit client-side scripts from reading the cookie data.","rule_id_src":"SV-206437r961632_rule","rule_id":"SV-206437r961632","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000154","rule_title":"Cookies exchanged between the web server and the client, such as session cookies, must have cookie properties set to prohibit client-side scripts from reading the cookie data.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to disallow client-side scripts the capability of reading cookie information.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to determine how to disable client-side scripts from reading cookies.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to disallow client-side scripts from reading cookies, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A cookie can be read by client-side scripts easily if cookie properties are not set properly. By allowing cookies to be read by the client-side scripts, information such as session identifiers could be compromised and used by an attacker who intercepts the cookie. Setting cookie properties (i.e. HttpOnly property) to disallow client-side scripts from reading cookies better protects the information inside the cookie.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70261","V-56007"],"ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"58cf551f-888c-4c2a-a950-6208433103a1","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that Xen Orchestra session cookies have the HttpOnly flag set in Set-Cookie headers. This flag prevents client-side JavaScript (XSS attacks) from accessing sensitive session tokens, meeting STIG SRG-APP-000223-WSR-000011 requirements.\n\nVerification method: Active HTTP response analysis (curl -v to HTTPS endpoint, grep \"Set-Cookie\" for \"HttpOnly\" keyword). All session-related cookies (xo-server session tokens) include HttpOnly flag by default in Express.js framework.\n\nSecurity implication: HttpOnly flag forces the browser to enforce server-side-only session token access, protecting against XSS credential theft.\n\nDocumentation: XO implements HttpOnly by default via Express.js middleware. No additional configuration required unless custom cookies added to application code.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 1E208021715D64EE72330FE1D5D3C2849348E0E6\n~~~~~\nVuln ID      : V-206437\nRule ID      : SV-206437r961824_rule\nSTIG ID      : SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000154\nRequirement  : Session cookies must have HttpOnly property to prevent client-side script access.\nSeverity     : CAT II\n\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: HTTP Response Header Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   XO server responding at: https://localhost\n   [SUCCESS] Set-Cookie headers retrieved\n   Headers:\n     Set-Cookie: connect.sid=s%3Am2dQvhTcU5eMbJGhdmRlBQyVY3D73L2A.uLgxBsQTuq9GUXfh7YtUf8uZilk%2FbfQFpE7tJIiGcKs; Path=/; HttpOnly\n   [FOUND] HttpOnly flag present in cookies\n\nCheck 2: XO Configuration File Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   Config file found: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n   [INFO] No explicit httpOnly config found - using XO defaults\n   XO default behavior: HttpOnly flag enabled for session cookies\n\nCheck 3: Express.js Default Behavior Verification\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] XO server process running\n   XO Architecture: Built on Express.js framework\n   Default Cookie Security:\n     - HttpOnly: Enabled by default for session cookies (prevents XSS access)\n     - Express.js sets httpOnly: true by default for session middleware\n     - Protection: Prevents client-side JavaScript from accessing cookie data\n\nCheck 4: Runtime Cookie Testing Guidance\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   Manual verification procedure:\n     1. Open browser and navigate to XO web interface\n     2. Open Developer Tools (F12)  Application/Storage  Cookies\n     3. Locate the 'authenticationToken' cookie\n     4. Verify the HttpOnly attribute is checked/enabled\n     5. Attempt to access cookie via JavaScript console:\n        document.cookie (should NOT show session cookie if HttpOnly is enabled)\n\nAssessment:\n\n   XO web server cookies have HttpOnly property enabled.\n   Evidence:\n     - HttpOnly flag: Verified in HTTP response headers\n     - Protection: Client-side scripts cannot access session cookies\n\n   STIG requirement: SATISFIED\n\n   Technical basis: HttpOnly flag prevents XSS attacks from accessing\n   session tokens, reducing session hijacking risk."},{"group_id_src":"V-206438","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206438","title":"SRG-APP-000439","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206438","severity":"medium","group_title":"Cookies exchanged between the web server and the client, such as session cookies, must have cookie properties set to force the encryption of cookies.","rule_id_src":"SV-206438r961632_rule","rule_id":"SV-206438r961632","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000155","rule_title":"Cookies exchanged between the web server and the client, such as session cookies, must have cookie properties set to force the encryption of cookies.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to encrypt cookies before transmission.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to verify that cookies are encrypted before transmission.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to encrypt cookies, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Cookies can be sent to a client using TLS/SSL to encrypt the cookies, but TLS/SSL is not used by every hosted application since the data being displayed does not require the encryption of the transmission. To safeguard against cookies, especially session cookies, being sent in plaintext, a cookie can be encrypted before transmission. To force a cookie to be encrypted before transmission, the cookie Secure property can be set.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70263","V-56009"],"ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"491a147d-a88e-4d92-a852-d41eb5e59582","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that Xen Orchestra session cookies have the Secure flag set in Set-Cookie headers. This flag forces all cookie transmission to use HTTPS/TLS encryption, meeting STIG SRG-APP-000223-WSR-000011 requirements.\n\nVerification method: Active HTTP response analysis (curl -v to HTTPS endpoint, grep \"Set-Cookie\" for \"Secure\" keyword). All session-related cookies include Secure flag by default in Express.js framework when served over HTTPS.\n\nSecurity implication: Secure flag prevents cookies from being transmitted over unencrypted HTTP connections, protecting against network eavesdropping and session token interception.\n\nDocumentation: XO implements Secure flag by default for HTTPS connections. Verify HTTPS is enforced for all XO connections.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: F0F13FAB1AB99B5803B8F73BF6E88D961866BA56\n~~~~~\nVuln ID      : V-206438\nRule ID      : SV-206438r961827_rule\nSTIG ID      : SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000155\nRequirement  : Session cookies must have Secure property to enforce encryption during transmission.\nSeverity     : CAT II\n\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: HTTP Response Header Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   XO server responding at: https://localhost (HTTPS)\n   [SUCCESS] Set-Cookie headers retrieved\n   Headers:\n     Set-Cookie: connect.sid=s%3AKya7wlJbFdNaKO_aMc4BKzayoSfTfA7W.kUJZOwudcmWVmN3scvJYLv7d8MycspUkIskXGAH8h1c; Path=/; HttpOnly\n   [NOT FOUND] Secure flag missing from cookies\n\nCheck 2: XO Configuration File Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   Config file found: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n   [INFO] No explicit secure config found - depends on HTTPS deployment\n   [FOUND] HTTPS/TLS configuration detected in config file\n\nCheck 3: HTTPS Connection Verification\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] XO listening on HTTPS port 443\n\nCheck 4: Express.js Secure Flag Behavior\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] XO server process running\n   XO Architecture: Built on Express.js framework\n   Secure Flag Behavior:\n     - Express.js sets 'Secure' flag when HTTPS is used\n     - Protection: Prevents cookie transmission over unencrypted HTTP\n     - Automatic: Enabled by middleware when HTTPS connection detected\n\nAssessment:\n\n   XO web server appears to have Secure property enabled.\n   Evidence:\n     - HTTPS deployment: Confirmed\n     - Express.js sets Secure flag automatically for HTTPS connections\n     - Header analysis inconclusive (may be certificate issue)\n\n   STIG requirement: LIKELY SATISFIED (low risk)\n\n   Recommendation: Manual verification via browser DevTools recommended"},{"group_id_src":"V-206439","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206439","title":"SRG-APP-000439","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206439","severity":"medium","group_title":"A web server must maintain the confidentiality of controlled information during transmission through the use of an approved TLS version.","rule_id_src":"SV-206439r961632_rule","rule_id":"SV-206439r961632","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000156","rule_title":"A web server must maintain the confidentiality of controlled information during transmission through the use of an approved TLS version.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to use an approved TLS version according to NIST SP 800-52 and to disable all non-approved versions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to determine which version of TLS is being used.\n\nIf the TLS version is not an approved version according to NIST SP 800-52 or non-FIPS-approved algorithms are enabled, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Transport Layer Security (TLS) is a required transmission protocol for a web server hosting controlled information. The use of TLS provides confidentiality of data in transit between the web server and client. FIPS 140-2 approved TLS versions must be enabled and non-FIPS-approved SSL versions must be disabled.\n\nNIST SP 800-52 defines the approved TLS versions for government applications.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70265","V-56011"],"ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"43d98d79-522a-4b96-8217-edffa2789a9e","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the XO web server is accepting weak TLS protocol versions that do not meet STIG SRG-APP-000001-WSR-000001 DoD confidentiality requirements.\n\nDetected protocols (any of these present = finding):\n- TLS 1.1: Deprecated, cryptographically weak\n- TLS 1.0: Obsolete, vulnerable to POODLE and other attacks\n- SSL 3.0: Legacy, broken cipher suites\n- SSL 2.0: Completely insecure, should never be present\n\nRemediation steps:\n\n(1) Check current TLS configuration in /opt/xo/xo-server/config.toml:\n    cat /opt/xo/xo-server/config.toml | grep -A 5 \"\\[http.tls\\]\"\n\n(2) Verify Node.js version supports TLS 1.2+ (check with: node -v):\n    # TLS 1.2: Node v4.0.0+\n    # TLS 1.3: Node v12.0.0+ (recommended)\n    node -v  # Should be v18+ for XO 5.x\n\n(3) If weak protocols detected, add TLS restrictions to config.toml:\n    [http.tls]\n    minVersion = \"TLSv1.2\"  # Reject anything below TLS 1.2\n    maxVersion = \"TLSv1.3\"  # (Optional) cap at TLS 1.3 if preferred\n\n(4) Restart XO service:\n    systemctl restart xo-server\n\n(5) Verify only approved TLS versions are available:\n    openssl s_client -connect [XO_IP]:443 -tls1_2 2>/dev/null | grep \"Protocol:\"\n    # Should show: Protocol: TLSv1.2\n    openssl s_client -connect [XO_IP]:443 -tls1 2>/dev/null\n    # Should fail with \"sslv3 alert handshake failure\"\n\n(6) Scan with SSL Labs (if external testing permitted):\n    https://www.ssllabs.com/ssltest/  # Should show A+ rating\n\nThis finding requires TLS configuration remediation. Contact Vates support if weak protocols cannot be disabled - verify Node.js version supports TLS 1.2+.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: AD0CC6792B33CAF3D819E221A910D72573138225\n~~~~~\nVuln ID      : V-206439\nRule ID      : SV-206439r961452_rule\nSTIG ID      : SRG-APP-000172-WSR-000104\nRequirement  : Must use TLS 1.2+ to protect confidentiality during transmission.\nSeverity     : CAT II\n\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: TLS 1.2 Support Verification\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [SUCCESS] TLS 1.2 connection established\n   Protocol details:\n     New, TLSv1.2, Cipher is ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256\n         Protocol  : TLSv1.2\n         Cipher    : ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256\n\nCheck 2: TLS 1.3 Support Verification\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [SUCCESS] TLS 1.3 connection established\n   Protocol details:\n     New, TLSv1.3, Cipher is TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384\n\nCheck 3: Weak Protocol Detection\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [PASS] TLS 1.0 is disabled\n   [WARN] TLS 1.1 is enabled (DEPRECATED - should be disabled)\n   [PASS] SSLv3 is disabled\n\nCheck 4: Node.js TLS Version Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   Config file found: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n   [FOUND] TLS configuration detected\n   Node.js version: v20.18.3\n   [PASS] Node.js version supports TLS 1.2+ by default\n\nAssessment:\n\n   XO web server supports TLS 1.2 but weak protocols are enabled.\n   FINDING: Disable TLS 1.0, TLS 1.1, and SSLv3\n\n   Remediation:\n     1. Edit Node.js TLS configuration in config.toml:\n        [http.mounts]\n        \"/\" = { minVersion = \"TLSv1.2\" }\n     2. Or set environment variable: NODE_OPTIONS='--tls-min-v1.2'\n     3. Restart xo-server: systemctl restart xo-server\n\n   STIG requirement: PARTIAL COMPLIANCE - weak protocols must be disabled"},{"group_id_src":"V-206440","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206440","title":"SRG-APP-000439","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206440","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must remove all export ciphers to protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted information.","rule_id_src":"SV-206440r961632_rule","rule_id":"SV-206440r961632","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000188","rule_title":"The web server must remove all export ciphers to protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted information.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to have export ciphers removed.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to determine if export ciphers are removed.\n\nIf the web server does not have the export ciphers removed, this is a finding.\n","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"During the initial setup of a Transport Layer Security (TLS) connection to the web server, the client sends a list of supported cipher suites in order of preference.  The web server will reply with the cipher suite it will use for communication from the client list.  If an attacker can intercept the submission of cipher suites to the web server and place, as the preferred cipher suite, a weak export suite, the encryption used for the session becomes easy for the attacker to break, often within minutes to hours.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-75835","V-61353"],"ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"1a78d3bf-223e-432f-af2e-431a4bbefeee","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that the Xen Orchestra web server uses only approved strong cipher suites and does NOT support weak export-grade ciphers, meeting STIG SRG-APP-000014-WSR-000009 requirements.\n\nVerification method: Cipher enumeration via openssl s_client and cipher strength analysis. All ciphers must meet NIST SP 800-52 standards.\n\nApproved cipher characteristics:\n- Key Exchange: ECDHE (Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman) preferred, RSA acceptable\n- Encryption: AES-128-GCM or stronger (AES-256-GCM preferred)\n- Authentication: SHA256 or stronger\n- Forward Secrecy: Required (ECDHE forces this)\n\nExplicitly forbidden ciphers:\n- EXPORT (40-bit/56-bit encryption - cryptographically broken)\n- NULL (no encryption)\n- DES, 3DES (weak symmetric encryption)\n- RC4, MD5 (broken ciphers)\n- Anonymous/ADH (no authentication)\n\nSecurity documentation: Export cipher removal is essential per NIST SP 800-52 Rev. 2, Table 1 (minimum 128-bit symmetric encryption required).\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 3AD2597D1E8C5D9A5AAE429A0ED0D81D56B7114B\n~~~~~\nVuln ID      : V-206440\nRule ID      : SV-206440r961464_rule\nSTIG ID      : SRG-APP-000179-WSR-000110\nRequirement  : Must remove all export ciphers and weak algorithms.\nSeverity     : CAT II\n\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: EXPORT Cipher Detection\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [PASS] EXPORT ciphers rejected by server\n\nCheck 2: NULL Cipher Detection\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [PASS] NULL ciphers rejected by server\n\nCheck 3: Weak Cipher Suite Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   Active cipher information:\n     New, TLSv1.3, Cipher is TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384\n     Server public key is 2048 bit\n     Secure Renegotiation IS NOT supported\n     Compression: NONE\n     Expansion: NONE\n     No ALPN negotiated\n     Early data was not sent\n     Verify return code: 18 (self-signed certificate)\n     ---\n     DONE\n     ---\n     --\n         Cipher    : TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384\n         Session-ID: F8E794333EFEC8A141FC4292398001DB4606BAAE9E8A077CCDE952CB86D935B0\n         Session-ID-ctx: \n   [PASS] No weak cipher patterns detected\n   [FOUND] Strong cipher suites present (ECDHE, AES-256, ChaCha20)\n\nCheck 4: Node.js Cipher Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   Config file found: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n   [INFO] No explicit cipher config - using Node.js defaults\n   Node.js default: Excludes EXPORT/NULL/weak ciphers (modern versions)\n   Node.js version: v20.18.3\n   [PASS] Node.js version excludes EXPORT/NULL ciphers by default\n\nAssessment:\n\n   XO web server has removed all export and weak ciphers.\n   Evidence:\n     - EXPORT ciphers: Rejected\n     - NULL ciphers: Rejected\n     - Strong ciphers: Active (ECDHE, AES-256, ChaCha20)\n     - Weak algorithms: Not detected\n\n   STIG requirement: SATISFIED\n\n   Technical basis: Modern cipher suites prevent cryptographic\n   weaknesses that could compromise confidentiality and integrity."},{"group_id_src":"V-206441","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206441","title":"SRG-APP-000441","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206441","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during preparation for transmission.","rule_id_src":"SV-206441r961638_rule","rule_id":"SV-206441r961638","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000441-WSR-000181","rule_title":"The web server must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during preparation for transmission.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during preparation for transmission.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to determine if the web server maintains the confidentiality and integrity of information during preparation before transmission.\n\nIf the confidentiality and integrity are not maintained, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information can be either unintentionally or maliciously disclosed or modified during preparation for transmission, including, for example, during aggregation, at protocol transformation points, and during packing/unpacking. These unauthorized disclosures or modifications compromise the confidentiality or integrity of the information.\n\nAn example of this would be an SMTP queue. This queue may be added to a web server through an SMTP module to enhance error reporting or to allow developers to add SMTP functionality to their applications. \n\nAny modules used by the web server that queue data before transmission must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of the information before the data is transmitted.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70267","V-56013"],"ccis":["CCI-002420"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"88f00e19-acb4-4295-a83e-e7e67ca0dd70","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check could not conclusively verify that Xen Orchestra maintains confidentiality and integrity of information DURING preparation for transmission (before TLS encryption begins), per STIG SRG-APP-000002-WSR-000002.\n\nThis check requires manual code review and architectural analysis that cannot be fully automated. Verification required for:\n\n(1) SOURCE CODE REVIEW (XO development team or Vates support):\n    - Examine session token generation (crypto/randomBytes usage in XO)\n    - Confirm no sensitive data logged before encryption\n    - Verify buffer overflow protections\n    - Check for timing attacks on cryptographic operations\n    - Review error handling to ensure no plaintext in error messages\n\n(2) SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE REVIEW:\n    - Verify ASLR enabled: cat /proc/sys/kernel/randomize_va_space (should be 2 or 3)\n    - Confirm no unencrypted swap: swapon -s | grep -i crypt (should show LUKS)\n    - Verify memory protection: dmesg | grep \"Kernel/User page tables isolation\"\n    - Check Linux kernel hardening: cat /proc/cmdline | grep \"smep\\|smap\"\n\n(3) SYSTEM HARDENING VERIFICATION:\n    - SELinux/AppArmor status for xo-server process\n    - File permissions on config files (should be 600 or 640)\n    - No world-readable XO configuration files\n\n(4) ORGANIZATIONAL DOCUMENTATION:\n    - Security architecture diagram\n    - Code review results (signed by architect)\n    - Incident response plan for compromised XO systems\n    - Data protection policy during preparation\n\nRemediation process:\n\n(a) Contact Vates support for XO security architecture documentation\n(b) Request code review results for current XO version\n(c) Implement system hardening controls identified above\n(d) Document findings in security plan\n\nThis finding requires ISSO/ISSM review and documentation of cryptographic controls during data preparation phase.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 4118F9599AF463DF11E6380A3F1B24A78B5B2D25\n~~~~~\nVuln ID      : V-206441\nRule ID      : SV-206441r961704_rule\nSTIG ID      : SRG-APP-000416-WSR-000118\nRequirement  : Must maintain confidentiality of controlled information during preparation for transmission.\nSeverity     : CAT II\n\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: TLS Handshake Verification\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [SUCCESS] TLS handshake established before data transmission\n   Handshake details:\n     New, TLSv1.3, Cipher is TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384\n     Post-Handshake New Session Ticket arrived:\n         Cipher    : TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384\n         Session-ID: 21B16913F06D85A210AA3B7527998F2F96C1844DFB076B1E0BED444CE2EFA9E7\n         Session-ID-ctx: \n\nCheck 2: Application-Level Encryption\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   Config file found: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n   [FOUND] Encryption configuration detected\n\nCheck 3: Pre-Transmission Data Protection\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] XO server process running\n   XO Architecture: Express.js with Node.js TLS/SSL stack\n   Data Protection Mechanisms:\n     - TLS handshake: Established before any application data transmission\n     - Express.js: Buffers data until TLS connection ready\n     - Node.js crypto: Encrypts data in preparation buffers before network transmission\n     - Session data: Encrypted by TLS layer before leaving server\n\nCheck 4: Code Review Documentation Requirement\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   This check requires organizational verification:\n     1. Review XO application code for data handling before transmission\n     2. Verify no plaintext data written to temporary buffers\n     3. Confirm TLS encryption applied before any network I/O\n     4. Document XO's use of Node.js TLS stream encryption\n\n   Evidence needed:\n     - Code review showing Express.js middleware enforces HTTPS\n     - Documentation of Node.js TLS implementation\n     - Verification that no plaintext data exposed during preparation phase\n\nAssessment:\n\n   Automated check results:\n     - TLS handshake: Verified (encryption established before data transmission)\n     - Application encryption: Configuration present\n\n   STIG Requirement: Organizational verification required\n   This check cannot be fully automated. Manual verification must confirm:\n     1. Application code review shows no plaintext exposure during preparation\n     2. TLS encryption applied before data leaves server memory buffers\n     3. No temporary files or logs contain unencrypted controlled information\n     4. XO development documentation addresses pre-transmission encryption\n\n   Recommended Actions:\n     1. Request code review documentation from Vates (XO developers)\n     2. Verify Node.js TLS implementation (inherently encrypts before transmission)\n     3. Review XO logs for any plaintext sensitive data exposure\n     4. Document organizational acceptance of Express.js/Node.js TLS architecture\n\n   Status: Open (requires organizational verification and documentation)"},{"group_id_src":"V-206442","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206442","title":"SRG-APP-000442","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206442","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during reception.","rule_id_src":"SV-206442r961641_rule","rule_id":"SV-206442r961641","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000442-WSR-000182","rule_title":"The web server must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during reception.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to utilize a transmission method that maintains the confidentiality and integrity of information during reception.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review web server configuration to determine if the server is using a transmission method that maintains the confidentiality and integrity of information during reception.\n\nIf a transmission method is not being used that maintains the confidentiality and integrity of the data during reception, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information can be either unintentionally or maliciously disclosed or modified during reception, including, for example, during aggregation, at protocol transformation points, and during packing/unpacking. These unauthorized disclosures or modifications compromise the confidentiality or integrity of the information.\n\nProtecting the confidentiality and integrity of received information requires that application servers take measures to employ approved cryptography in order to protect the information during transmission over the network. This is usually achieved through the use of Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSL VPN, or IPsec tunnel. \n\nThe web server must utilize approved encryption when receiving transmitted data.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70269","V-56015"],"ccis":["CCI-002422"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"55102e4f-03ab-455b-9e78-f911dcb7b58c","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check could not conclusively verify that Xen Orchestra maintains confidentiality and integrity of information DURING reception (after TLS decryption), per STIG SRG-APP-000003-WSR-000003.\n\nThis check requires manual code review and architectural analysis that cannot be fully automated. Verification required for:\n\n(1) CRYPTOGRAPHIC MODULE REVIEW (XO development team or Vates support):\n    - Verify Node.js OpenSSL bindings are current and patched\n    - Confirm TLS decryption is performed by system crypto (not custom code)\n    - Review request body parsing for buffer overflow vulnerabilities\n    - Check for timing attacks in decryption/authentication\n    - Verify authenticated encryption (AEAD ciphers) to ensure integrity\n\n(2) DATA HANDLING DURING RECEPTION:\n    - Examine request body handling to ensure data not written to disk unencrypted\n    - Verify express.json() middleware uses secure parsing\n    - Check for proper error handling (no decrypted data in error responses)\n    - Confirm session reconstruction uses authenticated tokens\n    - Review file upload handling (temp files with restricted permissions)\n\n(3) SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE VERIFICATION:\n    - Confirm ASLR enabled for process memory layout randomization\n    - Verify DEP/NX enabled for stack non-execution\n    - Check kernel hardening: cat /proc/cmdline | grep \"smep\\|smap\"\n    - Review process capabilities: getcap /opt/xo/xo-server/bin/xo-server (should be minimal)\n    - Verify AppArmor/SELinux profile for xo-server process\n\n(4) SUPPORTING SYSTEM HARDENING:\n    - Encrypted swap: swapon -s | grep -i crypt (should show /dev/mapper/*)\n    - File permissions on request temp directories (should be 700, owned by xo-server)\n    - Core dump restrictions: cat /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern (should reject core dumps or encrypt)\n    - No ptrace access to xo-server: /proc/sys/kernel/ptrace_scope = 2 or 3\n\n(5) ORGANIZATIONAL DOCUMENTATION:\n    - Security architecture documentation\n    - Code review results for data reception handling\n    - Cryptographic module certification (OpenSSL FIPS mode if required)\n    - Data protection policy\n\nRemediation process:\n\n(a) Request XO security architecture documentation from Vates\n(b) Obtain code review for data reception functions\n(c) Implement system hardening controls identified above\n(d) Document findings in organizational security plan\n\nThis finding requires ISSO/ISSM review and documentation of cryptographic controls during data reception phase.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: C4A1FA23A26825E288774EF43E87A2863A025447\n~~~~~\nVuln ID      : V-206442\nRule ID      : SV-206442r961830_rule\nSTIG ID      : SRG-APP-000441-WSR-000181\nRequirement  : Must maintain confidentiality of controlled information during reception.\nSeverity     : CAT II\n\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: TLS Decryption Verification\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [SUCCESS] TLS connection established with proper decryption\n   Connection details:\n     Verify return code: 18 (self-signed certificate)\n     Post-Handshake New Session Ticket arrived:\n     SSL-Session:\n         Protocol  : TLSv1.3\n         Session-ID: F00AE92E062C20EADCB05788BEEA9D1A544598DFD7B9A4E9AF4EA7109D2D8557\n\nCheck 2: Post-Reception Data Handling\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] XO server process running\n   XO Architecture: Express.js with Node.js TLS/SSL stack\n   Post-Reception Mechanisms:\n     - TLS layer: Decrypts received data immediately upon reception\n     - Node.js buffers: Decrypted data held in memory (not written to disk)\n     - Express.js middleware: Processes decrypted data in secure context\n     - Application layer: Data available only after TLS decryption\n\nCheck 3: Reception Buffer Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   Config file found: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n   [PASS] No plaintext HTTP reception detected\n\nCheck 4: Application Data Flow Documentation\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   This check requires organizational verification:\n     1. Review XO application code for data handling after reception\n     2. Verify decrypted data not written to unprotected storage\n     3. Confirm no logging of plaintext sensitive data\n     4. Document XO's use of Node.js TLS stream decryption\n\n   Evidence needed:\n     - Code review showing Express.js middleware handles decrypted data securely\n     - Documentation of Node.js TLS buffer handling\n     - Verification that no plaintext data exposed after reception phase\n     - Review of application logs to ensure no sensitive data leakage\n\nAssessment:\n\n   Automated check results:\n     - TLS decryption: Verified (data decrypted securely after reception)\n     - Post-reception handling: Node.js TLS stack provides secure buffer handling\n     - Data flow: HTTPS enforced (no plaintext reception)\n\n   STIG Requirement: Organizational verification required\n   This check cannot be fully automated. Manual verification must confirm:\n     1. Application code review shows secure handling of decrypted data\n     2. No plaintext sensitive data written to disk after reception\n     3. No application logs contain unencrypted controlled information\n     4. XO development documentation addresses post-reception data protection\n\n   Recommended Actions:\n     1. Request code review documentation from Vates (XO developers)\n     2. Verify Node.js TLS implementation (decrypts data securely in memory)\n     3. Review XO logs for any plaintext sensitive data after reception\n     4. Document organizational acceptance of Express.js/Node.js TLS architecture\n     5. Ensure no DEBUG logging modes expose decrypted data\n\n   Status: Open (requires organizational verification and documentation)"},{"group_id_src":"V-206443","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206443","title":"SRG-APP-000456","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206443","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must install security-relevant software updates within 30 days unless the time period is directed by an authoritative source (e.g., IAVM, CTOs, DTMs, STIGs).","rule_id_src":"SV-206443r1138080_rule","rule_id":"SV-206443r1138080","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000456-WSR-000187","rule_title":"The web server must install security-relevant software updates within 30 days unless the time period is directed by an authoritative source (e.g., IAVM, CTOs, DTMs, STIGs).","fix_text":"Install security-relevant web server updates within 30 days unless the time period is directed by an authoritative source (e.g., IAVM, CTOs, DTMs, STIGs).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server installs security-relevant software updates within 30 days unless the time period is directed by an authoritative source (e.g., IAVM, CTOs, DTMs, STIGs).\n\nIf security-relevant software updates to the web server are not installed within 30 days, unless the time period is directed by an authoritative source, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Security flaws with software applications are discovered daily. Vendors are constantly updating and patching their products to address newly discovered security vulnerabilities. Organizations (including any contractor to the organization) are required to promptly install security-relevant software updates (e.g., patches, service packs, and hot fixes). Flaws discovered during security assessments, continuous monitoring, incident response activities, or information system error handling must also be addressed expeditiously. \n\nThe web server will be configured to check for and install security-relevant software updates from an authoritative source within an identified time period from the availability of the update. By default, this time period will be every 24 hours.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70287","V-56033"],"ccis":["CCI-002605"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"aa95ede1-2df4-4f31-b2b4-ceb9b4ec15c1","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\n\nXO WebSRG V-206443 (CAT II): Security updates are available and must be installed.\n\nFINDING DETAILS:\nThe automated check identified available security updates requiring installation.\n\nREQUIRED ACTIONS:\n1. Review Available Updates:\n   - OS security updates: apt list --upgradable | grep -i security\n   - XO vulnerabilities: cd /opt/xo/xo-server && npm audit\n   - Node.js security advisories: Check Node.js release notes\n\n2. Coordinate with Stakeholders:\n   - Review change management requirements\n   - Schedule maintenance window\n   - Notify affected users of planned downtime\n   - Coordinate with Vates support for XO-specific updates\n\n3. Test Updates in Non-Production:\n   - Apply updates to test/dev environment first\n   - Verify XO functionality post-update\n   - Test critical workflows (VM operations, backups, etc.)\n   - Document any compatibility issues\n\n4. Apply Updates to Production:\n   - Operating system: sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade\n   - XO packages: cd /opt/xo/xo-server && npm audit fix\n   - Node.js runtime: Follow Vates compatibility guidance\n   - Restart services as needed: systemctl restart xo-server\n\n5. Post-Update Verification:\n   - Confirm XO web interface accessible\n   - Verify pool/host connectivity\n   - Test VM operations\n   - Review system logs for errors\n   - Re-run V-206443 check to confirm NotAFinding status\n\n6. Enable Automated Security Updates (if not configured):\n   - Install: sudo apt install unattended-upgrades\n   - Configure: /etc/apt/apt.conf.d/50unattended-upgrades\n   - Enable: sudo systemctl enable unattended-upgrades\n   - Verify: systemctl status unattended-upgrades\n\nORGANIZATIONAL CONSIDERATIONS:\n- DoD requires security patches within 30 days unless directed otherwise\n- IAVMs, CTOs, and DTMs may impose shorter timeframes\n- Document justification for any delayed updates\n- Maintain audit trail of update activities\n\nVATES-SPECIFIC GUIDANCE:\n- Check Vates security advisories: https://xen-orchestra.com/blog/\n- Review XO release notes for breaking changes\n- Consider XOA upgrade path vs XOCE manual updates\n- Coordinate breaking changes with virtualization team\n\nRISK STATEMENT:\nUnpatched vulnerabilities expose the virtualization management platform to potential exploitation. As XO controls the entire XCP-ng infrastructure, compromise could affect all hosted VMs and sensitive workloads.\n\nThis finding should be escalated to ISSM/ISSO for risk assessment and mitigation planning.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 9288CCE555EDA44499C133EE94C5923BD5509B0F\n~~~~~\nCAT II / Medium - V-206443: Security patches and updates must be installed and up to date.\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nCheck 1: Node.js Runtime Security Status\n\n   Current Node.js version: v20.18.3\n   [WARN] Outdated global npm packages detected:\n   corepack    0.30.0  0.34.6  0.34.6  node_modules/corepack   global node       20.18.3  25.6.0  25.6.0  node_modules/node       global npm         10.8.3  11.9.0  11.9.0  node_modules/npm        global xo-server  5.194.6   5.7.4   5.7.4  node_modules/xo-server  global xo-web     5.191.3  5.7.10  5.7.10  node_modules/xo-web     global\n\nCheck 2: Operating System Security Updates\n\n   Operating system: No updates available\n\nCheck 3: Xen Orchestra Application Security\n\n   [WARN] XO Server directory not found at /opt/xo/xo-server\n\nCheck 4: Automated Security Update Configuration\n\n   Unattended-upgrades: ENABLED\n   Service status: active\n   Automatic security updates: CONFIGURED\n\nCheck 5: Recent Update Activity\n\n   Last apt activity: Could not determine\n\nAssessment:\n\n   [FINDING] Security updates are available and must be installed\n   Manual actions required:\n   1. Review available OS security updates: apt list --upgradable | grep -i security\n   2. Apply OS security patches: sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade\n   3. Review XO vulnerabilities: cd /opt/xo/xo-server && npm audit\n   4. Update XO packages: npm audit fix (test in non-production first)\n   5. Consider enabling unattended-upgrades for automated security updates\n   6. Coordinate with Vates support for XO-specific updates"},{"group_id_src":"V-206444","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206444","title":"SRG-APP-000516","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206444","severity":"medium","group_title":"All accounts installed with the web server software and tools must have passwords assigned and default passwords changed.","rule_id_src":"SV-206444r961863_rule","rule_id":"SV-206444r961863","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000516-WSR-000079","rule_title":"All accounts installed with the web server software and tools must have passwords assigned and default passwords changed.","fix_text":"Set passwords for non-service/system accounts containing no passwords and change the passwords for accounts which still have default passwords.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployment configuration to determine what non-service/system accounts were installed by the web server installation process.\n\nVerify the passwords for these accounts have been set and/or changed from the default passwords.\n\nIf these accounts still have no password or default passwords, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"During installation of the web server software, accounts are created for the web server to operate properly. The accounts installed can have either no password installed or a default password, which will be known and documented by the vendor and the user community.\n\nThe first things an attacker will try when presented with a login screen are the default user identifiers with default passwords. Installed applications may also install accounts with no password, making the login even easier. Once the web server is installed, the passwords for any created accounts should be changed and documented. The new passwords must meet the requirements for all passwords, i.e., upper/lower characters, numbers, special characters, time until change, reuse policy, etc. \n\nService accounts or system accounts that have no login capability do not need to have passwords set or changed.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70241","V-55987"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"c72cb2c2-6ccb-4c9c-b767-dcf5e4da73d5","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nDefault accounts or empty passwords detected. REMEDIATION REQUIRED:\n\n1. Change default XO admin password:\n   xo-cli --register http://xo-server admin@admin.net newPassword123!\n\n2. Remove/disable default accounts (if found):\n   For system accounts: passwd -l [account-name]\n   For XO accounts: Use XO web UI to delete or disable\n\n3. Verify all accounts have strong passwords:\n   awk -F: '($2 == \"\" || $2 == \"*\" || $2 == \"!\") {print $1}' /etc/shadow\n\n4. Configure password complexity requirements (see V-264353)\n\n5. Document password change procedures in organizational policy\n\nRe-run scan after remediation.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 4156968409091FD4CA70A4001DD0D39A87B2CD0C\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-206444: Password Assignment & Default Password Changes\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: XO User Accounts Detection (via REST API)\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [INFO] No API token available - cannot check XO user accounts\n  [INFO] Manual verification required for XO user account passwords\n\nCheck 2: System Account Password Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [PASS] No accounts with empty passwords detected\n  [INFO] 5 locked account(s) detected (secure state)\n\nCheck 3: Default Account Detection\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [PASS] No common default accounts detected\n\nCheck 4: Password Hash Verification\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [INFO] 0 account(s) with password hashes\n  [INFO] Hash algorithms: SHA-256 ($5), SHA-512 ($6), yescrypt ($y), bcrypt ($2)\n  [WARN] Accounts with weak/legacy hash algorithms detected\n\nCheck 5: LDAP/External Authentication Detection\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [INFO] No LDAP/external authentication detected - local passwords required\n\nCheck 6: XO Service Account Validation\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [FOUND] XO process owner: root\n  [PASS] Service account is locked (secure configuration)\n\n================================================================================\nASSESSMENT\n================================================================================\n\nMANUAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED\n\nFinding: Unable to verify XO user account passwords (no API access)\n\nRequired Verification:\n  1. Verify all XO user accounts have unique passwords assigned\n  2. Confirm default accounts (admin, xoa-admin) have changed passwords\n  3. Ensure service accounts are properly locked/disabled for interactive login\n  4. Review system accounts in /etc/shadow for empty password fields\n\nRemediation Steps:\n  1. Change default passwords: xo-cli user.set --email admin@example.com --password <new>\n  2. Lock unused accounts: passwd -l <username>\n  3. Remove/disable default accounts if not needed\n  4. Enable LDAP/AD authentication for centralized password management"},{"group_id_src":"V-206445","group_tree":[{"id":"V-206445","title":"SRG-APP-000516","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-206445","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must be configured in accordance with the security configuration settings based on DoD security configuration or implementation guidance, including STIGs, NSA configuration guides, CTOs, and DTMs.","rule_id_src":"SV-206445r961863_rule","rule_id":"SV-206445r961863","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000516-WSR-000174","rule_title":"The web server must be configured in accordance with the security configuration settings based on DoD security configuration or implementation guidance, including STIGs, NSA configuration guides, CTOs, and DTMs.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to be configured according to DoD security configuration guidance.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the web server documentation and deployed configuration to determine if web server is configured in accordance with the security configuration settings based on DoD security configuration or implementation guidance.\n\nIf the web server is not configured according to the guidance, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Configuring the web server to implement organization-wide security implementation guides and security checklists guarantees compliance with federal standards and establishes a common security baseline across the DoD that reflects the most restrictive security posture consistent with operational requirements. \n\nConfiguration settings are the set of parameters that can be changed that affect the security posture and/or functionality of the system. Security-related parameters are those parameters impacting the security state of the web server, including the parameters required to satisfy other security control requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70239","V-55985"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"61da487c-97a9-4523-a9bb-23a601586a17","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 4C6E7D8C9A991DA7F4C9CE65C0DCA4B51304D2EE\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-206445: DoD Baseline Configuration Compliance\n================================================================================\n\nREQUIREMENT:\nThe Xen Orchestra web server must be configured in accordance with DoD security\nconfiguration settings based on DoD security configuration or implementation guidance,\nincluding STIGs, NSA configuration guides, CTOs, and DTMs.\n\nAUTOMATED CONFIGURATION DISCOVERY:\n--------------------------------------------------\n\nCheck 1: Configuration Management System\n\n   [NOT FOUND] No configuration management system detected\n   [INFO] Manual configuration management may be in use\n\nCheck 2: XO Configuration Files\n\n   [FOUND] /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n   Permissions: 644 root:root\n\nCheck 3: Security Hardening Evidence\n\n   [FOUND] /etc/security/limits.conf (last modified: 2023-09-21)\n   [FOUND] /etc/sysctl.conf (last modified: 2022-12-19)\n   [FOUND] /etc/ssh/sshd_config (last modified: 2026-01-30)\n   [FOUND] /etc/pam.d/common-auth (last modified: 2026-01-26)\n\nCheck 4: Baseline Documentation Discovery\n\n   [NOT FOUND] No baseline documentation found in common locations\n\nCheck 5: Compliance Automation Tools\n\n   [NOT FOUND] No automated compliance scanning tools detected\n\nCheck 6: Compliance Scan Evidence\n\n   [NOT FOUND] No compliance scan logs found in /var/log\n\n================================================================================\nDOD BASELINE CONFIGURATION ASSESSMENT\n================================================================================\n\nAUTOMATED CHECK COMPLETE - MANUAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED\n\nThe automated check has discovered the current configuration state but CANNOT\ndetermine compliance with DoD baseline requirements. Manual ISSO/ISSM review is\nrequired to verify adherence to organizational security configuration baselines.\n\nMANDATORY MANUAL VERIFICATION:\n\n1. DOD STIG COMPLIANCE:\n   - Verify XO configuration matches Web Server SRG V4R4 requirements\n   - Confirm all applicable STIG controls are implemented or documented as N/A\n   - Review deviation requests for any non-compliant settings\n   - Verify STIG compliance scan results (OpenSCAP, Nessus, SCAP, etc.)\n\n2. NSA CONFIGURATION GUIDES:\n   - Verify adherence to NSA Cybersecurity Technical Reports (CTRs)\n   - Review NSA hardening guidance for Debian 12 and Node.js applications\n   - Confirm secure defaults per NSA recommendations\n\n3. CYBER TASKING ORDERS (CTOs):\n   - Identify applicable CTOs from USCYBERCOM/JFHQ-DODIN\n   - Verify compliance with time-sensitive security directives\n   - Document CTO implementation or waiver status\n\n4. DoD TECHNICAL MEMORANDA (DTMs):\n   - Review applicable DTMs for web servers and virtualization management\n   - Verify compliance with DTM requirements\n   - Document organizational interpretation of DTM guidance\n\n5. ORGANIZATIONAL SECURITY BASELINE:\n   - Confirm configuration matches organization's approved security baseline\n   - Review Configuration Control Board (CCB) approval records\n   - Verify change management documentation for baseline deviations\n   - Validate periodic baseline compliance reviews are conducted\n\nREQUIRED EVIDENCE FOR AUDITOR:\n\nSystem Owner/ISSO must provide:\n- Approved security configuration baseline document for XO web server\n- STIG compliance scan results (SCAP, Nessus, manual checklist, etc.)\n- NSA configuration guide compliance matrix\n- Applicable CTO compliance documentation\n- Configuration Change Control Board (CCB) approval records\n- Deviation requests and waiver approvals (if any)\n- Periodic compliance review reports\n- Configuration management system reports (if automated)\n\nCOMPLIANCE RESOURCES:\n- Web Server SRG: https://public.cyber.mil/stigs/downloads/\n- NSA Cybersecurity: https://www.nsa.gov/ia/guidance\n- DoD CTO Repository: SIPRNET USCYBERCOM portal (access restricted)\n- RMF Knowledge Service: https://rmfks.osd.mil/ (CAC required)\n\nNON-COMPLIANCE RISK:\nFailure to configure the web server according to DoD security baselines increases\nthe attack surface and may result in unauthorized access, data compromise, or\nfailure to detect/prevent malicious activity. Non-compliance with DoD guidance\nmay also prevent system accreditation and result in ATO denial."},{"group_id_src":"V-239371","group_tree":[{"id":"V-239371","title":"SRG-APP-000416","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-239371","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must implement required cryptographic protections using cryptographic modules complying with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, standards, and guidance when encrypting data that must be compartmentalized.","rule_id_src":"SV-239371r1117186_rule","rule_id":"SV-239371r1117186","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000416-WSR-000118","rule_title":"The web server must implement required cryptographic protections using cryptographic modules complying with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, standards, and guidance when encrypting data that must be compartmentalized.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to utilize cryptography when protecting compartmentalized data.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review policy documents to identify data that is compartmentalized (i.e. classified, sensitive, need-to-know, etc.) and requires cryptographic protection.\n\nReview the web server documentation and deployed configuration to identify the encryption modules utilized to protect the compartmentalized data.\n\nIf the encryption modules used to protect the compartmentalized data are not compliant with the data, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Cryptography is only as strong as the encryption modules/algorithms employed to encrypt the data. \r\n\r\nUse of weak or untested encryption algorithms undermines the purposes of utilizing encryption to protect data. \r\n\r\nNSA has developed Type 1 algorithms for protecting classified information. The Committee on National Security Systems (CNSS) National Information Assurance Glossary (CNSS Instruction No. 4009) defines Type 1 products as:\r\n\r\n\"Cryptographic equipment, assembly or component classified or certified by NSA for encrypting and decrypting classified and sensitive national security information when appropriately keyed. Developed using established NSA business processes and containing NSA-approved algorithms are used to protect systems requiring the most stringent protection mechanisms.\"\r\n\r\nAlthough persons may have a security clearance, they may not have a \"need-to-know\" and are required to be separated from the information in question. The web server must employ NSA-approved cryptography to protect classified information from those individuals who have no \"need-to-know\" or when encryption of compartmentalized data is required by data classification.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-70271","V-56017"],"ccis":["CCI-002450"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"b1bb3dec-e99a-4970-baeb-9258b9f325f3","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that Xen Orchestra is NOT using FIPS-validated cryptographic modules, violating STIG SRG-APP-000289-WSR-000071 requirements for compartmentalized data encryption in DoD Classified environments.\n\nThis is a CRITICAL finding if this system will handle DoD Classified information. FIPS 140 compliance is mandatory for:\n- DoD Secret/Top Secret data protection\n- Key derivation functions\n- Cryptographic algorithm selection\n- Cryptographic module certification\n\nNon-compliance findings:\n- OpenSSL FIPS mode not enabled\n- Non-FIPS algorithms in use (MD5, SHA1, RC4, DES)\n- Node.js crypto module not linked to FIPS OpenSSL\n- Cryptographic module not NIST-certified\n\nRemediation steps:\n\n(1) Verify current cryptographic configuration:\n    node -e \"console.log(require('crypto').constants)\"\n    openssl version -a  # Should show \"FIPS\" in output\n\n(2) Install OpenSSL FIPS module (if not present):\n    # For RHEL/CentOS/Debian:\n    apt-get install libssl1.0.0-fips  # Debian\n    yum install openssl-fips  # RHEL/CentOS\n\n    # Verify FIPS module: /usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/engines-1.1/fips.so\n\n(3) Enable FIPS mode in Linux kernel:\n    # Check current status:\n    cat /proc/sys/crypto/fips_enabled\n\n    # Enable FIPS (requires dracut-fips package):\n    fips-mode-setup --enable\n\n    # Reboot to activate:\n    systemctl reboot\n\n    # Verify after reboot:\n    cat /proc/sys/crypto/fips_enabled  # Should show 1\n\n(4) Rebuild Node.js with FIPS support (if needed):\n    # XO may need Node.js rebuilt with FIPS module support\n    # Contact Vates for FIPS-enabled XO builds\n\n    # Check if current Node.js supports FIPS:\n    node -e \"console.log('FIPS:', process.versions.openssl.includes('fips'))\"\n\n(5) Update XO configuration to use only FIPS algorithms:\n    # Edit /opt/xo/xo-server/config.toml\n    [http.tls]\n    ciphers = \"ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384\"  # FIPS only\n    minVersion = \"TLSv1.2\"\n\n(6) Verify FIPS algorithms in use:\n    openssl list -cipher-algorithms | grep -i \"aes-256\\|sha256\\|ecdsa\"\n    openssl list -digest-algorithms | grep -E \"sha(256|384|512)\" # Only these allowed\n\n(7) Validate FIPS compliance:\n    # Test that non-FIPS algorithms fail:\n    echo -n \"test\" | openssl md5  # Should fail: \"Digital Envelope routines error\"\n    echo -n \"test\" | openssl sha256  # Should work\n\n    # Test FIPS TLS:\n    openssl s_client -connect [XO_IP]:443 -cipher \"AES256-GCM\" 2>/dev/null | grep Cipher\n\n(8) Document FIPS configuration:\n    - Cryptographic module certification (OpenSSL FIPS 2.0 #1747)\n    - FIPS mode enablement procedures\n    - Approved algorithm list\n    - Key management procedures\n    - Incident response for FIPS module failure\n\nORGANIZATIONAL DECISION REQUIRED:\n- If handling DoD Classified data: FIPS mode MUST be enabled\n- If handling Unclassified data: FIPS mode recommended but not mandatory\n- If FIPS mode cannot be enabled: System cannot be used for Classified data\n\nContact Vates support for FIPS-enabled XO builds and deployment procedures.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 6795BC3EBC952E24C093BB97BED7A972DD3EC24A\n~~~~~\nVuln ID      : V-239371\nRule ID      : SV-239371r961146_rule\nSTIG ID      : SRG-APP-000514-WSR-000078\nRequirement  : Must use FIPS 140-2+ cryptographic modules for remote access sessions.\nSeverity     : CAT II\n\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: Node.js FIPS Mode Detection\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] XO server process running\n   [NOT FOUND] --force-fips flag not detected in Node.js process\n   Note: FIPS mode is typically required only for classified data environments\n\nCheck 2: System-Wide FIPS Mode\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   System FIPS status: 0\n   [NOT FOUND] System-wide FIPS mode is DISABLED\n   Note: This is typical for Unclassified/FOUO data environments\n\nCheck 3: OpenSSL FIPS Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   OpenSSL version information:\n     OpenSSL 3.0.18 30 Sep 2025 (Library: OpenSSL 3.0.18 30 Sep 2025)\n     built on: Sat Jan 24 15:01:59 2026 UTC\n     platform: debian-amd64\n     options:  bn(64,64)\n     compiler: gcc -fPIC -pthread -m64 -Wa,--noexecstack -Wall -fzero-call-used-regs=used-gpr -DOPENSSL_TLS_SECURITY_LEVEL=2 -Wa,--noexecstack -g -O2 -ffile-prefix-map=/build/reproducible-path/openssl-3.0.18=. -fstack-protector-strong -Wformat -Werror=format-security -DOPENSSL_USE_NODELETE -DL_ENDIAN -DOPENSSL_PIC -DOPENSSL_BUILDING_OPENSSL -DNDEBUG -Wdate-time -D_FORTIFY_SOURCE=2\n   [NOT FOUND] OpenSSL FIPS support not explicitly detected\n\nCheck 4: Node.js Crypto FIPS API\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   [SKIP] Unable to query Node.js crypto.getFips() API\n\nFIPS 140-2 Context for Xen Orchestra:\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n   Node.js FIPS Mode Requirements:\n     - Requires OpenSSL compiled with FIPS module\n     - Must start Node.js with --force-fips flag\n     - System-wide FIPS mode (echo 1 > /proc/sys/crypto/fips_enabled)\n     - Validated cryptographic module (NIST CMVP listing)\n\n   Typical DoD Classifications:\n     - Unclassified/FOUO: FIPS mode NOT typically required\n     - Classified (Secret/Top Secret): FIPS mode REQUIRED\n     - SBU/CUI: May require FIPS depending on data owner guidance\n\nAssessment:\n\n   FIPS mode not detected - this is EXPECTED for Unclassified data environments.\n   Evidence:\n     - Node.js FIPS mode: NOT ENABLED\n     - System FIPS mode: NOT ENABLED\n\n   Risk Assessment:\n     - For Unclassified/FOUO data: ACCEPTABLE (FIPS not required)\n     - For Classified data: NOT ACCEPTABLE (FIPS REQUIRED)\n     - For CUI/SBU: Consult data owner for FIPS requirement\n\n   If FIPS is required for your environment:\n     1. Enable system FIPS mode:\n        sudo fips-mode-setup --enable (RHEL/CentOS)\n     2. Configure Node.js FIPS mode:\n        Edit /etc/systemd/system/xo-server.service:\n        Environment=\"NODE_OPTIONS=--force-fips\"\n     3. Restart system or services\n     4. Verify: node -e 'console.log(require(\"crypto\").getFips())' (should return 1)\n\n   Status: Open (FIPS mode not enabled - acceptable for Unclassified data)\n   Organizational decision required: Does your data classification require FIPS 140-2?"},{"group_id_src":"V-264337","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264337","title":"SRG-APP-000700","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264337","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must disable accounts when the accounts have expired.","rule_id_src":"SV-264337r984356_rule","rule_id":"SV-264337r984356","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000700-WSR-000100","rule_title":"The web server must disable accounts when the accounts have expired.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to disable accounts when the accounts have expired.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to disable accounts when the accounts have expired.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to disable accounts when the accounts have expired, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Disabling expired, inactive, or otherwise anomalous accounts supports the concepts of least privilege and least functionality which reduce the attack surface of the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-003627"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"c406b682-b26b-4cc5-9541-f0d0c89ec8fa","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nMANUAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED: Verify account expiration mechanism.\n\nVerification Steps:\n1. Check system password expiration policy: grep PASS_MAX_DAYS /etc/login.defs (should be  60)\n2. Verify user account expiration: chage -l [username] for each user account\n3. If using LDAP/AD: Verify external directory enforces account expiration\n4. Review organizational account lifecycle policy\n5. Verify automated account review process (monthly/quarterly)\n\nRemediation:\n1. Configure system expiration: Set PASS_MAX_DAYS 60 in /etc/login.defs\n2. Apply to existing accounts: chage -M 60 [username]\n3. For LDAP/AD: Configure accountExpires attribute enforcement\n4. Establish automated account review process (cron job or systemd timer)\n5. Document procedures in System Security Plan\n\nRe-run scan after configuration changes.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 77A0DE5D1716BF9B36F540D515F89C228B56FF9A\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-264337: Disable Expired Accounts\n================================================================================\n\nDoD Requirement: The web server must disable accounts when the accounts\nhave expired (automated expiration enforcement).\n\nCheck 1: System Account Expiration 