t/xo/docs/account-lifecycle.md\n  - /usr/local/share/xo/policies/accounts.txt\n  - /root/account-management-policy.txt\n\nCheck 6: Automated Account Review Process\n--------------------------------------------------\nNo automated account review jobs detected in cron.\n\nNo automated account review jobs detected in systemd timers.\n\n================================================================================\nORGANIZATIONAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED\n================================================================================\n\nThis check ALWAYS requires manual ISSO/ISSM verification of:\n\n1. Organizational account lifecycle management procedures\n2. Orphaned account identification process (accounts no longer associated to users)\n3. Account disablement procedures when users leave or change roles\n4. Periodic account review frequency (typically quarterly or annually)\n5. Documentation of account reviews and disablements\n6. Integration with HR systems for automated account lifecycle management\n\nMANUAL VERIFICATION PROCEDURES:\n\n1. Review organizational account management policy:\n   - Verify policy requires disabling accounts when users leave/change roles\n   - Verify periodic account review procedures (frequency, responsibility)\n   - Verify documentation requirements for account lifecycle events\n\n2. Cross-reference system accounts with current user lists:\n   - Obtain current organizational user roster from HR/management\n   - Compare against system accounts (from Check 2 above)\n   - Compare against XO user accounts (from Check 4 above)\n   - Identify accounts not associated with current users\n\n3. Review account activity for potential orphaned accounts:\n   - Accounts with no login >90 days (from Check 3 above)\n   - Accounts belonging to former employees\n   - Shared/generic accounts not associated with specific users\n\n4. Verify account disablement evidence:\n   - Review audit logs for account disablement events\n   - Check /etc/shadow for locked accounts (!! in password field)\n   - Verify XO user accounts match organizational user roster\n\n5. Review automated account review processes:\n   - Verify existence of automated account review scripts/jobs\n   - Review logs of periodic account reviews\n   - Verify integration with HR systems (if applicable)\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264339","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264339","title":"SRG-APP-000745","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264339","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must implement the capability to centrally review and analyze audit records from multiple components within the system.","rule_id_src":"SV-264339r984362_rule","rule_id":"SV-264339r984362","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000745-WSR-000120","rule_title":"The web server must implement the capability to centrally review and analyze audit records from multiple components within the system.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to implement the capability to centrally review and analyze audit records from multiple components within the system.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to implement the capability to centrally review and analyze audit records from multiple components within the system.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to implement the capability to centrally review and analyze audit records from multiple components within the system, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Automated mechanisms for centralized reviews and analyses include security information and event management products.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-003821"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"669778d9-994d-4fae-8fef-9aa06a98dd34","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check detected centralized logging capabilities but cannot verify security personnel perform regular centralized review of audit records.\n\nRequired Manual Verification:\n(1) Verify security personnel have access to centralized log review tools\n    - SIEM platform credentials assigned to security analysts\n    - XO logs visible in SIEM search interface\n    - Test query: Search for XO authentication events in SIEM\n    - Document security personnel with log review access\n\n(2) Verify audit records from XO web server are included in central repository\n    - Confirm XO logs forwarded to SIEM/central log server\n    - Verify log parsing: SIEM recognizes XO log format\n    - Check log completeness: All XO log sources included (Winston, systemd journal, nginx)\n    - Test correlation: SIEM can correlate XO events with other system events\n\n(3) Verify organizational procedures mandate regular centralized log review\n    - Request copy of security operations procedures\n    - Confirm log review frequency defined (daily/weekly/monthly)\n    - Verify review scope includes XO audit records\n    - Check for assigned responsibilities (who performs review)\n\n(4) Verify review frequency meets DoD/organizational requirements\n    - CNSSI 1253 guidance: High systems require daily review\n    - Moderate systems: Weekly review acceptable\n    - Low systems: Monthly review minimum\n    - Confirm current practice meets categorization requirements\n\n(5) Verify review findings are documented and acted upon\n    - Request sample log review reports\n    - Verify findings trigger incident response procedures\n    - Confirm documentation of anomalies detected\n    - Verify corrective actions taken for identified issues\n\nRemediation for missing centralized review procedures:\n\nStep 1: Document Log Review Procedures\n  1. Create security operations procedure (SOP) for log review:\n     - Purpose: Regular review of centralized audit records\n     - Scope: All systems forwarding logs to SIEM (including XO)\n     - Frequency: [Daily/weekly based on system categorization]\n     - Responsibilities: [Security analyst role]\n     - Escalation: [ISSO/ISSM notification procedures]\n\n  2. Define review checklist:\n     - Authentication failures (failed login attempts)\n     - Privilege escalations (role changes, permission modifications)\n     - Unauthorized access attempts (access denied events)\n     - System errors and anomalies\n     - Security alert review (SIEM-generated alerts)\n\n  3. Document in security plan Section [X.X]\n\nStep 2: Configure SIEM for XO Audit Record Review\n  1. Create SIEM dashboard for XO:\n     - Authentication summary (successful/failed logins)\n     - User activity timeline\n     - Error rate trends\n     - Security events (privilege changes, configuration modifications)\n\n  2. Configure saved searches for common review queries:\n     - Failed authentication attempts (last 24 hours)\n     - Privilege escalations (last 7 days)\n     - Unusual access patterns (logins from new IPs/locations)\n     - System errors requiring investigation\n\n  3. Schedule automated reports:\n     - Daily summary email to security team\n     - Weekly detailed report to ISSO\n     - Monthly trend analysis\n\nStep 3: Train Security Personnel\n  1. SIEM platform training:\n     - How to search XO logs in SIEM\n     - How to interpret XO log events\n     - How to correlate XO events with other system events\n     - How to export findings for reporting\n\n  2. Incident response training:\n     - When to escalate findings to ISSO/ISSM\n     - How to document review findings\n     - How to initiate incident response procedures\n\n  3. Document training completion\n\nStep 4: Implement Regular Review Process\n  1. Assign security analyst responsibility:\n     - Primary reviewer: [Name/role]\n     - Backup reviewer: [Name/role]\n     - Escalation contact: [ISSO/ISSM]\n\n  2. Create review schedule:\n     - Daily: Quick check of critical alerts\n     - Weekly: Detailed review of authentication and privilege events\n     - Monthly: Trend analysis and comprehensive review\n\n  3. Document review findings:\n     - Use ticketing system or log review spreadsheet\n     - Record date, reviewer, findings, actions taken\n     - Archive review reports per retention policy\n\nStep 5: Test and Validate Review Process\n  1. Perform initial comprehensive review:\n     - Review all XO logs in SIEM for past 30 days\n     - Document baseline (normal activity patterns)\n     - Identify any existing security issues\n\n  2. Perform test incident simulation:\n     - Generate test security event (e.g., failed login attempts)\n     - Verify event appears in SIEM\n     - Verify review process detects event\n     - Verify escalation procedures work\n\n  3. Validate review completeness:\n     - Confirm all XO log sources reviewed\n     - Verify no log gaps or missing data\n     - Test log retention and retrieval\n\nRe-run scan after centralized review procedures documented and implemented.\n\nNote: DoD requires centralized review and analysis of audit records from multiple system components per NIST SP 800-53r5 AU-6(1). Simply forwarding logs to SIEM is insufficient; security personnel must actively review logs and respond to findings.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 368859D7400B1D79F83F65CB8F9BA7B8364FD885\n~~~~~\n=== Centralized Audit Record Review and Analysis Check ===\n\nDoD Requirement: Security personnel must be able to centrally review and analyze\naudit records from multiple components within the system.\n\n1. Centralized Log Aggregation (rsyslog/syslog-ng Remote Logging):\n   [NOT DETECTED] No rsyslog remote logging found\n\n2. SIEM/Log Management Platform (Splunk, Elastic Beats, Fluentd):\n   [NOT DETECTED] No SIEM/log management agents found\n\n3. Log Search and Analysis Tools:\n   [AVAILABLE] grep command-line tool\n   [AVAILABLE] journalctl (systemd journal query tool)\n\n4. Audit Log Forwarding to Central Server:\n   [NOT DETECTED] No XO-specific audit forwarding found\n   [DETECTED] systemd-journal-upload service active\n   [DETECTED] systemd-journal-remote service active (receiving logs)\n\n5. Scheduled Log Review Procedures (Automated Scripts/Jobs):\n   [NOT DETECTED] No log review cron jobs found\n   [NOT DETECTED] No automated log review procedures found\n\n=== Summary ===\nLog Aggregation: NOT DETECTED\nSIEM Platform: NOT DETECTED\nAnalysis Tools: DETECTED\nAudit Forwarding: DETECTED\nScheduled Review: NOT DETECTED\n\nFINDING: This is an ORGANIZATIONAL POLICY check.\n\nThe automated check detected the following centralized logging capabilities:\n- 2 of 5 capability areas detected\n\nHowever, ISSO/ISSM verification is REQUIRED to confirm:\n1. Security personnel have access to centralized log review tools\n2. Audit records from XO web server are included in central repository\n3. Organizational procedures mandate regular centralized log review\n4. Review frequency meets DoD/organizational requirements\n5. Review findings are documented and acted upon\n\nManual Verification Required:\n- Request copy of centralized log review procedures\n- Verify XO audit logs are forwarded to SIEM/central log server\n- Confirm security personnel perform regular review of centralized logs\n- Review log analysis reports and incident response actions\n- Validate review frequency aligns with CNSSI 1253 guidance"},{"group_id_src":"V-264340","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264340","title":"SRG-APP-000795","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264340","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must alert organization-defined personnel or roles upon detection of unauthorized access, modification, or deletion of audit information.","rule_id_src":"SV-264340r984365_rule","rule_id":"SV-264340r984365","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000795-WSR-000130","rule_title":"The web server must alert organization-defined personnel or roles upon detection of unauthorized access, modification, or deletion of audit information.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to alert organization-defined personnel or roles upon detection of unauthorized access, modification, or deletion of audit information.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to alert organization-defined personnel or roles upon detection of unauthorized access, modification, or deletion of audit information.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to alert organization-defined personnel or roles upon detection of unauthorized access, modification, or deletion of audit information, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Audit information includes all information needed to successfully audit system activity, such as audit records, audit log settings, audit reports, and personally identifiable information. Audit logging tools are those programs and devices used to conduct system audit and logging activities. Protection of audit information focuses on technical protection and limits the ability to access and execute audit logging tools to authorized individuals. Physical protection of audit information is addressed by both media protection controls and physical and environmental protection controls.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-003831"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"6d81ba2f-7187-409d-95e2-321a5ba7693d","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check detected file protection mechanisms but cannot verify file integrity monitoring (FIM) is configured to immediately alert security personnel of unauthorized audit log changes.\n\nRequired Manual Verification:\n(1) Verify FIM tools configured to monitor ALL audit log locations\n    - XO logs: /var/log/xo-server, /opt/xo/logs (if applicable)\n    - System logs: /var/log/syslog, /var/log/auth.log\n    - Web server logs: /var/log/nginx (if applicable)\n    - Systemd journal: /var/log/journal\n    - Request FIM configuration file for review\n\n(2) Verify alert thresholds properly calibrated to detect unauthorized changes\n    - Alert on file modification (content changes)\n    - Alert on file deletion\n    - Alert on permission changes (chmod)\n    - Alert on ownership changes (chown)\n    - Test alert generation by modifying test log file\n\n(3) Verify alerting mechanisms reach designated security personnel (ISSO/SA)\n    - Confirm ISSO/SA email addresses configured in FIM tool\n    - Test alert delivery by triggering FIM check\n    - Verify alerts received within acceptable timeframe (<15 minutes)\n    - Check spam filters (alerts not blocked)\n\n(4) Verify response procedures documented and tested\n    - Request copy of incident response procedures\n    - Confirm procedures define actions for audit log tampering\n    - Verify assignment of responsibilities (who investigates)\n    - Test response process with tabletop exercise\n\n(5) Verify integration with organizational SIEM/monitoring infrastructure\n    - Confirm FIM alerts forwarded to SIEM\n    - Verify SIEM correlation rules for audit log tampering\n    - Check for automated response workflows (e.g., ticket creation)\n    - Test end-to-end alert flow (FIM > SIEM > SOC > ISSO)\n\nRemediation for missing FIM alerting:\n\nOption 1: Configure AIDE (Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment)\n  1. Install AIDE:\n     apt install aide aide-common  # Debian\n\n  2. Configure /etc/aide/aide.conf to monitor audit logs:\n     # Add monitoring rules\n     /var/log/xo-server LOG\n     /var/log/nginx LOG\n     /var/log/syslog LOG\n     /var/log/auth.log LOG\n     /var/log/journal DATAONLY\n\n     # Rule definitions\n     LOG = p+i+n+u+g+s+m+c+md5+sha256\n     DATAONLY = p+n+u+g+s+md5+sha256\n\n  3. Initialize AIDE database:\n     aideinit\n     mv /var/lib/aide/aide.db.new /var/lib/aide/aide.db\n\n  4. Create check script /usr/local/bin/aide-check-alert.sh:\n     #!/bin/bash\n     AIDE_REPORT=$(aide --check 2>&1)\n     if [ $? -ne 0 ]; then\n       echo \"$AIDE_REPORT\" | mail -s \"ALERT: Audit Log Integrity Violation on $(hostname)\" \\\n         isso@example.mil,sa@example.mil\n     fi\n\n  5. Make executable and add to cron:\n     chmod +x /usr/local/bin/aide-check-alert.sh\n     echo \"0 */4 * * * /usr/local/bin/aide-check-alert.sh\" >> /etc/crontab\n\nOption 2: Configure OSSEC (Host Intrusion Detection System)\n  1. Install OSSEC agent:\n     wget -q -O - https://updates.atomicorp.com/installers/atomic | bash\n     yum install ossec-hids-agent  # RHEL/CentOS\n     # OR\n     apt install ossec-hids-agent  # Debian\n\n  2. Configure /var/ossec/etc/ossec.conf:\n     <syscheck>\n       <frequency>300</frequency>\n       <directories check_all=\"yes\" realtime=\"yes\">/var/log/xo-server</directories>\n       <directories check_all=\"yes\" realtime=\"yes\">/var/log/nginx</directories>\n       <directories check_all=\"yes\">/var/log/syslog</directories>\n       <alert_new_files>yes</alert_new_files>\n     </syscheck>\n\n     <email_notification>\n       <email_to>isso@example.mil</email_to>\n       <email_to>sa@example.mil</email_to>\n       <smtp_server>mail.example.mil</smtp_server>\n       <email_from>ossec@xo1.example.mil</email_from>\n     </email_notification>\n\n  3. Configure OSSEC server to receive alerts (on OSSEC manager)\n\n  4. Start OSSEC agent:\n     systemctl start ossec-hids\n     systemctl enable ossec-hids\n\nOption 3: Configure Auditd + Alerting\n  1. Install auditd:\n     apt install auditd audispd-plugins  # Debian\n\n  2. Add watch rules /etc/audit/rules.d/50-xo-audit-logs.rules:\n     -w /var/log/xo-server/ -p wa -k xo_log_tampering\n     -w /var/log/nginx/ -p wa -k nginx_log_tampering\n     -w /var/log/syslog -p wa -k syslog_tampering\n     -w /var/log/auth.log -p wa -k auth_log_tampering\n\n  3. Load rules:\n     augenrules --load\n     systemctl restart auditd\n\n  4. Create alert script /usr/local/bin/auditd-log-alert.sh:\n     #!/bin/bash\n     ausearch -k xo_log_tampering -k nginx_log_tampering -k syslog_tampering \\\n       --start recent -i 2>&1 | \\\n     mail -s \"ALERT: Audit Log Modification Detected on $(hostname)\" \\\n       isso@example.mil,sa@example.mil\n\n  5. Add to cron (check every 15 minutes):\n     */15 * * * * /usr/local/bin/auditd-log-alert.sh\n\nOption 4: Configure File Immutability (Prevention)\n  1. Set append-only attribute on log files:\n     chattr +a /var/log/xo-server/*.log\n     chattr +a /var/log/nginx/*.log\n     chattr +a /var/log/syslog\n     chattr +a /var/log/auth.log\n\n  2. Verify attributes:\n     lsattr /var/log/xo-server/\n     # Should show 'a' flag (append-only)\n\n  3. Note: Requires root to remove attribute\n     # To remove for log rotation:\n     chattr -a /var/log/xo-server/*.log\n     # Perform rotation\n     chattr +a /var/log/xo-server/*.log\n\nStep 5: Test FIM Alerting\n  1. Create test log file:\n     echo \"Test log entry\" > /var/log/xo-server/test.log\n\n  2. Modify test file (should trigger alert):\n     echo \"Unauthorized modification\" >> /var/log/xo-server/test.log\n\n  3. Wait for FIM check interval (or run manually)\n\n  4. Verify alert delivered to ISSO/SA email\n\n  5. Remove test file:\n     rm /var/log/xo-server/test.log\n\n  6. Document test results\n\nRe-run scan after FIM alerting configured and tested.\n\nNote: DoD requires immediate alerting of unauthorized audit log changes per NIST SP 800-53r5 AU-9(3) (Protection of Audit Information - Cryptographic Protection). File integrity monitoring with real-time alerting is mandatory to detect audit log tampering attempts.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 8C6457606577358C7025FC184772B7241F2A1237\n~~~~~\nVulnerability ID: V-264340\nRule ID: SV-264340r508029_rule\nCAT II / Medium - Unauthorized Audit Log Change Alerting\n---[Organizational Policy Check]---\n\nRequirement: Web server must immediately alert security personnel of unauthorized audit log changes.\n\nCheck 1: Log File Immutability Protection\n  Log Directory: /var/log/journal\n    [FOUND] Append-only attribute set (prevents deletion/modification)\n    Permissions: 2755 root:systemd-journal\n\nCheck 2: File Integrity Monitoring (FIM) Configuration\n  [NOT FOUND] No FIM tools detected (AIDE/Tripwire/OSSEC)\n\nCheck 3: Auditd Rules for Log Directory Monitoring\n  [NOT FOUND] Auditd rules directory not present\n\nCheck 4: Alert Configuration for Log Tampering\n  [MANUAL] Cannot automatically verify alerting configuration\n\nCheck 5: ISSO/SA Notification Mechanism\n  [MANUAL] ISSO/SA notification requires organizational verification\n\n  Required notification mechanisms:\n  - Email alerts to security personnel\n  - SIEM platform integration (Splunk, QRadar, ArcSight, etc.)\n  - Centralized monitoring console alerts\n  - Incident response ticketing system integration\n  - 24/7 SOC notification for critical events\n\n---[Manual Verification Required]---\n\nSTATUS: Open (Organizational Policy)\n\nRATIONALE:\nFile integrity monitoring and real-time alerting for unauthorized audit log changes\nrequires organizational implementation and ISSO verification. While automated checks\ncan detect file protection mechanisms and FIM tool configurations, only manual review\ncan verify:\n\n1. FIM tools are configured to monitor ALL audit log locations\n2. Alert thresholds are properly calibrated to detect unauthorized changes\n3. Alerting mechanisms reach designated security personnel (ISSO/SA)\n4. Response procedures are documented and tested\n5. Integration with organizational SIEM/monitoring infrastructure\n\nDISCOVERY SUMMARY:\n- Log file protection: Configured (immutable/append-only attributes)\n- File integrity monitoring: Not detected (no FIM tools found)\n- Auditd log monitoring: Not detected (no watch rules)\n- Alert configuration: Manual verification required\n\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264341","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264341","title":"SRG-APP-000805","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264341","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must automatically generate audit records of the enforcement actions.","rule_id_src":"SV-264341r984368_rule","rule_id":"SV-264341r984368","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000805-WSR-000140","rule_title":"The web server must automatically generate audit records of the enforcement actions.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to automatically generate audit records of the enforcement actions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to automatically generate audit records of the enforcement actions.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to automatically generate audit records of the enforcement actions, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Organizations log system accesses associated with applying configuration changes to ensure that configuration change control is implemented and to support after-the-fact actions should organizations discover any unauthorized changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-003938"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"f88825bc-3c73-442a-ba26-7e61c07000ba","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: DC2A5CDC670EF3998783475FDAEFCF4297BE2767\n~~~~~\nCHECK 1: XO Audit Plugin Detection\n   [INFO] XO audit plugin not detected in standard package locations\n\nCHECK 2: Winston Logger Enforcement Event Configuration\n   [INFO] No explicit enforcement logging configuration (Winston default: info level)\n\nCHECK 3: Sample Enforcement Events in Logs\n   [INFO] No enforcement events found in recent logs (may indicate no violations)\n\nCHECK 4: Systemd Journal Enforcement Records\n   [SAMPLE] Enforcement events from systemd journal:\n      Feb 01 07:11:06 xoa xo-server[1076588]: 2026-02-01T12:11:06.401Z xo:xo-server ERROR unhandled error event {\n      Feb 01 12:14:45 xoa xo-server[1076588]: 2026-02-01T17:14:45.401Z xo:xo-server ERROR unhandled error event {\n      Feb 02 05:56:26 xoa xo-server[1076588]: 2026-02-02T10:56:26.401Z xo:xo-server ERROR unhandled error event {\n      Feb 03 00:08:42 xoa xo-server[1076588]: 2026-02-03T05:08:42.401Z xo:xo-server ERROR unhandled error event {\n      Feb 07 17:55:22 xoa xo-server[1076588]: 2026-02-07T22:55:22.401Z xo:xo-server ERROR unhandled error event {\n\nCHECK 5: XO REST API Audit Records (Enforcement Actions)\n   [INFO] No XO REST API token available (skipping API audit check)\n   Token search locations:\n      - /etc/xo-server/stig/api-token\n      - Environment variable: XO_API_TOKEN\n      - /var/lib/xo-server/.xo-cli\n\n====================================================================\nDETERMINATION:\n   [PASS] Enforcement actions are automatically logged - DoD requirement MET\n\nCOMPLIANCE SUMMARY:\n   - Winston logger: Enforcement events logged\n   - Systemd journal: Enforcement records present\n\nEnforcement actions logged:\n   - VM operation denials (RBAC/ACL blocks)\n   - Authentication failures and lockouts\n   - Configuration change rejections\n   - Resource quota enforcement\n   - Policy violation blocks\n\nDoD Requirement: Enforcement actions MUST be automatically logged for audit trail\n                 and security monitoring purposes.\n\n====================================================================\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264342","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264342","title":"SRG-APP-000815","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264342","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must require users to be individually authenticated before granting access to the shared accounts or resources.","rule_id_src":"SV-264342r984371_rule","rule_id":"SV-264342r984371","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000815-WSR-000160","rule_title":"The web server must require users to be individually authenticated before granting access to the shared accounts or resources.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to require users to be individually authenticated before granting access to the shared accounts or resources.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to require users to be individually authenticated before granting access to the shared accounts or resources.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to require users to be individually authenticated before granting access to the shared accounts or resources, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Individual authentication prior to shared group authentication mitigates the risk of using group accounts or authenticators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004045"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"f48941e6-0654-4db5-a26e-c1d0ae73e875","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nORGANIZATIONAL POLICY VERIFICATION REQUIRED: Verify individual authentication for shared accounts/resources.\n\nRequired Verification:\n1. Review XO authentication method:\n   - LDAP/AD integration: Users login with individual credentials\n   - Local accounts: Each user has unique username (no shared \"admin\" account)\n2. Verify audit logging attributes actions to individuals (not shared account)\n3. Check for prohibited shared credential usage:\n   - No generic \"xoadmin\" account shared among multiple people\n   - No password sharing via email/sticky notes\n4. Validate organizational password sharing policy prohibits shared credentials\n\nRemediation:\n1. Implement LDAP/AD authentication:\n   - Install xo-server-auth-ldap plugin\n   - Configure LDAP connection in config.toml\n   - Map AD groups to XO roles\n2. Disable shared local accounts:\n   - Transition to individual LDAP/AD accounts\n   - Delete generic \"admin\" account after LDAP working\n3. Configure individual user attribution in logs:\n   - Enable XO audit plugin\n   - Configure Winston logger with user context\n   - Forward logs to SIEM with user attribution\n4. Establish password sharing prohibition policy:\n   - Document in System Security Plan\n   - Include in user security awareness training\n   - Enforce through annual access reviews\n\nDoD requirement: All access must be attributable to individual users for accountability and non-repudiation.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 020E89B54A3F3586A75F1E66177D47F7EB13933C\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-264342: Individual Authentication for Shared Accounts\n================================================================================\n\nRequirement: Users must be individually authenticated before accessing shared accounts/resources.\nThis check requires verification of individual authentication before shared resource access.\n\nCheck 1: Shared Account Detection (Multiple Simultaneous Logins)\n--------------------------------------------------\nNo accounts with multiple simultaneous logins detected.\n\nMost frequently logged in accounts (top 10):\nawk: 1: unexpected character '\\'\nhead: write error: Broken pipe\n\nReview for shared account patterns (multiple users using same account).\n\nCheck 2: XO Group Permissions Analysis (REST API)\n--------------------------------------------------\nXO API token not found. Unable to enumerate XO groups via API.\nChecked: /etc/xo-server/stig/api-token, XO_API_TOKEN env, /var/lib/xo-server/.xo-cli\n\nCheck 3: Audit Logging for Account Access (Winston/Audit Plugin)\n--------------------------------------------------\nXO Winston logs not found at /var/log/xo-server/.\n\nXO audit plugin not detected. Consider installing for enhanced user attribution.\n\nCheck 4: Authentication Method Verification (Individual vs. Shared)\n--------------------------------------------------\nXO authentication configuration:\n/etc/xo-server/config.toml:# If a chain of certificates authorities is needed, you may bundle\n/etc/xo-server/config.toml:# certificate authority up to the root.\n\nReview authentication methods for individual user attribution.\n\nCheck 5: LDAP/AD Group-Based Access (External Authentication)\n--------------------------------------------------\nNo LDAP/AD authentication plugins detected.\n\nNo SAML/OAuth/OIDC authentication plugins detected.\n\nCheck 6: Session Tracking and User Attribution\n--------------------------------------------------\nUnable to retrieve authentication events from systemd journal.\n\n================================================================================\nORGANIZATIONAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED\n================================================================================\n\nThis check ALWAYS requires manual ISSO/ISSM verification of:\n\n1. Individual authentication before shared resource access\n2. No shared credentials for accessing XO or underlying systems\n3. User attribution in audit logs (each action traceable to individual user)\n4. Group-based access control (not shared accounts)\n5. External authentication integration (LDAP/AD/SAML) for individual identity\n6. Prohibition of shared account usage in organizational policy\n\nMANUAL VERIFICATION PROCEDURES:\n\n1. Review authentication architecture:\n   - Verify individual user accounts (no shared credentials)\n   - Verify external authentication integration (LDAP/AD/SAML/OAuth)\n   - Verify group-based access control (permissions via groups, not shared accounts)\n   - Verify MFA/2FA for individual user authentication\n\n2. Review shared resource access patterns:\n   - Identify shared resources (VMs, storage repositories, networks)\n   - Verify access control via XO groups/roles (not shared accounts)\n   - Verify individual authentication before accessing shared resources\n   - Review XO audit logs for user attribution on shared resource access\n\n3. Review organizational policy:\n   - Verify policy prohibits shared account usage\n   - Verify policy requires individual authentication\n   - Verify policy requires user attribution in audit logs\n   - Review training materials on shared account prohibition\n\n4. Review audit logging:\n   - Verify Winston logs capture individual user identity\n   - Verify audit plugin installed and configured (if available)\n   - Verify systemd journal captures authentication events with user attribution\n   - Review sample logs to confirm individual user tracking\n\n5. Interview system administrators:\n   - Verify no shared accounts used for XO administration\n   - Verify all users have individual accounts\n   - Verify external authentication enforces individual identity\n   - Verify shared resource access follows individual authentication model\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264343","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264343","title":"SRG-APP-000820","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264343","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must implement multifactor authentication for local; network; and/or remote access to privileged accounts; and/or nonprivileged accounts such that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system gaining access.","rule_id_src":"SV-264343r984374_rule","rule_id":"SV-264343r984374","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000820-WSR-000170","rule_title":"The web server must implement multifactor authentication for local; network; and/or remote access to privileged accounts; and/or nonprivileged accounts such that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system gaining access.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to implement multifactor authentication for local; network; and/or remote access to privileged accounts; and/or nonprivileged accounts such that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system gaining access.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to implement multifactor authentication for local; network; and/or remote access to privileged accounts; and/or nonprivileged accounts such that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system gaining access.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to implement multifactor authentication for local; network; and/or remote access to privileged accounts; and/or nonprivileged accounts such that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system gaining access, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The purpose of requiring a device separate from the system to which the user is attempting to gain access for one of the factors during multifactor authentication is to reduce the likelihood of compromising authenticators or credentials stored on the system. Adversaries may be able to compromise such authenticators or credentials and subsequently impersonate authorized users. Implementing one of the factors on a separate device (e.g., a hardware token), provides a greater strength of mechanism and an increased level of assurance in the authentication process.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004046"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"1daac788-687e-4cb6-9a5b-fcfd021c0c4f","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 124C3776F3DCC368B4097A160BA5FA87BD5F7393\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-264343: Multifactor Authentication (MFA) Implementation\n================================================================================\n\nREQUIREMENT:\nThe web server must implement multifactor authentication for local, network, and\nremote access to privileged and nonprivileged accounts per organizational requirements.\n\nAUTOMATED MFA DETECTION:\n--------------------------------------------------\n\nCheck 1: XO Authentication Plugins\n\n   [NOT FOUND] No XO authentication plugins detected\n   [INFO] Using default XO authentication (local accounts only)\n\nCheck 2: LDAP/Active Directory Integration\n\n   [NOT FOUND] No LDAP/AD configuration detected\n\nCheck 3: SAML/OAuth/OIDC Configuration\n\n   [NOT FOUND] No SAML/OAuth/OIDC configuration detected\n\nCheck 4: Two-Factor Authentication (2FA) Plugins\n\n   [FOUND] 2FA npm packages installed:\n   /root \n\nCheck 5: System-Level MFA (PAM Configuration)\n\n   [NOT FOUND] No PAM-based MFA modules detected\n\nCheck 6: Reverse Proxy MFA Enforcement\n\n   [NOT FOUND] No reverse proxy MFA enforcement detected\n\n================================================================================\nMULTIFACTOR AUTHENTICATION ASSESSMENT\n================================================================================\n\nAUTOMATED DETECTION - MFA INDICATORS FOUND:\n- Authentication plugins or external providers detected\n- Configuration suggests MFA capability exists\n\nMANUAL VERIFICATION STILL REQUIRED:\nAutomated checks detected MFA-capable configurations but cannot verify:\n- Whether MFA is actually enforced for all users\n- Compliance with organization-defined strength requirements\n- User enrollment and policy enforcement status\n\nMANDATORY MANUAL VERIFICATION:\n\n1. MFA IMPLEMENTATION VERIFICATION:\n   - Verify MFA is enabled for ALL privileged accounts (administrators)\n   - Verify MFA is enabled for nonprivileged accounts per org policy\n   - Confirm MFA enforcement for local, network, AND remote access\n   - Test MFA login process with representative user accounts\n\n2. AUTHENTICATION STRENGTH REQUIREMENTS:\n   - Verify MFA mechanism meets organization-defined strength requirements\n   - Acceptable factors: CAC/PIV, OTP (TOTP/HOTP), hardware tokens, biometrics\n   - Unacceptable single factors: SMS, email, knowledge-based authentication\n   - Confirm compliance with NIST SP 800-63B Authenticator Assurance Levels\n\n3. MFA ENROLLMENT AND MANAGEMENT:\n   - Verify all users are enrolled in MFA program\n   - Review MFA enrollment procedures and documentation\n   - Confirm backup authentication methods are secure\n   - Validate MFA recovery/reset procedures prevent unauthorized access\n\n4. ORGANIZATIONAL POLICY COMPLIANCE:\n   - Review organization's MFA policy document\n   - Verify web server MFA aligns with org requirements\n   - Document any approved exceptions or waivers\n   - Confirm periodic MFA compliance audits are conducted\n\nREQUIRED EVIDENCE FOR AUDITOR:\n\nSystem Owner/ISSO must provide:\n- Organizational MFA policy and implementation guide\n- Screenshots of MFA login process for privileged and nonprivileged accounts\n- Authentication plugin/provider configuration documentation\n- User enrollment reports showing MFA coverage\n- MFA strength verification (FIPS 140-2 validation certificates, etc.)\n- External authentication provider SLA/MOA (if LDAP/SAML/OAuth used)\n- MFA audit logs and compliance reports\n\nIMPLEMENTATION GUIDANCE:\n\nFor XO MFA implementation options:\n1. LDAP/Active Directory Integration:\n   - Install xo-server-auth-ldap plugin\n   - Configure LDAP server with MFA support (AD + Azure MFA, FreeIPA + OTP)\n   - XO delegates authentication to LDAP, MFA enforced at directory level\n\n2. SAML/OAuth/OIDC Integration:\n   - Install xo-server-auth-saml or xo-server-auth-oidc plugin\n   - Integrate with DoD-approved identity provider (Okta, Azure AD, etc.)\n   - IdP enforces MFA before issuing SAML assertion/OAuth token\n\n3. Reverse Proxy MFA:\n   - Deploy oauth2-proxy or similar in front of XO\n   - Proxy authenticates users with MFA before forwarding to XO\n   - XO trusts proxy authentication headers\n\n4. Custom Plugin Development:\n   - Develop custom xo-server-auth-* plugin for organization-specific MFA\n   - Integrate with existing DoD authentication infrastructure\n\nNON-COMPLIANCE RISK:\nFailure to implement MFA allows attackers to gain unauthorized access using only\ncompromised passwords. MFA significantly reduces the risk of credential-based\nattacks, phishing, and unauthorized privileged access to the virtualization\nmanagement platform."},{"group_id_src":"V-264344","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264344","title":"SRG-APP-000825","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264344","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must implement multifactor authentication for local; network; and/or remote access to privileged accounts; and/or nonprivileged accounts such that the device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements.","rule_id_src":"SV-264344r984377_rule","rule_id":"SV-264344r984377","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000825-WSR-000180","rule_title":"The web server must implement multifactor authentication for local; network; and/or remote access to privileged accounts; and/or nonprivileged accounts such that the device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to implement multifactor authentication for local; network; and/or remote access to privileged accounts; and/or nonprivileged accounts such that the device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to implement multifactor authentication for local; network; and/or remote access to privileged accounts; and/or nonprivileged accounts such that the device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to implement multifactor authentication for local; network; and/or remote access to privileged accounts; and/or nonprivileged accounts such that the device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The purpose of requiring a device that is separate from the system to which the user is attempting to gain access for one of the factors during multifactor authentication is to reduce the likelihood of compromising authenticators or credentials stored on the system. Adversaries may be able to compromise such authenticators or credentials and subsequently impersonate authorized users. Implementing one of the factors on a separate device (e.g., a hardware token), provides a greater strength of mechanism and an increased level of assurance in the authentication process.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004047"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"7204bcb8-7ff3-4b98-bf32-dc2a04588af8","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 6FFDC4803E1617F8426BEE96F3F092C8539954CD\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-264344: MFA Strength Requirement - Separate Device Factor\n================================================================================\n\nREQUIREMENT:\nThe web server must implement multifactor authentication such that one of the\nauthentication factors is provided by a device SEPARATE from the system gaining access.\n\nThis requirement ensures MFA strength by mandating a physical separation between\nauthentication factors (something you know + something you have on a separate device).\n\nACCEPTABLE MFA IMPLEMENTATIONS (Separate Device Factor):\n--------------------------------------------------\n\n1. CAC/PIV SMART CARD + PIN:\n   - DoD Common Access Card (CAC) or Personal Identity Verification (PIV) card\n   - Smart card reader required (separate device)\n   - PIN entered on system keyboard\n   - FIPS 140-2 validated cryptographic module\n   - PREFERRED METHOD for DoD environments\n\n2. HARDWARE OTP TOKEN + PASSWORD:\n   - YubiKey, RSA SecurID, or similar hardware token (separate device)\n   - Time-based One-Time Password (TOTP) or HMAC-based OTP (HOTP)\n   - Password entered on system\n   - Token generates cryptographic code independent of system\n\n3. MOBILE AUTHENTICATOR APP + PASSWORD:\n   - Microsoft Authenticator, Google Authenticator, Duo Mobile (on smartphone)\n   - Smartphone is the separate device\n   - TOTP codes generated on mobile device\n   - Password entered on system accessing XO\n   - Acceptable if smartphone meets org security requirements\n\n4. BIOMETRIC (on separate device) + PASSWORD:\n   - Fingerprint scanner on CAC reader or USB device (separate hardware)\n   - Facial recognition on approved biometric device\n   - Password entered on system\n   - Biometric device must be FIPS 201 compliant\n\n5. FIDO2/WebAuthn SECURITY KEY + PASSWORD:\n   - YubiKey 5, Google Titan, or FIDO2-certified security key\n   - USB/NFC security key is the separate device\n   - Password entered on system\n   - Public key cryptography, phishing-resistant\n\nUNACCEPTABLE MFA IMPLEMENTATIONS (Not Separate Device):\n--------------------------------------------------\n\n1. SMS TO SAME DEVICE:\n   - SMS code sent to smartphone used to access web server\n   - FAILS separate device requirement (single point of compromise)\n   - Also vulnerable to SIM swapping and SS7 attacks\n\n2. EMAIL TO SAME DEVICE:\n   - Email verification code accessed on same system/device\n   - FAILS separate device requirement\n   - Email account compromise defeats MFA\n\n3. SOFTWARE TOKEN ON SAME DEVICE:\n   - OTP app installed on same computer accessing XO\n   - FAILS separate device requirement\n   - Malware on system can steal both password and OTP seed\n\n4. KNOWLEDGE-BASED AUTHENTICATION (KBA):\n   - Security questions (mother's maiden name, first pet, etc.)\n   - Not a separate device\n   - Vulnerable to social engineering and data breaches\n   - NOT acceptable as second factor\n\n5. PASSWORD + DIFFERENT PASSWORD:\n   - Two passwords or passphrases\n   - Same authentication factor (knowledge) used twice\n   - NOT multifactor authentication\n\n================================================================================\nMFA STRENGTH ASSESSMENT\n================================================================================\n\nAUTOMATED CHECK COMPLETE - MANUAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED\n\nAutomated checks CANNOT determine:\n- The type of MFA implementation deployed\n- Whether the second factor is provided by a separate device\n- Compliance with organization-defined MFA strength requirements\n\nManual ISSO/ISSM review is MANDATORY to verify MFA strength.\n\nMANDATORY MANUAL VERIFICATION:\n\n1. MFA MECHANISM IDENTIFICATION:\n   - Document the exact MFA mechanism used for XO authentication\n   - Identify both authentication factors (e.g., password + CAC)\n   - Verify one factor is provided by a SEPARATE DEVICE\n   - Confirm separate device is not same system accessing XO\n\n2. SEPARATE DEVICE VERIFICATION:\n   - For CAC/PIV: Verify smart card reader is separate USB/integrated device\n   - For OTP token: Verify hardware token or smartphone app used\n   - For FIDO2 key: Verify USB security key is separate from computer\n   - For biometric: Verify biometric scanner is separate hardware device\n   - Document make/model of separate authentication device\n\n3. FIPS VALIDATION (for DoD systems):\n   - Verify MFA device has FIPS 140-2 validation (CAC, YubiKey FIPS, etc.)\n   - Obtain FIPS validation certificate number\n   - Confirm cryptographic module meets DoD requirements\n   - Check NIST CMVP validation list: https://csrc.nist.gov/projects/cryptographic-module-validation-program\n\n4. NIST SP 800-63B COMPLIANCE:\n   - Verify MFA meets Authenticator Assurance Level (AAL) requirements\n   - AAL2: Requires possession and control of two distinct factors\n   - AAL3: Requires hardware cryptographic authenticator (CAC, FIDO2 key)\n   - Document AAL level achieved by current MFA implementation\n\n5. ORGANIZATIONAL POLICY ALIGNMENT:\n   - Review organization's MFA strength policy\n   - Verify XO MFA meets or exceeds org requirements\n   - Document approved MFA methods from org policy\n   - Confirm any exceptions or waivers are documented and approved\n\nREQUIRED EVIDENCE FOR AUDITOR:\n\nSystem Owner/ISSO must provide:\n- Detailed MFA implementation documentation with separate device specification\n- Screenshots of MFA login process showing separate device usage\n- FIPS 140-2 validation certificate for MFA device (if applicable)\n- NIST SP 800-63B Authenticator Assurance Level determination\n- Organizational MFA policy specifying acceptable authentication mechanisms\n- User training documentation on proper MFA device usage\n- MFA device inventory and lifecycle management procedures\n- Evidence of periodic MFA effectiveness testing\n\nIMPLEMENTATION NOTES:\n\nFor XO deployments, the MFA separate device requirement is typically satisfied by:\n\n1. LDAP/AD Integration with CAC Authentication:\n   - Active Directory configured for CAC/PIV smart card authentication\n   - XO delegates authentication to AD via LDAP\n   - CAC reader is the separate device\n   - Meets DoD PKI requirements\n\n2. SAML/OIDC with DoD Identity Provider:\n   - Integration with DoD-approved IdP (Azure AD + CAC, Okta + YubiKey)\n   - IdP enforces MFA with separate device before issuing assertion\n   - XO trusts IdP authentication decision\n   - Centralized MFA management\n\n3. OAuth2 Proxy with MFA Gateway:\n   - Deploy oauth2-proxy or similar in front of XO\n   - Proxy integrates with MFA gateway (Duo, Azure MFA, etc.)\n   - Users authenticate with password + separate device (phone, token)\n   - Proxy validates MFA before forwarding to XO\n\nNON-COMPLIANCE RISK:\nMFA without a separate device factor (e.g., password + security questions) provides\nweak protection. If both factors are on the same device or in the user's memory,\ncompromise of that single element defeats MFA. Separate device requirement ensures\nan attacker must compromise BOTH the user's knowledge (password) AND physical\npossession of a separate authentication device."},{"group_id_src":"V-264345","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264345","title":"SRG-APP-000830","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264345","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must, for password-based authentication, maintain a list of commonly used, expected, or compromised passwords on an organization-defined frequency.","rule_id_src":"SV-264345r984380_rule","rule_id":"SV-264345r984380","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000830-WSR-000190","rule_title":"The web server must, for password-based authentication, maintain a list of commonly used, expected, or compromised passwords on an organization-defined frequency.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to maintain a list of commonly used, expected, or compromised passwords on an organization-defined frequency.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to maintain a list of commonly used, expected, or compromised passwords on an organization-defined frequency.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to maintain a list of commonly used, expected, or compromised passwords on an organization-defined frequency, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Password-based authentication applies to passwords regardless of whether they are used in single-factor or multifactor authentication. Long passwords or passphrases are preferable over shorter passwords. Enforced composition rules provide marginal security benefits while decreasing usability. However, organizations may choose to establish certain rules for password generation (e.g., minimum character length for long passwords) under certain circumstances and can enforce this requirement in IA-5(1)(h). Account recovery can occur, for example, in situations when a password is forgotten. Cryptographically protected passwords include salted one-way cryptographic hashes of passwords. The list of commonly used, compromised, or expected passwords includes passwords obtained from previous breach corpuses, dictionary words, and repetitive or sequential characters. The list includes context-specific words, such as the name of the service, username, and derivatives thereof.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004058"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"9c26a340-9baf-4f71-85ac-2e54bc0d42d9","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nORGANIZATIONAL POLICY VERIFICATION REQUIRED: Verify compromised password list maintenance.\n\nRequired Verification:\n1. Review organizational password policy:\n   - Documents compromised password list maintenance frequency (recommend: quarterly)\n   - Specifies password list sources (e.g., NIST password list, HaveIBeenPwned, internal breach reports)\n   - Defines update procedures and approval process\n2. Verify password list implementation:\n   - PAM pwquality dictcheck enabled\n   - Custom dictionary files present in /etc/security/ or /usr/share/dict/\n   - Dictionary updated within organizational frequency requirement\n3. Check for LDAP/AD integration (delegated password policy enforcement)\n4. Review evidence of periodic updates (change logs, approved change requests)\n\nRemediation:\n1. Establish password list maintenance policy:\n   - Frequency: At least annually (recommend quarterly)\n   - Sources: NIST 800-63B Appendix A, HaveIBeenPwned API, internal breach analysis\n   - Approval: ISSO/ISSM must approve list updates\n2. Configure PAM pwquality dictionary checking:\n   - Edit /etc/security/pwquality.conf\n   - Set: dictcheck = 1\n   - Set: dictpath = /etc/security/pwdictionary (custom dictionary path)\n3. Download and install compromised password lists:\n   - NIST list: wget https://pages.nist.gov/800-63-3/sp800-63b.html\n   - SecLists: git clone https://github.com/danielmiessler/SecLists.git\n   - Extract common passwords to /etc/security/pwdictionary\n4. Establish quarterly update process:\n   - Scheduled task to download updated lists\n   - Change management approval for dictionary updates\n   - Testing in non-production before deployment\n5. Document procedures in System Security Plan\n\nDoD requirement: Password lists must be updated at organization-defined frequency (recommend quarterly minimum).\n\nFor LDAP/AD environments: Verify Active Directory password filter DLL implements compromised password checking or integrate with Azure AD Password Protection.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 5B9CBE4DC6ABCFAEC762AE00F3D562BCE8691995\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-264345: Compromised Password List Maintenance\n================================================================================\n\nRequirement: Maintain list of commonly used/expected/compromised passwords on organization-defined frequency.\nThis check requires verification of organizational password list maintenance procedures.\n\nCheck 1: Password Policy Documentation Discovery\n--------------------------------------------------\nNo password policy documentation found at standard locations.\nChecked locations:\n  - /etc/xo-server/password-policy.txt\n  - /opt/xo/docs/password-requirements.md\n  - /usr/local/share/xo/policies/passwords.txt\n  - /root/password-policy.txt\n  - /etc/security/password-policy.conf\n\nCheck 2: PAM pwquality Configuration (System-Level Password Enforcement)\n--------------------------------------------------\nPAM pwquality configuration not found at /etc/security/pwquality.conf.\n\nCheck 3: Dictionary File Existence (Common/Compromised Password Lists)\n--------------------------------------------------\nDictionary file found: /usr/share/dict/words\n  lrwxrwxrwx 1 root root 30 Jun  4  2025 /usr/share/dict/words -> /etc/dictionaries-common/words\nDictionary file found: /usr/share/dict/american-english\n  -rw-r--r-- 1 root root 962K Jan 20  2022 /usr/share/dict/american-english\nDictionary file found: /etc/security/opasswd\n  -rw------- 1 root root 0 Jun  4  2025 /etc/security/opasswd\n\nCheck 4: Organizational Password Policy Files (Custom Lists)\n--------------------------------------------------\nConfiguration file found: /etc/pam.d/common-password\nPassword-related settings:\n# /etc/pam.d/common-password - password-related modules common to all services\n# used to change user passwords.  The default is pam_unix.\n#hashed passwords using the yescrypt algorithm, introduced in Debian\n#used the option \"sha512\"; if a shadow password hash will be shared\npassword\t[success=1 default=ignore]\tpam_unix.so obscure yescrypt\npassword\trequisite\t\t\tpam_deny.so\npassword\trequired\t\t\tpam_permit.so\nConfiguration file found: /etc/login.defs\nPassword-related settings:\n# Password aging controls:\n#\tPASS_MAX_DAYS\tMaximum number of days a password may be used.\n#\tPASS_MIN_DAYS\tMinimum number of days allowed between password changes.\n#\tPASS_WARN_AGE\tNumber of days warning given before a password expires.\nPASS_MAX_DAYS\t99999\nPASS_MIN_DAYS\t0\nPASS_WARN_AGE\t7\n# Max number of login retries if password is bad. This will most likely be\n# If set to \"yes\", new passwords will be encrypted using the MD5-based\n# It supports passwords of unlimited length and longer salt strings.\nConfiguration file found: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n\nCheck 5: LDAP/AD Password Policy (External Authentication)\n--------------------------------------------------\nNo LDAP/AD authentication plugins detected.\nPassword policy enforcement is local to XO and the underlying Debian system.\n\nCheck 6: Evidence of Periodic Password List Updates\n--------------------------------------------------\nChecking modification times of password-related files for update frequency...\n\n  2025-06-04 07:57:00.628404000 -0400 /usr/share/dict/words\n  2022-01-20 00:16:40.000000000 -0500 /usr/share/dict/american-english\n  2025-06-04 07:42:52.092404000 -0400 /etc/security/opasswd\n\nNo automated password list update jobs detected in cron.\n\nNo automated password list update jobs detected in systemd timers.\n\n================================================================================\nORGANIZATIONAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED\n================================================================================\n\nThis check ALWAYS requires manual ISSO/ISSM verification of:\n\n1. Organizational password policy requiring compromised password list maintenance\n2. Defined update frequency (e.g., quarterly, semi-annually, annually)\n3. Sources of compromised password lists (e.g., NIST, HaveIBeenPwned, CISA)\n4. Implementation method (PAM pwquality, custom scripts, LDAP/AD integration)\n5. Documentation of password list updates (change logs, audit trails)\n6. Testing procedures to verify compromised password blocking\n\nMANUAL VERIFICATION PROCEDURES:\n\n1. Review organizational password policy:\n   - Verify policy requires maintaining list of compromised passwords\n   - Verify organization-defined update frequency (e.g., 'at least annually')\n   - Verify acceptable sources for compromised password lists\n   - Verify procedures for integrating new compromised passwords into enforcement\n\n2. Review implementation method:\n   - For LOCAL authentication: PAM pwquality with dictcheck/dictpath settings\n   - For LDAP/AD authentication: Directory service password policy (delegated)\n   - For custom implementation: Scripts/tools that check passwords against lists\n   - Verify implementation blocks passwords matching compromised list\n\n3. Review compromised password list sources:\n   - NIST Special Publication 800-63B Appendix A (banned passwords)\n   - HaveIBeenPwned Pwned Passwords database\n   - CISA/NSA guidance on commonly exploited passwords\n   - Organizational intelligence (passwords from incidents/breaches)\n\n4. Review evidence of periodic updates:\n   - Change logs documenting password list updates\n   - Audit trails showing list downloads/integrations\n   - Modification timestamps on dictionary files (Check 6 above)\n   - Automated update jobs (cron/systemd timers) - Check 6 above\n\n5. Test password enforcement:\n   - Attempt to set known compromised password (e.g., 'Password123!')\n   - Verify system rejects password with appropriate error message\n   - Document test results as evidence of enforcement\n\nACCEPTABLE EVIDENCE:\n   - Organizational password policy document with update frequency\n   - Change logs showing password list updates within required frequency\n   - Configuration files showing dictionary enforcement (PAM pwquality)\n   - LDAP/AD password policy documentation (if external auth)\n   - Test results demonstrating compromised password blocking\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264346","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264346","title":"SRG-APP-000835","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264346","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must, for password-based authentication, update the list of passwords on an organization-defined frequency.","rule_id_src":"SV-264346r984383_rule","rule_id":"SV-264346r984383","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000835-WSR-000200","rule_title":"The web server must, for password-based authentication, update the list of passwords on an organization-defined frequency.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to update the list of passwords on an organization-defined frequency.