 the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nWeak password hashing algorithm detected or unable to verify KDF implementation.\n\nAPPROVED KDFs (DoD/NIST SP 800-132):\n- bcrypt (adaptive cost factor, salt included)\n- PBKDF2 (with HMAC-SHA-256 or HMAC-SHA-512)\n- scrypt (memory-hard KDF)\n- Argon2 (Password Hashing Competition winner)\n- yescrypt (Debian 12 default, passwd/shadow)\n- SHA-512 with salt (Linux system passwords)\n\nPROHIBITED ALGORITHMS:\n- MD5 (cryptographically broken)\n- SHA-1 (collision attacks demonstrated)\n- DES crypt (56-bit key, obsolete)\n- Unsalted hashes of any type\n- Plaintext storage\n\nRemediation:\n1. For system accounts (/etc/shadow):\n   - Edit /etc/login.defs\n   - Set: ENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512 (or yescrypt if available)\n   - Force password reset: passwd --expire [username]\n2. For PAM configuration:\n   - Edit /etc/pam.d/common-password\n   - Ensure: password [success=1 default=ignore] pam_unix.so obscure sha512\n   - Or: password [success=1 default=ignore] pam_unix.so obscure yescrypt\n3. For XO application:\n   - Bcrypt is Node.js default (no change needed)\n   - If using custom authentication: Implement bcrypt with cost factor  12\n4. For LDAP/AD integration:\n   - Verify directory uses approved KDF (AD uses PBKDF2)\n   - Configure minimum password hash algorithm in AD policy\n\nRe-run scan after configuration changes.\n\nNOTE: Changing ENCRYPT_METHOD only affects NEW passwords. Existing password hashes must be regenerated through forced password changes.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: D2B9BBE2254FB4C873C7F2935540EFC89CF9CF13\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-264349: Password Storage Using Approved Salted Key Derivation Function\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: XO Password Storage Mechanism (bcrypt detection)\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [INFO] Unable to detect bcrypt library (may be bundled or using alternative method)\n\nCheck 2: System Password Hashing Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [FOUND] ENCRYPT_METHOD: SHA512\n  [PASS] System uses approved hash algorithm: SHA512\n\nCheck 3: PAM Password Modules Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [FOUND] PAM configuration: /etc/pam.d/common-password\n  [PASS] PAM configured for yescrypt password hashing\n\nCheck 4: LDAP/External Authentication Detection\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [INFO] No external authentication detected - local password storage used\n\nCheck 5: XO Database Password Storage Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [INFO] Redis detected (used for session management, not password storage)\n  [FOUND] XO database path: /var/lib/xo-server/data\n  [INFO] XO stores hashed passwords in LevelDB (using bcrypt)\n\nCheck 6: Approved Hash Algorithm Validation\n--------------------------------------------------\n  Approved salted key derivation functions:\n    - bcrypt (Blowfish-based, adaptive)\n    - PBKDF2 (NIST SP 800-132)\n    - scrypt (memory-hard KDF)\n    - Argon2 (modern, memory-hard)\n    - SHA-256/SHA-512 with salt (FIPS 140-2 approved)\n    - yescrypt (enhanced scrypt variant)\n\n  [PASS] Detected approved algorithms:\n        - SHA512 (system accounts)\n\n================================================================================\nASSESSMENT\n================================================================================\n\nMANUAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED\n\nFinding: Unable to confirm XO password hashing algorithm\n\nRequired Verification:\n  1. Verify XO uses bcrypt or approved algorithm for password storage\n  2. Confirm system ENCRYPT_METHOD is SHA-512, SHA-256, or YESCRYPT\n  3. Check PAM configuration uses approved password modules\n  4. If LDAP/AD used, verify external directory uses approved algorithms\n\nRemediation Steps:\n  1. System: Edit /etc/login.defs, set ENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512\n  2. PAM: Configure pam_unix.so with sha512 parameter in /etc/pam.d/common-password\n  3. XO: Verify bcrypt library is installed (npm list bcrypt --prefix /opt/xo/xo-server)\n  4. Consider LDAP/AD integration for centralized password management\n\nNote: XO uses bcrypt by default - manual code review may be needed to confirm"},{"group_id_src":"V-264350","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264350","title":"SRG-APP-000855","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264350","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must, for password-based authentication, require immediate selection of a new password upon account recovery.","rule_id_src":"SV-264350r984395_rule","rule_id":"SV-264350r984395","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000855-WSR-000240","rule_title":"The web server must, for password-based authentication, require immediate selection of a new password upon account recovery.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to require immediate selection of a new password upon account recovery.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to require immediate selection of a new password upon account recovery.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to require immediate selection of a new password upon account recovery, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Password-based authentication applies to passwords regardless of whether they are used in single-factor or multifactor authentication. Long passwords or passphrases are preferable over shorter passwords. Enforced composition rules provide marginal security benefits while decreasing usability. However, organizations may choose to establish certain rules for password generation (e.g., minimum character length for long passwords) under certain circumstances and can enforce this requirement in IA-5(1)(h). Account recovery can occur, for example, in situations when a password is forgotten. Cryptographically protected passwords include salted one-way cryptographic hashes of passwords. The list of commonly used, compromised, or expected passwords includes passwords obtained from previous breach corpuses, dictionary words, and repetitive or sequential characters. The list includes context-specific words, such as the name of the service, username, and derivatives thereof.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004063"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"536f07f9-8870-4471-9e13-7d3b2e195d59","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nORGANIZATIONAL POLICY VERIFICATION REQUIRED: Verify forced password change on account recovery.\n\nRequired Verification:\n1. Review organizational password recovery procedures:\n   - Documents forced password change requirement\n   - Specifies temporary password generation method\n   - Defines password change enforcement mechanism\n2. Test password recovery process:\n   - Request password reset for test account\n   - Verify temporary password is single-use or expires within 24 hours\n   - Confirm system forces new password selection on first login\n3. For LDAP/AD: Verify \"User must change password at next logon\" flag set after recovery\n4. For XO local accounts: Verify xo-cli password reset forces immediate change\n\nRemediation:\n1. Establish password recovery policy:\n   - Temporary passwords expire within 24 hours\n   - Temporary passwords are single-use only\n   - System forces password change on first login after recovery\n2. For system accounts (Linux):\n   - When resetting: chage --lastday 0 [username]\n   - This forces password change on next login\n3. For XO local accounts:\n   - Use XO web UI password reset feature\n   - Configure session termination after password change\n4. For LDAP/AD integration:\n   - Enable \"User must change password at next logon\" in AD\n   - Configure account lockout policy (3 failed attempts)\n5. Document procedures:\n   - Password recovery request approval process\n   - Identity verification before password reset\n   - Forced change enforcement mechanism\n   - Temporary password complexity requirements\n\nDoD requirement: Temporary/recovery passwords must be changed immediately upon first use. Temporary passwords must not be reusable.\n\nBest practice: Use password reset tokens with expiration (e.g., 15-minute validity) instead of temporary passwords where possible.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 7969672E3DB1517E30D357783C8A520400B5B7B8\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-264350: Password Change on Recovery\n================================================================================\n\nRequirement: Web server must require immediate password change upon account recovery.\nThis check requires verification of organizational password recovery procedures.\n\nCheck 1: Password Recovery Mechanism Discovery (XO Admin Password Reset)\n--------------------------------------------------\nXO CLI tool found: /usr/local/bin/xo-cli\n\nXO provides admin password reset via xo-cli commands:\n  xo-cli --register http://localhost http://localhost admin@admin.net admin\n  xo-cli user.set id=<user_id> password=<new_password>\n\nIMPORTANT: XO does NOT enforce immediate password change upon admin reset.\nOrganizational procedures MUST enforce this requirement externally.\n\nCheck 2: Temporary Password Policy Documentation\n--------------------------------------------------\nNo password recovery policy documentation found at standard locations.\nChecked locations:\n  - /etc/xo-server/password-recovery-policy.txt\n  - /opt/xo/docs/password-reset-procedures.md\n  - /usr/local/share/xo/policies/password-recovery.txt\n  - /root/password-reset-policy.txt\n\nCheck 3: XO Password Reset Procedures (xo-cli Commands)\n--------------------------------------------------\nNo password recovery/reset configuration found in XO config files.\n\nNo password recovery documentation found in XO installation.\n\nCheck 4: LDAP/AD Password Recovery Delegation (External Authentication)\n--------------------------------------------------\nNo LDAP/AD authentication plugins detected.\nPassword recovery is managed locally by XO and the underlying Debian system.\n\nCheck 5: Organizational Password Reset Policy\n--------------------------------------------------\nPAM password module configuration (/etc/pam.d/common-password):\n# used to change user passwords.  The default is pam_unix.\n# Explanation of pam_unix options:\n#`OBSCURE_CHECKS_ENAB' option in login.defs.  See the pam_unix manpage\npassword\t[success=1 default=ignore]\tpam_unix.so obscure yescrypt\n\nSystem-level password enforcement settings (does NOT force change on recovery).\n\nSystem login.defs password settings:\nPASS_MAX_DAYS\t99999\nPASS_MIN_DAYS\t0\nPASS_WARN_AGE\t7\nENCRYPT_METHOD SHA512\n\nCheck 6: Evidence of Forced Password Change on Recovery\n--------------------------------------------------\nSample account password aging (root account):\nLast password change\t\t\t\t\t: Jun 04, 2025\nPassword expires\t\t\t\t\t: never\nPassword inactive\t\t\t\t\t: never\nAccount expires\t\t\t\t\t\t: never\nMinimum number of days between password change\t\t: 0\nMaximum number of days between password change\t\t: 99999\nNumber of days of warning before password expires\t: 7\n\nThe 'chage' command can force password change via 'Password expires' field.\nSet to 'password must be changed' (expires=0) forces immediate change on next login.\n\nIMPORTANT: XO lacks built-in 'force password change on recovery' functionality.\nOrganizational procedures MUST enforce this requirement through:\n  1. Administrative policy requiring immediate password change notification\n  2. LDAP/AD password expiration flags (if external auth)\n  3. Manual verification of password change after account recovery\n  4. Audit logging to track password resets and subsequent changes\n\n================================================================================\nORGANIZATIONAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED\n================================================================================\n\nThis check ALWAYS requires manual ISSO/ISSM verification of:\n\n1. Organizational password recovery procedures\n2. Enforcement of immediate password change upon account recovery\n3. Documentation of password reset events and subsequent user password changes\n4. LDAP/AD integration with forced password change (if external auth)\n5. Administrative accountability for password recovery operations\n6. Audit logging of password resets and forced password changes\n\nMANUAL VERIFICATION PROCEDURES:\n\n1. Review organizational password recovery policy:\n   - Verify policy requires immediate password change upon account recovery\n   - Verify procedures for generating temporary passwords (if used)\n   - Verify administrative accountability (who can perform password resets)\n   - Verify user notification procedures (secure delivery of temporary password)\n\n2. Review password recovery implementation:\n   - For LOCAL authentication:\n     * XO admin resets password via xo-cli (Check 3 above)\n     * Admin notifies user securely (out-of-band communication)\n     * User required to change password on first login (enforced procedurally)\n   - For LDAP/AD authentication:\n     * Directory administrators perform password reset\n     * 'User must change password at next logon' flag set (Check 4 above)\n     * Automated enforcement via directory service password policy\n\n3. Review evidence of password recovery events:\n   - Audit logs showing password reset events (who, when, which account)\n   - Evidence of subsequent password change by user (audit logs)\n   - Time delta between reset and user-initiated change (should be minimal)\n   - Documentation of password recovery tickets/requests\n\n4. Test password recovery procedures:\n   - Perform test password reset on non-production account\n   - Verify temporary password delivered securely\n   - Verify user CANNOT use account without changing password\n   - Document test results as evidence of enforcement\n\n5. Interview administrators and users:\n   - Verify administrators understand password recovery procedures\n   - Verify users understand requirement to change password immediately\n   - Verify accountability mechanisms for password recovery operations\n\nACCEPTABLE EVIDENCE:\n   - Organizational password recovery policy document (Check 2 above)\n   - LDAP/AD password policy with 'force change' enforcement (Check 4 above)\n   - Audit logs showing password resets and subsequent user changes\n   - Test results demonstrating forced password change enforcement\n   - Training materials for administrators and users on password recovery\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264351","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264351","title":"SRG-APP-000860","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264351","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must, for password-based authentication, allow user selection of long passwords and passphrases, including spaces and all printable characters.","rule_id_src":"SV-264351r984398_rule","rule_id":"SV-264351r984398","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000860-WSR-000250","rule_title":"The 