1 lowercase letter (a-z)\n- At least 1 number (0-9)\n- At least 1 special character (!@#$%^&*()_+-=[]{}|:;\"'<>,.?/)\n- No dictionary words\n- No username in password\n- No repeating characters (>3 consecutive)\n- Password history: Cannot reuse last 5 passwords\n\nRequired Verification:\n1. Review organizational password policy - verify requirements  DoD minimums\n2. Verify technical enforcement:\n   - PAM pwquality: Check /etc/security/pwquality.conf\n   - LDAP/AD: Check Group Policy password settings\n   - XO application: Verify password validation logic\n3. Test password enforcement:\n   - Attempt to set weak password (should be rejected)\n   - Verify complexity error messages guide users\n4. Validate password history enforcement (reuse prevention)\n\nRemediation:\n1. Configure PAM pwquality (/etc/security/pwquality.conf):\n   minlen = 15         # Minimum password length\n   dcredit = -1        # At least 1 digit required\n   ucredit = -1        # At least 1 uppercase required\n   lcredit = -1        # At least 1 lowercase required\n   ocredit = -1        # At least 1 special char required\n   maxrepeat = 3       # Max 3 consecutive repeating chars\n   usercheck = 1       # Reject passwords containing username\n   dictcheck = 1       # Check against dictionary\n   enforcing = 1       # Enforce (don't just warn)\n\n2. Configure password history in PAM (/etc/pam.d/common-password):\n   password required pam_pwhistory.so remember=5 use_authtok\n\n3. For LDAP/AD integration:\n   - Open Group Policy Management\n   - Navigate to: Computer Config > Policies > Windows Settings > Security Settings > Account Policies > Password Policy\n   - Set complexity requirements per DoD standards\n   - Enable \"Password must meet complexity requirements\"\n   - Set \"Minimum password length\" to 15\n   - Set \"Enforce password history\" to 5 passwords\n\n4. Document organizational password policy:\n   - Include all DoD/NIST requirements\n   - Specify enforcement mechanisms\n   - Define exception/waiver process (if any)\n   - Include in user security awareness training\n\n5. Test enforcement:\n   passwd [username]  # Attempt weak password - should reject\n\nRe-run scan after configuration changes.\n\nNOTE: Some organizations may have stricter requirements (e.g., 20-character minimum for privileged accounts). Always align with organizational policy if more restrictive than DoD minimums.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 0B2A460264E59E7F296DA501F2284B8C1B565E01\n~~~~~\n================================================================================\nV-264353: Password Composition and Complexity Rules Enforcement\n================================================================================\n\nCheck 1: PAM Password Quality Configuration (/etc/security/pwquality.conf)\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [INFO] /etc/security/pwquality.conf not found\n  [INFO] System may be using PAM default settings or alternative configuration\n\nCheck 2: System Password Requirements (/etc/login.defs)\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [FOUND] PASS_MAX_DAYS: 99999\n  [FOUND] PASS_MIN_DAYS: 0\n  [FOUND] PASS_WARN_AGE: 7\n\nCheck 3: XO Password Complexity Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [FOUND] XO configuration: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n  [INFO] No explicit password policy configuration in XO config\n  [INFO] XO may enforce complexity at application level (code-based)\n  [INFO] XO configuration not found or no password policy specified\n  [INFO] Password complexity may be enforced through PAM or code logic\n\nCheck 4: LDAP/AD Password Policy Delegation\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [INFO] No external authentication detected - local password policy applies\n\nCheck 5: Organizational Password Policy Documentation\n--------------------------------------------------\n  [INFO] No password policy documentation found in standard locations\n  [INFO] Organization should document password complexity requirements\n\nCheck 6: Password Complexity Enforcement Analysis\n--------------------------------------------------\n  DoD Password Complexity Requirements (typical):\n    - Minimum length: 15 characters (or 12 with CAC/PIV)\n    - Character diversity: Mix of uppercase, lowercase, digits, special\n    - No dictionary words or easily guessable patterns\n    - Password history: Last 24 passwords cannot be reused\n    - Account lockout: 3 failed attempts within 15 minutes\n\n  [WARN] Unable to confirm complexity enforcement mechanism\n\n================================================================================\nASSESSMENT\n================================================================================\n\nMANUAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED\n\nFinding: Unable to confirm password complexity enforcement\n\nRequired Verification:\n  1. Confirm organizational password complexity policy is documented\n  2. Verify PAM/system settings align with organizational requirements\n  3. Test password creation to ensure complexity rules are enforced\n  4. If LDAP/AD used, verify directory service enforces org policy\n  5. Document any deviations or approved exceptions\n\nRecommended Remediation (if non-compliant):\n  1. Edit /etc/security/pwquality.conf:\n       minlen = 15        # DoD requirement: 15 chars (or 12 with CAC)\n       dcredit = -1       # Require at least 1 digit\n       ucredit = -1       # Require at least 1 uppercase\n       lcredit = -1       # Require at least 1 lowercase\n       ocredit = -1       # Require at least 1 special character\n       minclass = 4       # Require all 4 character classes\n\n  2. Edit /etc/pam.d/common-password (or system-auth):\n       Add: password requisite pam_pwquality.so retry=3\n\n  3. If using LDAP/AD, configure Fine-Grained Password Policy (FGPP)\n\n  4. Document organizational password policy in security plan\n\nNote