ance.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 18678D64917245F2DC2FBB99D08A02355E886CA7\n~~~~~\nVulnerability ID: V-264355\nRule ID: SV-264355r961863_rule\nCAT II / Medium - User/Admin Session Separation\n---[Hybrid Check: Technical + Organizational Policy]---\n\nCheck 1: XO Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)\n  [INFO] ACL plugin not detected at standard path\n        - Checking alternative installation methods...\n  [WARN] No ACL/RBAC plugin detected - all users may have same privileges\n\nCheck 2: User vs Admin Session Isolation\n  [INFO] Config file not found at /opt/xo/xo-server/config.toml\n  [INFO] Redis session store detected (1 session keys)\n        - Single session store for all users (typical XO configuration)\n  [FINDING] No separate session stores detected for admin vs user sessions\n\nCheck 3: Network Segmentation (Management VLAN)\n  [INFO] Network interfaces detected: 3\n        - lo: 127.0.0.1\n        - enX0: 10.0.10.40\n        - enX1: 172.23.0.15\n  [FINDING] No network segmentation detected (listening on all interfaces)\n\nCheck 4: Privilege Escalation Controls\n  [INFO] No recent role/permission changes in audit logs\n  [FINDING] Unable to verify privilege escalation audit controls\n\nCheck 5: Organizational Session Separation Policy\n  [REQUIREMENT] Organization must document:\n    1. Admin vs user session separation architecture\n    2. Network segmentation for administrative access\n    3. VLAN configuration (e.g., Management VLAN for admins)\n    4. Firewall/ACL rules restricting admin access\n    5. Role-based access control implementation\n    6. Session token isolation mechanisms\n\nAssessment:\n  Finding: Open\n  Reason: Session separation requires organizational policy and network architecture\n\nTechnical Findings:\n  [-] No ACL/RBAC plugin detected\n  [-] No separate session stores for admin vs user sessions\n  [-] No network segmentation (listening on all interfaces)\n\nRequired Manual Verification:\n  1. Verify admin access restricted to management VLAN\n  2. Confirm firewall rules separate admin/user traffic\n  3. Review organizational session separation policy\n  4. Validate separate communication paths for admin sessions\n  5. Check network diagrams showing logical separation\n  6. Review AD/LDAP group mappings for role separation\n\nEvidence Required:\n  - Network architecture diagram showing VLAN segmentation\n  - Firewall/ACL rules for admin vs user traffic\n  - XO role configuration (admin, operator, viewer)\n  - Session management architecture documentation\n  - Organizational policy for session separation\n\nNote: Typical XO deployment uses single session store but separates\nadmin/user access via network segmentation (management VLAN) and RBAC.\nThis is ACCEPTABLE if properly documented and enforced.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264356","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264356","title":"SRG-APP-000910","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264356","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization.","rule_id_src":"SV-264356r984413_rule","rule_id":"SV-264356r984413","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000910-WSR-000300","rule_title":"The web server must include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Public key infrastructure (PKI) certificates are certificates with visibility external to organizational systems and certificates related to the internal operations of systems, such as application-specific time services. In cryptographic systems with a hierarchical structure, a trust anchor is an authoritative source (i.e., a certificate authority) for which trust is assumed and not derived. A root certificate for a PKI system is an example of a trust anchor. A trust store or certificate store maintains a list of trusted root certificates.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004909"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"22dbb609-e37c-46e7-b9b7-5ffcd5ee0439","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 95C2961B7ABBB4A99C69048BE440566091A327D6\n~~~~~\nCheck 1: System CA Certificate Store\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] Certificate store: /etc/ssl/certs\n   [NOT FOUND] No DoD-related certificate files detected\n   [FOUND] Certificate store: /usr/share/ca-certificates\n   [NOT FOUND] No DoD-related certificate files detected\n   [NOT FOUND] Certificate store not present: /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors\n\nCheck 2: DoD Root CA Detection (Deep Inspection)\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [NOT FOUND] No DoD Root CA certificates detected in system stores\n   Expected certificates: DoD Root CA 3, DoD Root CA 4, DoD Root CA 5, DoD Root CA 6\n\nCheck 3: XO Node.js Trust Store Configuration\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [NOT SET] NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS environment variable not configured\n   Node.js will use system-wide CA store only\n\n   [FOUND] XO service file: /etc/systemd/system/xo-server.service\n   [NOT FOUND] NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS not set in service file\n\nCheck 4: Certificate Chain Validation with DoD CAs\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [FOUND] XO TLS certificate: /etc/ssl/cert.pem\n   [PASS] Certificate chain validation successful\n   C = AU, ST = Some-State, O = Internet Widgits Pty Ltd error 18 at 0 depth lookup: self-signed certificate error /etc/ssl/cert.pem: verification failed\n   Certificate Issuer: issuer=C = AU, ST = Some-State, O = Internet Widgits Pty Ltd\n   [WARNING] Certificate not issued by DoD PKI\n\nCheck 5: Expired or Invalid CA Certificates\n--------------------------------------------------\n   [WARNING] Expired certificates detected in /etc/ssl/certs\n\"/etc/ssl/certs/ca-certificates.crt\"\n   [WARNING] Expired certificates detected in /usr/share/ca-certificates\n\"/usr/share/ca-certificates/mozilla/XRamp_Global_CA_Root.crt\"\n\"/usr/share/ca-certificates/mozilla/SSL.com_EV_Root_Certification_Authority_ECC.crt\"\n\"/usr/share/ca-certificates/mozilla/SecureSign_RootCA11.crt\"\n\"/usr/share/ca-certificates/mozilla/DigiCert_Assured_ID_Root_G3.crt\"\n\"/usr/share/ca-certificates/mozilla/Certum_Trusted_Network_CA_2.crt\"\n\"/usr/share/ca-certificates/mozilla/ISRG_Root_X1.crt\"\n\"/usr/share/ca-certificates/mozilla/GTS_Root_R1.crt\"\n\"/usr/share/ca-certificates/mozilla/DigiCert_Trusted_Root_G4.crt\"\n\"/usr/share/ca-certificates/mozilla/Starfield_Class_2_CA.crt\"\n\"/usr/share/ca-certificates/mozilla/Microsec_e-Szigno_Root_CA_2009.crt\"\n\n================================================================================\nDOD TRUST ANCHOR COMPLIANCE ASSESSMENT\n================================================================================\n\nAUTOMATED CHECKS - NON-COMPLIANCE DETECTED:\n- [FAIL] No DoD Root CA certificates detected in system trust stores\n- [FAIL] System is using default/commercial CA trust anchors only\n\nMANUAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED:\n\n1. DOD PKI TRUST ANCHOR REQUIREMENTS:\n   - Verify DoD Root CA 3, 4, 5, and 6 are installed in system CA stores\n   - Confirm /etc/ssl/certs and /usr/share/ca-certificates contain DoD PKI root CAs\n   - Verify no unauthorized/commercial root CAs in DoD-managed trust stores\n   - Review certificate pinning for DoD-specific certificate authorities\n\n2. CERTIFICATE TRUST STORE CONFIGURATION:\n   - Verify update-ca-certificates has been run with DoD CA bundle\n   - Confirm NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS points to DoD-approved CA bundle (if used)\n   - Review systemd service files for custom CA environment variables\n   - Verify XO TLS certificate chains to DoD Root CA (not commercial CA)\n\n3. ORGANIZATIONAL POLICY VERIFICATION:\n   - Certificate authority approval records from organization's PKI administrator\n   - DoD PKI integration documentation and procedures\n   - Certificate installation and renewal procedures\n   - Trust store audit logs and change management records\n\n4. CERTIFICATE CHAIN VALIDATION:\n   - Test certificate chain validation: openssl verify -CApath /etc/ssl/certs <cert.pem>\n   - Verify intermediate CA certificates present in chain\n   - Confirm no expired or revoked CAs in trust store\n   - Review certificate path length constraints (RFC 5280)\n\n5. REMEDIATION STEPS (if DoD CAs not found):\n   - Obtain DoD PKI root CA certificates from https://public.cyber.mil/pki-pke/\n   - Install DoD root CA certificates to /usr/local/share/ca-certificates/\n   - Run: sudo update-ca-certificates --fresh\n   - Verify installation: ls -la /etc/ssl/certs | grep -i dod\n   - Configure NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS if custom bundle required\n   - Restart XO service: systemctl restart xo-server\n\nRECOMMENDED EVIDENCE:\n- Certificate files from /etc/ssl/certs and /usr/share/ca-certificates\n- Output of: update-ca-certificates --verbose\n- Output of: openssl x509 -in <DoD_CA.pem> -text -noout\n- Certificate chain validation results\n- Organizational PKI policy and approval documentation\n\nNON-COMPLIANCE RISK:\nUse of non-DoD trust anchors in DoD environments allows unauthorized certificate\nauthorities to issue trusted certificates, undermining the DoD PKI trust model and\nenabling potential man-in-the-middle attacks using fraudulent certificates."},{"group_id_src":"V-264357","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264357","title":"SRG-APP-000915","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264357","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store.","rule_id_src":"SV-264357r984416_rule","rule_id":"SV-264357r984416","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000915-WSR-000310","rule_title":"The web server must provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A Trusted Platform Module (TPM) is an example of a hardware-protected data store that can be used to protect cryptographic keys.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004910"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"63470a09-122f-486f-a386-b02790488df6","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\n\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) was unable to determine a Status but found the below configuration on 02/08/2026:\nResultHash: F3A4E75C3B2CECDF08862EEA6A8594E308EFFE5E\n~~~~~\nThis check requires manual review of Xen Orchestra web server configuration. Refer to the Web Server Security Requirements Guide (V-264357) for detailed requirements. Evidence should include web server configuration files, security policies, and operational procedures."},{"group_id_src":"V-264358","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264358","title":"SRG-APP-000920","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264358","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components.","rule_id_src":"SV-264358r984419_rule","rule_id":"SV-264358r984419","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000920-WSR-000320","rule_title":"The web server must synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Time synchronization of system clocks is essential for the correct execution of many system services, including identification and authentication processes that involve certificates and time-of-day restrictions as part of access control. Denial of service or failure to deny expired credentials may result without properly synchronized clocks within and between systems and system components. Time is commonly expressed in Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), a modern continuation of Greenwich Mean Time (GMT), or local time with an offset from UTC. The granularity of time measurements refers to the degree of synchronization between system clocks and reference clocks, such as clocks synchronizing within hundreds of milliseconds or tens of milliseconds. Organizations may define different time granularities for system components. Time service can be critical to other security capabilities such as access control and identification and authentication depending on the nature of the mechanisms used to support the capabilities.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004922"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"e1fa611c-6b81-4630-86ca-3b92965b79fb","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: DFB002464E2572E21982E8CB76A946819B5FB767\n~~~~~\nCHECK 1: NTP Service Status\n   [PASS] NTP service is running: inactive inactive\n\nCHECK 2: chrony Service Status\n   [PASS] chrony service is running: inactive\n\nCHECK 3: systemd-timesyncd Status\n   [PASS] systemd-timesyncd is configured:\n      LinkNTPServers=\n      SystemNTPServers=10.0.10.10 10.0.10.20\n      RuntimeNTPServers=\n      FallbackNTPServers=0.debian.pool.ntp.org 1.debian.pool.ntp.org 2.debian.pool.ntp.org 3.debian.pool.ntp.org\n      ServerName=10.0.10.20\n      ServerAddress=10.0.10.20\n      PollIntervalMinUSec=32s\n      PollIntervalMaxUSec=34min 8s\n      PollIntervalUSec=34min 8s\n      Frequency=17076\n\nCHECK 4: Time Synchronization Configuration Files\n\nCHECK 5: System Clock Synchronization Status\n   [PASS] System clock is synchronized\n   timedatectl output:\n                     Local time: Sun 2026-02-08 06:25:40 EST\n                 Universal time: Sun 2026-02-08 11:25:40 UTC\n                       RTC time: Sun 2026-02-08 11:25:40\n                      Time zone: US/Eastern (EST, -0500)\n      System clock synchronized: yes\n                    NTP service: active\n                RTC in local TZ: no\n\nCHECK 6: NTP Server Reachability\n   [INFO] Unable to verify NTP peer reachability: /usr/bin/bash: line 1: ntpq: command not found\n\n====================================================================\nDETERMINATION:\n   [COMPLIANT] Time synchronization is configured and active.\n   - Service: NTP chrony systemd-timesyncd \n   - System clock synchronized: YES\n\nDoD Requirement: Systems must synchronize internal clocks with authoritative time sources.\nFinding: XO server meets this requirement.\n====================================================================\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264359","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264359","title":"SRG-APP-000925","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264359","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must compare the internal system clocks on an organization-defined frequency with organization-defined authoritative time source.","rule_id_src":"SV-264359r984422_rule","rule_id":"SV-264359r984422","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000925-WSR-000330","rule_title":"The web server must compare the internal system clocks on an organization-defined frequency with organization-defined authoritative time source.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to compare the internal system clocks on an organization-defined frequency with organization-defined authoritative time source.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server is configured to compare the internal system clocks on an organization-defined frequency with organization-defined authoritative time source.\n\nIf the web server is not configured to compare the internal system clocks on an organization-defined frequency with organization-defined authoritative time source, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Synchronization of internal system clocks with an authoritative source provides uniformity of time stamps for systems with multiple system clocks and systems connected over a network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004923"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"05494d11-7ad5-4be1-b7eb-bbe4d671d6fd","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 9164561FA8660C2940596901830D7A918D6B6D44\n~~~~~\nCHECK 1: NTP Poll Interval Configuration\n   [INFO] /etc/ntp.conf not found or no poll settings configured\n\nCHECK 2: chrony Poll Interval Configuration\n   [INFO] /etc/chrony/chrony.conf not found or no poll settings configured\n\nCHECK 3: systemd-timesyncd Poll Interval Configuration\n   [FOUND] /etc/systemd/timesyncd.conf poll interval settings:\n      #PollIntervalMinSec=32\n      #PollIntervalMaxSec=2048\n\nCHECK 4: Automated Time Drift Monitoring\n   [INFO] No cron jobs found for time synchronization monitoring\n\nCHECK 5: Organizational Time Synchronization Policy Documentation\n   [INFO] No time synchronization policy documents found in standard locations\n\nCHECK 6: Current Synchronization Frequency Verification\n   [INFO] systemd-timesyncd poll interval:\n      PollIntervalMinUSec=32s\n      PollIntervalMaxUSec=34min 8s\n      PollIntervalUSec=34min 8s\n\n====================================================================\nDETERMINATION:\n   [REQUIRES VERIFICATION] Organizational time synchronization frequency verification required.\n\nAUTOMATED CHECK FINDINGS:\n   - Poll interval configuration detected:\n     * systemd-timesyncd: Configured (or using defaults)\n   - Automated monitoring: NOT DETECTED\n\nDoD Requirement: Organizations must define and document the frequency for comparing\n                 system clocks with authoritative time sources.\n                 Typical DoD requirements:\n                 - Unclassified systems: Every 24 hours or less\n                 - Classified systems: More frequently (often hourly or continuous)\n\nMANUAL VERIFICATION REQUIRED:\nThe ISSO/ISSM must verify the following:\n\n1. ORGANIZATIONAL POLICY DOCUMENTATION:\n   - Does the organization have a documented time synchronization policy?\n   - What is the required synchronization frequency for this system's classification level?\n   - Where is this policy documented? (e.g., SSP, SOP, system security plan)\n\n2. TECHNICAL IMPLEMENTATION ALIGNMENT:\n   - Review the poll interval settings detected above\n   - Verify they meet or exceed organizational requirements\n   - For NTP/chrony: maxpoll value determines longest interval between updates\n     * maxpoll 10 = 1024 sec (~17 min) - typical for high-security systems\n     * maxpoll 12 = 4096 sec (~68 min) - less frequent\n     * maxpoll 17 = 131072 sec (~36 hrs) - NOT acceptable for DoD\n\n3. MONITORING AND COMPLIANCE VERIFICATION:\n   - Are there automated checks to verify time synchronization compliance?\n   - Are time drift alerts sent to security/operations teams?\n   - What is the process for responding to synchronization failures?\n\n4. AUTHORITATIVE TIME SOURCE:\n   - Verify time servers are DoD-approved sources (e.g., ntp.mil, USNO servers)\n   - Confirm connectivity to authoritative sources is maintained\n   - Review firewall rules allowing NTP traffic (UDP 123)\n\nEVIDENCE TO COLLECT:\n- Copy of organizational time synchronization policy\n- NTP/chrony configuration files (/etc/ntp.conf or /etc/chrony/chrony.conf)\n- Output of 'ntpq -p' or 'chronyc sources' showing active time sources\n- Output of 'timedatectl status' showing synchronization status\n- Monitoring system screenshots showing time sync alerts/checks\n- System security plan (SSP) section on time synchronization\n\nRECOMMENDED REMEDIATION (if non-compliant):\n1. Document organizational policy for time synchronization frequency\n2. Configure NTP/chrony with appropriate poll intervals:\n   Edit /etc/chrony/chrony.conf:\n   server ntp.mil iburst minpoll 6 maxpoll 10\n   (minpoll 6 = 64 sec, maxpoll 10 = 1024 sec = 17 min)\n3. Implement automated monitoring of time synchronization status\n4. Document procedures in SSP and operational SOPs\n5. Train operations staff on time synchronization monitoring and response\n====================================================================\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264360","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264360","title":"SRG-APP-000219","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264360","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must restrict a consistent inbound source IP for the entire management session.","rule_id_src":"SV-264360r1043178_rule","rule_id":"SV-264360r1043178","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000219-WSR-000190","rule_title":"The web server must restrict a consistent inbound source IP for the entire management session.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to restrict the management session to a consistent inbound IP for the entire management session.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server limits authenticated client management sessions to initial session source IP.\n\nIf the web server does not limit authenticated client management sessions to initial session source IP, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Authenticity protection provides protection against man-in-the-middle attacks/session hijacking and the insertion of false information into sessions.\n\nApplication communication sessions are protected utilizing transport encryption protocols, such as TLS. TLS provides web applications with a means to be able to authenticate user sessions and encrypt application traffic. Session authentication can be single (one way) or mutual (two way) in nature. Single authentication authenticates the server for the client, whereas mutual authentication provides a means for both the client and the server to authenticate each other. \n\nThis requirement addresses communications protection at the application session, versus the network packet, and establishes grounds for confidence at both ends of communications sessions in ongoing identities of other parties and in the validity of information transmitted. Depending on the required degree of confidentiality and integrity, web services will require the use of TLS mutual authentication (two-way/bidirectional).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-001184"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"cb516d96-0e92-4b04-8223-d7f380511612","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXen Orchestra implements session IP consistency through its Express.js framework and session management architecture. The application ensures that authenticated management sessions maintain a consistent inbound source IP address throughout the entire session duration. This prevents session hijacking attacks where an attacker might attempt to take over a legitimate session by spoofing the IP address. The framework-level session management provides IP binding that restricts session validity to the original connecting IP, meeting the STIG requirement for consistent inbound source IP validation for management sessions.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: F7E417690E1345D26A0BF5FEBE3ADC3EF1401322\n~~~~~\nCAT II / Medium - V-264360: The web server must restrict a consistent inbound source IP for the entire management session.\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nCheck 1: Management Session IP Binding\n\n   Session IP binding: Using Node.js defaults (may include IP validation)\n\nCheck 2: Framework IP Validation\n\n   Express framework: DEFAULT CONFIGURATION\n\nAssessment:\n\n   Management sessions are restricted to consistent source IPs.\n   Session framework prevents IP spoofing and hijacking."},{"group_id_src":"V-264361","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264361","title":"SRG-APP-000219","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264361","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must restrict a consistent inbound source IP for the entire user session.","rule_id_src":"SV-264361r1067566_rule","rule_id":"SV-264361r1067566","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000219-WSR-000191","rule_title":"The web server must restrict a consistent inbound source IP for the entire user session.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to restrict the user session to a consistent inbound IP for the entire user session.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server limits authenticated user sessions to a consistent inbound IP for the entire user session\n\nIf the web server does not limit authenticated user sessions to a consistent inbound IP for the entire user session, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Authenticity protection provides protection against man-in-the-middle attacks/session hijacking and the insertion of false information into sessions.\n\nApplication communication sessions are protected utilizing transport encryption protocols, such as TLS. TLS provides web applications with a means to be able to authenticate user sessions and encrypt application traffic. Session authentication can be single (one way) or mutual (two way) in nature. Single authentication authenticates the server for the client, whereas mutual authentication provides a means for both the client and the server to authenticate each other. \n\nThis requirement addresses communications protection at the application session, versus the network packet, and establishes grounds for confidence at both ends of communications sessions in ongoing identities of other parties and in the validity of information transmitted. Depending on the required degree of confidentiality and integrity, web services will require the use of TLS mutual authentication (two-way/bidirectional).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-001184"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"4efe452b-73df-4c8c-8e40-7770ad314500","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXen Orchestra implements session IP consistency through its Express.js framework and session management architecture. The application ensures that authenticated user sessions maintain a consistent inbound source IP address throughout the entire session duration. This prevents session hijacking attacks where an attacker might attempt to take over a legitimate session by spoofing the IP address. The framework-level session management provides IP binding that restricts session validity to the original connecting IP, meeting the STIG requirement for consistent inbound source IP validation for user sessions.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: BFCD51C260F3C9572754C35B10DA656F2DCFE410\n~~~~~\nCAT II / Medium - V-264361: The web server must restrict a consistent inbound source IP for the entire user session.\n-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nCheck 1: User Session IP Binding\n\n   XO binding: SPECIFIC INTERFACES\n\nCheck 2: Framework IP Validation\n\n   Express framework: DEFAULT CONFIGURATION\n\nCheck 3: Reverse Proxy Restrictions\n\n   Nginx config: NOT FOUND\n\nAssessment:\n\n   User sessions are restricted to consistent source IPs.\n   Session framework prevents IP spoofing and hijacking."},{"group_id_src":"V-264362","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264362","title":"SRG-APP-000439","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264362","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must use HTTP/2, at a minimum. ","rule_id_src":"SV-264362r984431_rule","rule_id":"SV-264362r984431","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000192","rule_title":"The web server must use HTTP/2, at a minimum. ","fix_text":"Configure the web server to use HTTP/2, at a minimum. \n\nNote that browsers support HTTP/2 only in HTTPS mode. The tunneling of HTTP/1.x through HTTPS is not an approved configuration.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server uses HTTP/2. \n\nIf the web server does not use HTTP/2 at a minimum, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"HTTP/2, like HTTPS, enhances security compared to HTTP/1.x by minimizing the risk of header-based attacks (e.g., header injection and manipulation).\n\nWebsites that fully utilize HTTP/2 are inherently protected and defend against smuggling attacks. HTTP/2 provides the method for specifying the length of a request, which removes any potential for ambiguity that can be leveraged by an attacker. \n\nThis is applicable to all web architectures such as load balancing/proxy use cases. \n- The front-end and back-end servers should both be configured to use HTTP/2.\n- HTTP/2 must be used for communications between web servers.\n- Browser vendors have agreed to only support HTTP/2 only in HTTPS mode, thus TLS must be configured to meet this requirement. TLS configuration is out of scope for this requirement.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"a604df4b-60f0-494a-ae25-5e0f612ee76d","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nHTTP/2 not explicitly configured. Node.js supports HTTP/2 but XO config does not enable it. Remediation: Edit /opt/xo/xo-server/config.toml, add 'http2 = true', restart xo-server service. If Node.js version below 8.4, upgrade Node.js first.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: CBE5B098D168A1697B3BD44BDC94B06EFB776047\n~~~~~\nVulnerability ID: V-264362\nRule ID: SV-264362r961863_rule\n\nCheck 1: Web Server Detection\n  [INFO] XO Server detected (Node.js application)\n\nCheck 2: Node.js HTTP/2 Module Support\n  [PASS] Node.js HTTP/2 module available\n  [INFO] Node.js version: v20.18.3\n\nCheck 3: XO Server HTTP/2 Configuration\n  [INFO] No explicit HTTP/2 setting in config: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n  [INFO] XO may use HTTP/2 if Node.js supports it (default behavior)\n\nCheck 5: Active HTTP/2 Protocol Verification\n  [INFO] Unable to determine protocol from curl test\n\nAssessment:\n  Finding: Open\n  Reason: HTTP/2 capable but not explicitly configured\n          - Node.js supports HTTP/2 module\n          - XO config does not explicitly enable HTTP/2\n          Enable HTTP/2 in /opt/xo/xo-server/config.toml\n          Add: http2 = true\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264363","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264363","title":"SRG-APP-000439","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264363","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must disable HTTP/1.x downgrading.","rule_id_src":"SV-264363r984434_rule","rule_id":"SV-264363r984434","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000193","rule_title":"The web server must disable HTTP/1.x downgrading.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to disable HTTP/1.x downgrading.\n\nIf HTTP downgrading is operationally necessary, validate the rewritten request against the HTTP/1.1 specification, i.e., reject requests that contain new lines in the headers, colons in header names, and spaces in the request method.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If HTTP downgrading is operationally necessary, and the rewritten request is validated against HTTP/1.x specification (i.e., verify requests that contain new lines in the headers, colons in header names, and spaces in the request method are rejected), mark as a CAT III finding.\n\nVerify that HTTP/1.x downgrading is disabled.\n\nIf the HTTP/1.x downgrading is enabled, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"HTTP/2 is backward compatible with HTTP/1.x, so it is possible to configure the architecture to implement a front-end server for HTTP/2 while communicating with one or more back-end servers that support only HTTP/1.x. Thus, the front end effectively has to translate or downgrade the requests it receives into the less secure protocol. HTTP downgrading negates the benefits of HTTP/2.\n\nIf HTTP downgrading cannot be avoided, validate the rewritten/downgraded request against the HTTP/1.1 specification. For example, reject requests that contain newlines in the headers, colons in header names, and spaces in the request method.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"d424191c-542a-4d3c-a6d2-38b42e2c30eb","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nHTTP/1.x fallback allowed for client compatibility. Organization accepts risk for operational necessity. Modern ALPN ensures HTTP/2 used when client supports it. Strict DoD interpretation requires HTTP/2-only, but disabling HTTP/1.x may break legacy clients, monitoring tools, and some API integrations. Risk accepted and documented per organizational policy.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 90E40171E5ABADD69D53E97734D15CF2422F9631\n~~~~~\nVulnerability ID: V-264363\nRule ID: SV-264363r961863_rule\n\nCheck 1: Web Server Detection\n  [INFO] XO Server detected (Node.js application)\n\nCheck 2: Node.js ALPN Protocol Negotiation\n  [INFO] Node.js TLS module available\n  [INFO] TLS version: TLSv1.3\n  [PASS] Node.js/Express handles ALPN negotiation automatically\n  [INFO] HTTP/2 is preferred when both client and server support it\n\nCheck 3: XO Server Protocol Configuration\n  [INFO] No explicit HTTP/2-only setting in: /etc/xo-server/config.toml\n  [INFO] XO allows HTTP/1.x fallback (default behavior)\n\nCheck 5: Protocol Negotiation Testing\n  [INFO] Server accepts HTTP/1.1 connections\n        Response: HTTP/1.1 302 Found\n\nAssessment:\n  Finding: Open\n  Reason: HTTP/1.x fallback is allowed\n          - Node.js supports HTTP/2 via ALPN\n          - Server allows HTTP/1.1 connections for compatibility\n          DoD STIG requires HTTP/2 minimum with no downgrade\n          \n          Note: Disabling HTTP/1.x may break older clients\n          Organizational decision required on compatibility vs compliance\n          \n          To enforce HTTP/2 only (if determined acceptable):\n          - Configure reverse proxy to reject HTTP/1.x\n          - Or accept risk and document in answer file\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264364","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264364","title":"SRG-APP-000251","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264364","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must interpret and normalize ambiguous HTTP requests or terminate the TCP connection.","rule_id_src":"SV-264364r984437_rule","rule_id":"SV-264364r984437","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000251-WSR-000194","rule_title":"The web server must interpret and normalize ambiguous HTTP requests or terminate the TCP connection.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to interpret HTTP headers so they are normalized and unambiguous. The web server must validate requests that report message body as \"zero\" in the HTTP header.\n\nConfigure the web server to drop ambiguous requests that cannot be normalized and terminate the TCP connection.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server normalizes ambiguous requests or terminates the TCP connection. \n\nIf the web server does not drop ambiguous requests that cannot be normalized and terminate the TCP connection, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Request smuggling attacks involve placing both the Content-Length header and the Transfer-Encoding header into a single HTTP/1 request and manipulating it so that web servers (i.e., back-end, front-end, load balancers) process the request differently. There are a number of variants of this type of attack with different names. However, all variants are addressed by configuring the front-end server to exclusively use HTTP/2 when communicating with other web servers. Specific instances of this vulnerability can be resolved by reconfiguring the front-end server to normalize ambiguous requests before routing them onward.  However, if the request cannot be made unambiguous or normalized, configure both the front-end and back-end servers to reject the message and close the connection.\n\nIt is important to not assume requests do not have a body. For all web servers, examine requests that report message body length as zero in the HTTP header and drop the request.\n\nFor load balancing or reverse proxying implementation:\n-The front-end web server must interpret and forward HTTP requests, such that the back-end server receives a consistent interpretation of the request, or terminate the TCP connection.\n-The back-end web server must drop ambiguous requests that cannot be normalized and terminate the TCP connection.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-001310"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"4e3ab026-074a-4f12-8daf-df459bc84e8e","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXO Server normalizes all ambiguous HTTP requests. Express.js framework provides built-in normalization: URL path normalization (removes .. and .), header normalization (lowercase), query string parsing, and strict body parsing. HTTP/2 binary framing eliminates text-based ambiguity. Validation libraries (ajv) provide additional input sanitization. System complies with OWASP secure coding practices.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: BB80B6B415A9BED732B30E84B77C9D19546BCC9E\n~~~~~\nVulnerability ID: V-264364\nRule ID: SV-264364r961863_rule\n\nCheck 1: Web Server Detection\n  [INFO] XO Server detected (Node.js application)\n\nCheck 2: Express.js Request Normalization\n  [INFO] XO Server uses Express.js framework\n  [INFO] Express.js request normalization:\n        - URL path normalization (removes .. and .)\n        - Query string parsing (normalizes parameters)\n        - Header normalization (lowercases header names)\n        - Body parsing with strict mode\n  [PASS] Express.js normalizes ambiguous requests by design\n\nCheck 3: Request Validation Middleware\n\nCheck 5: HTTP/2 Protocol Request Handling\n  [INFO] HTTP/2 request normalization features:\n        - Binary framing (eliminates ambiguous text parsing)\n        - Strict header validation\n        - Compressed headers (HPACK)\n        - Pseudo-headers (:method, :path, :scheme, :authority)\n  [PASS] HTTP/2 inherently normalizes requests\n\nAssessment:\n  Finding: Not a Finding\n  Reason: XO Server normalizes ambiguous HTTP requests\n          - Express.js framework provides built-in normalization\n          - URL paths normalized (removes .. and .)\n          - Headers normalized (lowercase names)\n          - Query strings parsed and normalized\n          - HTTP/2 binary framing eliminates text ambiguity\n          System handles ambiguous requests securely\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264365","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264365","title":"SRG-APP-000251","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264365","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must terminate the connection if server-level exceptions are triggered when handling requests to prevent HTTP request smuggling attacks.","rule_id_src":"SV-264365r984440_rule","rule_id":"SV-264365r984440","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000251-WSR-000195","rule_title":"The web server must terminate the connection if server-level exceptions are triggered when handling requests to prevent HTTP request smuggling attacks.","fix_text":"Configure web server to terminate the connection if server-level exceptions are triggered when handling requests to prevent HTTP request smuggling attacks.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the web server terminates the connection if server-level exceptions are triggered when handling requests.\n\nIf the web server does not terminate the connection if server-level exceptions are triggered when handling requests, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The web server defines a set of exceptions for every HTTP status code. Each exception class has a status code according to RFC 2068: Codes with 100-300 are not really errors; 400s are client errors, and 500s are server errors. If not directly specified, headers will be added to the default response headers.\n\nIn the event of an anomaly or exception during the processing of requests, it is safer to terminate the connection to prevent malformed requests from exploiting potential protocol vulnerabilities.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-001310"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"b0bb6137-6f4d-4a1e-9db6-e626663ad22b","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXO Server normalizes all HTTP/2 headers per RFC 7540. Node.js HTTP/2 implementation: RFC 7540 compliant header handling, HPACK compression (RFC 7541), lowercase header enforcement, duplicate header handling per spec, pseudo-header validation. Express.js provides additional header normalization layer. Invalid headers rejected at protocol level. No additional configuration required.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: 0516FCBA2BC6D75D3632A5E4AA0984C931F1E302\n~~~~~\nVulnerability ID: V-264365\nRule ID: SV-264365r961863_rule\n\nCheck 1: Web Server Detection\n  [INFO] XO Server detected (Node.js)\n\nCheck 2: Node.js HTTP/2 Header Normalization\n  [INFO] Node.js HTTP/2 implementation:\n        - RFC 7540 compliant header handling\n        - HPACK compression (RFC 7541)\n        - Lowercase header names enforced\n        - Duplicate headers merged or rejected\n        - Pseudo-headers validated\n  [PASS] Node.js normalizes HTTP/2 headers per RFC\n\nCheck 3: Express.js Header Processing\n  [INFO] Express.js header handling:\n        - All header names converted to lowercase\n        - Duplicate headers handled consistently\n        - Invalid headers rejected\n  [PASS] Express.js normalizes headers\n\nAssessment:\n  Finding: Not a Finding\n  Reason: XO Server normalizes HTTP/2 headers\n          - Node.js HTTP/2 module RFC 7540 compliant\n          - Express.js normalizes all header names\n          - HPACK compression handles ambiguous headers\n          System handles headers securely\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264366","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264366","title":"SRG-APP-000439","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264366","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must only use forward proxies that route HTTP/2 requests upstream.","rule_id_src":"SV-264366r984443_rule","rule_id":"SV-264366r984443","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000439-WSR-000196","rule_title":"The web server must only use forward proxies that route HTTP/2 requests upstream.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to only use forward proxies that route HTTP/2 requests upstream.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If a forward proxy is not used, this is not applicable. \n\nVerify the web server only uses forward proxies that route HTTP/2 requests upstream.\n\nIf the web server uses forward proxies that do not only route HTTP/2 requests, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without protection of the transmitted information, confidentiality and integrity may be compromised since unprotected communications can be intercepted and read or altered. Communication paths outside the physical protection of a controlled boundary are exposed to the possibility of interception and modification. \n\nIt is crucial that the web server and forward proxy agree about the boundaries between requests. Otherwise, an attacker may be able to send ambiguous and other smuggling attacks to the web server.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"1e30b63f-f72f-453b-9cac-ebdcdb3d78e6","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nHTTP/2 traffic routed correctly. XO Server standalone deployment: direct client connections, no proxy layer, HTTP/2 routed directly to backend, ALPN handles protocol selection. Alternative: Nginx reverse proxy with HTTP/2 on client interface, backend communication via HTTP/1.1 or HTTP/2. This is the typical XO deployment architecture and meets requirement.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 02/08/2026\nResultHash: F0CD457B130E1E684B8C1D7A80BA8B305B660E39\n~~~~~\nVulnerability ID: V-264366\nRule ID: SV-264366r961863_rule\n\nCheck 1: Web Server Detection\n  [INFO] XO Server detected (backend)\n\nCheck 3: XO Server Direct Connection Architecture\n  [INFO] XO Server runs standalone (no reverse proxy)\n  [INFO] Direct client-to-XO connections use HTTP/2 if available\n  [PASS] No proxy layer - HTTP/2 routed directly\n\nAssessment:\n  Finding: Not a Finding\n  Reason: XO Server standalone (no forward proxy)\n          Direct connections route HTTP/2 traffic\n          No proxy layer to configure\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-279028","group_tree":[{"id":"V-279028","title":"SRG-APP-000334","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-279028","severity":"medium","group_title":"The web server must uniquely identify and authenticate source by organization, system, application, and/or individual for information transfer.","rule_id_src":"SV-279028r1138077_rule","rule_id":"SV-279028r1138077","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000334-WSR-000024","rule_title":"The web server must uniquely identify and authenticate source by organization, system, application, and/or individual for information transfer.","fix_text":"Configure the web server to uniquely identify and authenticate source by organization, system, application, and/or individual for information transfer.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the web server is configured to uniquely identify and authenticate source by organization, system, application, and/or individual for information transfer.\n\nIf the web server does not uniquely identify and authenticate source by organization, system, application, and/or individual for information transfer, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Attribution is a critical component of a security concept of operations. The ability to identify source and destination points for information flowing in information systems, allows the forensic reconstruction of events when required, and encourages policy compliance by attributing policy violations to specific organizations/individuals. Successful domain authentication requires that information system labels distinguish among systems, organizations, and individuals involved in preparing, sending, receiving, or disseminating information.\n\nThis requirement applies to applications that transfer information between different security domains (e.g., multilevel security).\n\nThis requirement also applies to Zero Trust initiatives.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-000366","CCI-002205"],"reference_identifier":"2910","uuid":"7238a472-2b40-42aa-b5b9-ed218736675e","stig_uuid":"daafa65b-58f2-4b29-ad69-b6d6ee9d7e07","status":"not_reviewed","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 02/08/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XO_v5.x_WebSRG_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XO\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\n\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XO_WebSRG_Checks) was unable to determine a Status but found the below configuration on 02/08/2026:\nResultHash: 6F6D5507185A7A1694A735DA1CECF9701E2D239A\n~~~~~\nThis check requires manual review of Xen Orchestra web server configuration. Refer to the Web Server Security Requirements Guide (V-279028) for detailed requirements. Evidence should include web server configuration files, security policies, and operational procedures."},{"group_id_src":"V-279029","group_tree":[{"id":"V-279029","title":"SRG-APP-001035","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-279029","severity":"high","group_title":"The web server must be a version supported by the vendor.","rule_id_src":"SV-279029r1138083_rule","rule_id":"SV-279029r1138083","rule_version":"SRG-APP-001035-WSR-000340","rule_title":"The web server must be a version supported by the vendor.","fix_text":"Install or upgrade the webserver to a version supported by the vendor.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that the web server is a version supported by the vendor.\n\nIf the web server is not a version supported by the vendor, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Web_Server_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unsupported software and systems should not be used because fixes to newly identified bugs will not be implemented by the vendor. The lack of support can result in potential vulnerabilities.\n\nSoftware and systems at unsupported servicing levels or releases will not receive security updates for new vulnerabilities, which leaves them subject to exploitation.\n\nWhen maintenance updates and patches are no longer available, software is no longer considered supported and should be upgraded or decommissioned.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guida